Subject: [sfraves] Open Bar @ Mighty all week - Tsunami relief

hey sfravers...here you all thought you were SOOOOO original for coming up 
with the "drink your ass off for tsunami relief" and yet Club Mighty got you 
beat.  it's open bar ALL week you drunkards!!!!


Open bar  MIGHTY (Wednesday Jan. 12th  Sunday Jan. 16th)
Tsunami Relief Week
GIVE IT UP... to get down
5 Different Nights, 5 Different Scenes, 1 Common Goal
Open Bar every Night (check specific night for details)
Get involved early, Stay Involved!
Mighty (119 Utah St. at 15th St.)
San Francisco. 21up with ID
http://www.mighty119.com

--------------------

Wednesday, January 12th (Electronic/Experimental beats & music)
Princess Frillypants & Anon Salon present WISHING WELL
With live performances by:
The Evolution control committee, Gooferman, Chromelodeon
and more amazing acts
Open bar 9pm  10pm

Thursday, January 13th (House,and Funk and )
Give it up to get down on the house vibe. Pink Mammoth, Lo-Rise Recordings, 
The Fool, Aranji, and JZ of Red Melon
Are all giving it up tonite till the wee hours.
open bar 9pm  11pm

Friday, January 14th  Friends and Familly of the Scos Underground Hip Hop,
Turntabelism and Drum & Bass Community come togather on one special night 
for one great cause.
 Compression
 Flavor Group
 Future Primitive Sound
 Groundscore
 Just One Entertainment
 Phuturo
 Sleevless
OPEN BAR FROM 9-11PM


Saturday, January 15th (Breaks and Funky World Beats)
DJ Laird presents Get YER Freak on! With: Laird & Adnan (Lush), J-Boogie (OM 
Records), Smoove (Space Cowboys) Goldilox (Brass Tax), Cheb-I-Sabbah and 
More
open bar 10pm  12pm

Sunday, January 16th (R&B, Funk, Soul, and Hip Hop)
End your weekend shakin your ass for a good cause with DJs:
Sake One, D Sharp, MR. E, Malachi, Shania D, Ren the Vinyl Archeologist, and 
DJ Lex. Dance performances by: Soul Sector, Head Hunters, & Machine Gone 
Funk
open bar 9pm  11pm
 Proceeds go to American Red Cross Tsunami Disaster relief 
go to www.mighty119.com for more details

--------------------------
< Brandon / DJ Bam >

DJ Bam - serving breaks and beats
http://www.invibe.com/bam

December 4th:  Electroseekry
December 11th:  Private Party at Dragon Bar
January 29th:  Furious II

Thats right folks, Audience is back for the new year. 
With a new venue, new dj's, on a new soundsystem! 
Find yourself needing a little umph in your housemusic? 
Find yourself heading to the city for all your housemusic needs? 

We're about to change all that! 

Catch all your favorite dj's down here in the southbay for free! 
This wednesday (our re-opening night) you can catch 

DjTracy (SF endup www.djtracy.com) 

with your residents Gabriel Black and Dj Leks 
bumpin their delectable beats thru crystal clear mackie sound. 
This is House Music the way it was meant to be heard and felt. 
Come support underground Housemusic in the southbay! 
We hope to see you on the dancefloor! 
Audience can be found at Scruffy Murphy's 
187 Murphy Ave in downtown Sunnyvale 



Go To www.GabrielBlack.net for streaming and downloadable dj sets of Deep and Funky Tech-House Madness! 
Check out http://www.retroactivefunk.djcentral.com for self produced tracks and more mixes.
Visit my label www.Sierrarecordings.com
001 Gabriel Black with Jay Tripwire and JJVaas Remixs (out now) 
002 JJVaas with EBE and Gabriel Black remixs (who knows when?)
And vote for me at the dj list! http://www.thedjlist.com/djs/GABRIEL_BLACK/
I've started renting out my Mackie Rig for small/medium sized rooms, hit me up!

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright:  Introduction

Stage Left of Copyright: 
Audio Sampling Embraces the Public Domain

Peter Alden Sandifer
San Francisco State University
Broadcast and Electronic Communication Arts
masters thesis draft


I.  Introduction:  Audio Sampling 

     Musicians, DJs, and audiophiles record samples
from any available media  television, films, radio,
records, tapes, speeches, CD, DVD, and the airwaves. 
Car stereos around the world share the       (   (
((often annoying))  ) )   )    results of plundered
samples. Hip-hop, R&B, electronica, and Top 40 music
are a few popular genres that have welcomed sampling. 


     The sample itself is a section of pre-recorded
audio (such as a jazz horn riff, a drum section, or a
recorded voice) captured from one recording and reused
as a part of a new recording.  To turn an audio sample
into a usable musical ingredient, a common technique
is to sequence a loop.   
 
     Looping involves digitally or manually repeating
a sample in accurate musical time, tempo and key to
fit the design of the new song.  Digitally, a sample
can be looped with software or electronic sampling
hardware.  Manually, a live DJ uses records and
turntables (or other audio devices), cueing and
releasing the recorded sample at a musically
appropriate time. 

     This unconventional approach to composing music
arrived in Americas consciousness as a footnote to
rap music in the 1970s, bringing with it a host of
problems concerning artistic legitimacy, copyright law
and financial compensation.

     This paper includes some conjecture and rhetoric
about the nature of ownership and the creative spirit,
but pragmatics led me in search of historical roots
that would provide a sort of cultural validity for an
artistic experimentation that is too often dismissed
as illegitimate.  It is a compelling idea that a
generation of artists, armed with technology, would
seek to appropriate the sounds of their musical
forebearsas if by instinctand even in violation of
the law.

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright:  U.S. Copyright Law

Part I was a no-brainer for you techno geeks, so
here's part II.    Tomorrow:  Geri Dahl convinces Josh
Davis that a psychiatrist can cure his sampling habit.
....... .   .     .    .      .
Stage Left of Copyright: 
Audio Sampling Embraces the Public Domain

Peter Alden Sandifer
masters thesis draft


II.  Audio Sampling and U.S. Copyright Law
(see United States Copyright Act Section 107, below.)

     Copyright law was originally developed in
sixteenth century England as a tool of censorship
under Queen Mary Tudor (Vaidhyanathan, p. 37), but its
current directive in the United States is considerably
more honorable:  to encourage artists and creators to
continue at their craft with peace of mind (Epstein,
p.159) that their original ideas are protected from
thieves and plagiarists.  

     Still, the United States Copyright Act leaves
much to be interpreted by the music industry and the
judicial system when it comes to the creative re-use
of recorded music.  Ken Anderson and Eric Greenspan,
attorneys who separately represent a variety of rap
acts inclined to use samples, both contend that U.S.
copyright laws did not anticipate the innovation of
sampling technologies and art forms, and are therefore
unqualified to adequately serve as a judicial beacon
in current legal cases  (Marcus, p. 209).

     Recently, U.S courts have delivered conflicting
judgments about what constitutes an illegal sample. 
In 2002, a lower court determined that rap band NWAs
sample of a George Clinton riff did not rise to the
level of legally recognizable appropriation 
(Reynolds), applying a familiar de minimis (1) 
ruling:  If audiences arent likely to be confused by
the re-use, then the sample is legally clear.   

     In September 2004, that ruling was overturned by
the 6th District Federal Appeals Court, whose judges
made a blanket decree: Get a license, or do not
sample, regardless of the length or acoustic
alterations made to the borrowed audio (Rosinski). 
However, two months later, the 9th District Federal
Appeals Court reaffirmed its 2003 de minimis ruling in
favor of a Beastie Boys brief sample of a James
Newton flute recording:  that the borrowed sample was
"so meager and fragmentary that the average audience
would not recognize the appropriation" (Frederikse).

     Records store owner Robert Mooney voiced the
paradox that exists in U.S. copyright law, by
comparing sampling to scholarly research
[paraphrased]:  "You can go to the library and Xerox a
page of a book, but if you Xeroxed the whole book,
then you're breaking the law.  Theres supposed to be
room for you to cite a sentence in your paper or
book.  (Reynolds.)


1. De minimis: So minor as to be disregarded.

2. a determination of whether [a sample] is infringing
will typically focus on the issue of substantial
similarity (Korn, p. 222).


United States Copyright Act Section 107-- Limitations
on Exclusive Rights:  Fair Use.  (Negativland, p. i)

Notwithstanding the provisions of sections 106 and
106A, the fair use of copyrighted work, including such
use by reproduction for purposes such as criticism,
comment, news reporting, teachingscholarship or
research, is not an infringement of copyright.  In
determining whether the use made of a work in any
particular case is a fair use the factors to be
considered shall
include

1. the purpose and character of the use, including
whether such use is of a commercial nature or is for
nonprofit educational purposes;
2. the nature of the copyrighted work;
3. the amount and substantiality of the portion used
in relation 
to the copyrighted work as a whole; and
4. the effect of the use upon the potential market for
or value 
of the copyrighted work.

and decided a drinking competition is the stupidest
idea I've agreed to in a long time.

idiots, and brought together a mixing board, a 303,
andy's guitar, some bongos, congas, harmonicas,
trumpets, guitar pedals, samplers and microphones and
made a bunch of stupid idiot music for like an
afternoon and a night?   the DJs can sit in the corner
and sulk, or pick up an instrument and act stupid.

processor, etc.

Osby could pass around the hat to collect donations
for some random group of unlucky bastards.   doesn't
need to be tsunami relief,  we could keep it local.

it seems a bit more creative than competitive
drinking.  anybody game?   who's got a big enough
living room?

for some random group of unlucky bastards. doesn't

it seems a bit more creative than competitive
drinking. anybody game? who's got a big enough
living room?

--=====================_2140828==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Get YER Freak on!
Saturday January 15, 2005
Mighty 119 Utah
10pm - 5am, $10
OPEN BAR from 10-12!
Benefit to assist the survivors of the Tsunami 100% of Proceeds go to the 
Red Cross and OXFAM

Loving DJs donating their time:
Laird- LUSH, Get YER Freak on!
J-Boogie - OM Records
Smoove - Space Cowboys
Goldilox - Brass Tax
Adnan - LUSH
+ very special surprise guest

Join us for an evening of celebration helping those in a time of need. The 
world's heart and compassion go forth and we all do what we can.

Please help us raise funds for donation to the International Federation of 
Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies. All gross proceeds will be donated 
directly to the charities.

The International Federation is well placed to assist victims of disasters 
thanks to its network of National Societies. Almost every country in the 
world has a Red Cross or Red Crescent society, each with branches and 
trained volunteers at community level. Bringing emergency relief to 
refugees and victims of poverty and disasters has been a key activity of 
the International Federation and its member Red Cross and Red Crescent 
Societies for more than 80 years. Our collective has chosen the IFRC due to 
its reach on an international and community level, access to resources and 
record for putting forth 91% of funding directly toward program activity.

Oxfam's Purpose
Oxfam works with others to overcome poverty and suffering.

Oxfam's Beliefs
* The lives of all human beings are of equal value.

* In a world rich in resources, poverty is an injustice which must be 
overcome.

* Poverty makes people more vulnerable to conflict and natural calamity; 
much of this suffering can be prevented, and must be relieved.

* People's vulnerability to poverty and suffering is increased by unequal 
power relations based on, for example, gender, race, class, caste and 
disability; women, who make up a majority of the world's poor, are 
especially disadvantaged.

* Working together we can build a just and safer world, in which people 
take control over their own lives and enjoy their basic rights.

* To overcome poverty and suffering involves changing unjust policies and 
practices, nationally and internationally, as well as working closely with 
people in poverty.

Oxfam's Identity
* Oxfam works internationally as part of a world-wide movement to build a 
just and safer world.

* Oxfam is an independent British organisation, registered as a charity, 
affiliated to Oxfam International, with partners, volunteers, supporters, 
and staff of many nationalities.

* Oxfam is accountable both to those who support it and to those whom it 
seeks to benefit by its efforts.
Oxfam's Culture

Reflects a passionate commitment to overcoming the injustice of poverty and 
suffering. We seek to be:

* Making a difference
* Innovative
* Collaborative
* Accountable
* Cost-effective
more info: www.oxfam.org





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright: Negativland, U2 & The Postmodern Defense

Stage Left of Copyright: 
Audio Sampling Embraces the Public Domain
Peter Alden Sandifer
master's thesis draft


III.  History and Cultural Significance of Audio
Sampling 

     A. Negativland and the Postmodern Defense

     To some musicians and critics, sampling and
reusing copyrighted audio is not just a violation of
federal law, but a more damning accusation involving
unimaginative artists who cheat the creative process
by stealing from others for their own commercial
gain (Adams & McKibbins, p. 158). 

     To others, it is an action of artistic homage
(Theberge, p. 205), or parody, or critical commentary,
or deconstructive analysis.  "Re-contextualization" is
how the sample-happy band Negativland defends the
thousands of plundered samples they loop, mix, record
and broadcast in violation of the law.   
Negativlands artistic intent is to use captured
fragments to create something entirely newa
psychological impact based on a new juxtaposition of
diverse elements, ripped from their usual context,
chewed up and spit out as a new form of hearing the
world around us (Negativland, p. 121).

     Postmodernism  a common alibi for unusual
behavior -- is frequently employed to justify
sampling, with the argument that this
re-interpretation of previously documented media in a
novel setting (Marcus, p. 206) bears the same
legitimacy and cultural value as Andy Warhols
paintings of Campbells Soup cans. 

     Part of the movement against sampling seems to be
based on a proud Western insistence on originality,
coupled with an embarrassed denial of influence from
others.  Another obvious motivation is financial,
particularly when record labels pounce.  Folklore and
documented cases indicate that it is often record
labels (the custodians of musicians intellectual
property) who most avidly seek compensation from
copyright violators.  

     For example, when Negativland was sued for
releasing a provocative record called "U2" that
featured samples and parodies of that eponymous Irish
rock group, the band U2 apparently had no objection to
the satirical recording (Fax from Brian Eno, U2s
producer, p. 31).  Rather, it was U2s
representatives, Island Records and Warner-Chappel,
who sought to protect the bands clean-cut image
from Negativlands deceptive use of the U2 name on
the parody album cover (Excerpts from the
Island/Warner-Chappell lawsuit, p. 15). 

     Ironically, there is nothing original or
inherently private about U2 -- the Irish rockers had
lifted their name from the U-2 spy plane of the Cold
War era.  Ironically again, Negativland included a
picture of that spy plane on the cover of their U2
album, a detail which logically should have
invalidated the plaintiffs argument about dominion
over the word U2.  (Negativland, p. i- v).  
Representatives of U2 won possession of Negativlands
master tapes for the parody album, but three years
later agreed to return the reels to the tenacious
audio saboteurs on the condition that you stop
writing to us  (Negativland, p. 178).  

     As instigators and nuisance to the establishment
of creative ownership, Negativland waged an exhausting
and expensive war on the major labels.  Admittedly,
this is a group of artists who, this writer witnessed
at a San Francisco concert, hacked into local cable
lines and broadcast their performance through the
Playboy Channels audio signaljust for kicks.  And
admittedly, Negativland gained more recognition from
the U2 lawsuits than they would have from their U2
album alone.  But Negativland maintains that its
motivations are to expose the problems of the
individual as a passive spectator to popular media; to
challenge our modern surrender of the age-old concept
of shared culture[to] private owners (Negativland,
p. 190).


tomorrow--    Shared Culture:  From West Africa to the
Plantations

It doesn't "work with a tb303" but it's a series of modifications done by 
some guy in australia to your tb303.  You can get more information here: 
http://www.firstpr.com.au/rwi/dfish/

I know it adds MIDI to it so you can use modern day sequencers on it (well 
the future retro revolution can still do cv/gate controlling ;))

Down side is you have to mail your 303 to some dude in a different 
hemisphere.

-maz

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: devilfish

Mmmm... devilfish..  The devilfish I used to use was a TB-303 that was
sent to Australia to be modded by the guy who did them.  It added a big
red button that basically kicked everything into overdrive on the box. 
There were also a couple of non-standard knobs added to it.  I loved that
lil machine.

And when you usually see something labeled 303 in the electronic music
world, I'd say its 99.9% in reference to the TB-303.  And as an aside, I
don't think software can properly replicate a TB-303 and its
inconsistencies, especially while running off low batteries.


> Has anyone heard of Devilfish? Something about how it works with a tb303?

> opium poppies?
>
> Appreciate any info, couldn't think of a better place to ask.
>
> Thanks,

On Tue, 11 Jan 2005, CHUCK G wrote:

-&e->Has anyone heard of Devilfish? Something about how it works with a
-&e->tb303? Is that the same 303 thing I see in Reason, or are we talking
-&e->apples & opium poppies?

Apple and Opium Poppies...

Devilfish:
http://www.firstpr.com.au/rwi/dfish/
Real hardware mod to a real world tb-303.

The 303 in rebirth is a software emulation of an unmodified tb-303 in
interface and somewhat in sound (rebirth is a more primitive earlier
product from Propellorheadz with fixed routing and only a pair of 303's, a
808 and 909 modeled into it).  Reason contains no 303-style synth, but
it's analog synth can do a decent job at acidlines.

Sorta.  I need another fake acidline like I need another asshole.
andyw

AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote:

On Tue, 11 Jan 2005, CHUCK G wrote:

-&e->Has anyone heard of Devilfish? Something about how it works with a
-&e->tb303? Is that the same 303 thing I see in Reason, or are we talking
-&e->apples & opium poppies?

Apple and Opium Poppies...

Devilfish:
http://www.firstpr.com.au/rwi/dfish/
Real hardware mod to a real world tb-303.

The 303 in rebirth is a software emulation of an unmodified tb-303 in
interface and somewhat in sound (rebirth is a more primitive earlier
product from Propellorheadz with fixed routing and only a pair of 303's, a
808 and 909 modeled into it). Reason contains no 303-style synth, but
it's analog synth can do a decent job at acidlines.

Sorta. I need another fake acidline like I need another asshole.
andyw

Oh I know that place.  I'm sort of obsessed with the
number 23.  I'll post my 23 links sometime.

I bought the track at BPM on Victor's recommendation. 
My wife gets irritated everytime I take it out.  But I
like it, probably in part becasue it irritates people,
but also because I have this sort of vivid vision of
playing this record at a party I went to once upon a
time.

My wife and I were staying in Big Sur, and we went to
this benefit party for some guy that was paralyzed
after a biking accident.  We heard about it from some
locals that we knew from when we got married there.

The party was rocking in this little 2 room house
which was almost a shed really. Outside there was BBQ,
corn, beer, bikers, and some yelling and hollarin'.

The DJ was playing some house and hip-hop and it was
all OK.  After a while the DJ started playing like,
well, some sort of hoe-down banjo music that was not
good.  We lost our dancing motivation and were
considering getting more beverages when someone
released an incredibly smelly fart completely clearing
the place.  

This record was meant to be played at that party.  But
you'll have to trust me on that I suppose ;)

Regards,

Peter

--0-1314511912-1105483626=:6152
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii

01/11/05 Hope I referenced this correctly:
 
>Apple to make $499 Mac, $99 iPod 
Company to sell stripped down computer to broaden appeal, saw iPod 
sales hit 4.5 million.
January 11, 2005: 3:08 PM EST "
 
http://money.cnn.com/2005/01/11/technology/apple.reut/index.htm?cnn=yes
 

SAN FRANCISCO (Reuters) - Apple Computer Inc. Tuesday said it would 
begin selling a stripped-down Macintosh computer without monitor, keyboard 
or mouse for $499 and new iPod digital music players costing as little 
as $99. 

Chief Executive Steve Jobs, announcing the new products at the MacWorld 
exposition, also said that Apple had sold 4.5 million units of its 
blockbuster iPod in the 2004 holiday quarter. 

Apple shares fell nearly 4 percent, as some suggested that the news had 
been priced into the stock, thanks to widespread rumors ahead of the 
show. 

"There was so much expectation built in for the stock ... I think that 
the expectations were about as high as they could get for it," said 
Marc Pado, U.S. market strategist at Cantor Fitzgerald & Co. "I think it 
was a case of buy on the rumor and sell on the news." 

The iPod sales figure was also slightly below some Wall Street 
forecasts. Banc of America Securities had predicted iPod sales of 4.6 million 
units in a note Tuesday. Prudential had predicted 4.25 million units. 

Apple said the new "iPod shuffle" was smaller and lighter than a pack 
of gum and would come in 512 megabyte ($99) and 1 gigabyte ($149) 
capacities. The smaller one would hold about 120 songs, Jobs said. 

The new iPod falls into a category of music players that use "flash 
memory," like that found in digital cameras and some portable disk drives, 
rather than hard drives like the other iPod models. 

"We'd like to go after the remaining mainstream flash market," Jobs 
said, noting that the flash memory-based digital player market is 
currently highly fragmented. "The products are all pretty much the same." 

He also claimed the iPod holds a 65 percent share of the entire market 
for portable digital music players, up from only 31 percent a year 
earlier. 

Apple said a number of car companies like Mercedes-Benz USA, Volvo, 
Nissan and Ferrari were working to integrate the iPod line into their car 
stereo systems. 

The "Mac mini" will come in $499 and $599 models. Weighing in at less 
than 3 pounds and 2 inches tall, the box has digital media ports that 
let it connect to televisions as well as traditional PC monitors. 

Jobs' announcements were awaited eagerly by the Mac faithful worldwide, 
though they offered no real surprises, unlike in previous years. The 
new iPod and the smaller Mac were telegraphed by the many online Mac 
rumor sites in recent weeks, some of which are being sued by Apple for 
those leaks. 

Shares of Apple (Research) were off $2.50, or 3.7 percent at $66.44 in 
active afternoon trade on Nasdaq.  





--0-1314511912-1105483626=:6152--

ATI Remote Wonder. Works on both platforms. Make sure you get Bluetooth. 
Like Brandon said you can use a BT phone to control it, but it's kinda 
janky. Wireless BT keyboard and mouse is a good idea.

I still say this thing is stupid until they release a media kit for it so 
you can have a *built in* TV tuner and software that allows it to become a 
DVR as well.

I know if I bought one what I'd do with it. Rip it open, figure out how much 
power it requires, then integrate it into a car. Add a GPS antenna and 
software. Put an iPod dock up front. Write software for a 7" high resolution 
touch screen up front. Route all audio from the mac through an Alpine head 
unit (time correction, parametric eq, and electronic crossover built in). A 
cheap as fuck way to put a machine in your car without doing ghetto Clarion 
crap or hacking a laptop apart. Yeah people have stuck PC's in stupid cases 
in cars, but fuck that. Imagine how nice this would look at the end of a 
build with that mac in the rear of the bling bling SUV shit that every bitch 
has to have these days?

But that's just what I would do. It's a 12" PB in a box.

:: r ::

Subject: [sfraves] Sold to the man with red horns and pitchfork

   If i hadnt already sold my soul to the devil for that damn taco,
I'd so sell it for the gift of a catchy tune.  Dont you hate those
songs that just embed themselves in your brain never to leave.  All it
takes it the shortest little snippit of the song to enter your ear
canal and the rest of the day you cant seem to shake it out.  I woke
up this morning and heard like a half second of that stupid Destiny's
Child song "Lose my breath" or whatever the funk it's called.  GOD I
HATE THAT SONG!!!!  I'm sorry but people may bitch about house/techno
(electronic music in general) is too repeatative and they can't stand
it...but there's those people that bitch about that and still listen
to crap like Destiny's Child.  That song is so freakin repeatative,
they say the same thing over and over and over.  And it wont ever
leave my head.  I know today will be a  horrible day just cause that
was what i woke up to.  I'd rather roll out of bed onto a floor full
of thumb tacks then wake up to that song.  The radio station must have
gotten bumped somehow cause i always keep it on a classic rock
station,  I hate radio, the only decent way to listen to radio is with
classic rock at least there's like an 80% chance of hearing a good
song, or at least a tolerable song.  There's a girl here at work who
listens to that song like 5 times a dat, minimum.  That song make me
feel so violent, and not in a good way like Ministry does.  I'd say we
should find a way to assasinate them, but i think that would only
encourage the radio stations to play it more in honor of them and
their crappy music.

    Why do radio statiosn have to overplay everything, it doesnt make
any sence to me.  Am i the only person who gets tired of hearing the
same song more than once or twice in a day?  I dont think i am. 
there's gotta be more out there.  So why do they do it?  I mean great
radio station gets a couple of singles before the albums release,
cool, play them get people all ready to get the album, but once the
albums out, play some of the other songs off of it.  At least change
it up a little bit, why over play the same 2 freakin songs.  It just
doesnt click in my head.  Is the general populace just so dumb that
they forget they heard that song 5 times already today?  So many bands
have sold their souls for the knack of a catchy tune.

   Although not all bands sell their souls for horribly bad catchy
songs, there are a few out there that sell their soul for awesomly
good catchy songs.  One of the bands i can think of that sold their
soul for good is Hall and Oates.  Their music is so catchy it gets
stuck in your head, but in such a good way it brings a smile to your
face and you dont want it to ever leave.  I'm sure Stickman and AndyW
are onboard with me on this one.

Destiny's Child = Evil
Hall & Oates = God Like
-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

"no, i think they can see that part too. that is why i like to do it."
 
"can you give me an example?"
 
"yes, i like to get really upset, because i have a long skinny neck and bulging eyes, but then i act like there is something wrong with the person i am with and that it has nothing to do with my long skinny neck and bulging eyes, and after a while, i think that maybe they might think they have a long skinny neck and bulging eyes, but usually, they have eyes that stay in the sockets and a neck with a normal width, and they really know it." :)

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright: West Africa to the Plantations

Stage Left of Copyright: Audio 
Sampling Embraces the Public Domain
Peter Alden Sandifer
master's thesis draft


Shared Culture:  From West Africa to the Plantations

     If shared culture, as Negativland says, is at the
heart of the sampling defense, then it is crucial to
look at the history of sampling in terms of not just
technology, but of tradition and cultural
significance.  The story of sampling and how it came
to be complicates any quick assumptions about blatant
theft.

     It is an interesting historical fact that
sampling can be traced to slave traditions in the
United States and the Caribbean, by way of the regions
of West Africa from which slaves were taken.  Digital
sampling is a mere technological upgrade of traditions
belonging to a culture and a continent beyond the
understanding of the U.S. Supreme Court.

     Differing from the linear path of intellect
that dominates European-America, West African culture
tends to view the world from a circular perspective,
in homage to creative voices of the past as well as to
a community of shared consciousness. (Vaidhyanathan,
p. 125).    

     Long before the advent of electronic samplers,
African-American artists of blues, jazz, gospel, and
oral tradition treated songs as communal property: 
melodies, guitar riffs, and lyrics are in a constant
cycle of being borrowed, altered, and re-used (Jones,
p. 28). To the Black conscience, ownership of ideas
was as alien as the promise of owning forty acres and
a mule (2).

     It wasnt until the commodification of rap music
and the subsequent sampling of recorded music in the
1980s that copyright became an issue of public debate.
(Jones, p. 92).  Its ironic to consider that liberal
African-American ownership rules invited the lucrative
mimicry of superstars like Elvis Presley, while half a
century later, American copyright law would dampen
those same shared-culture ideals that spawned music
sampling.


2.   Forty acres and a mule: General Shermans
unfulfilled promise to freed slaves at the end of the
Civil War (Special Field Order #15).

tomorrow:  From Jamaica to the Bronx

(c) 2004 peter alden sandifer

?uestlove (Ahmir Khalib Thompson) became friends at the Philadelphia High 
School for Creative Performing Arts. Since the duo had no money for the DJ 
essentials -- two turntables and a microphone, plus a mixer and plenty of 
vinyl -- they recreated classic hip-hop tracks with ?uestlove's drum kit 
backing Black Thought's rhymes.

4. Reduce; degrade: declass.
5. Derived from: deverbative.


terminator ( P ) Pronunciation Key (trm-ntr)
n.

policies.

regions of the disk of the moon or an inner planet.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR My new media center

If you're into DIY projects, I heard MythTVFrontend runs smoothly on
OS X. Just slap together a Linux MythTV backend server and u can use
your spanking new Mac Mini to watch time-shifted TV shows.

The new Hauppauag PVR 150 card (MPEG2 TV reocrding card) can be had
for about $65. Add 5 of these to your MythTV server and u can record 5
shows at once.  It beats any WinXP MCE or Tivo.

Personally I think Apple will release a PVR soon. And they'll release
a PVR before they'll ever release a video iPod.

For a mac remote, try the Keyspan Digital Media Remote:

http://www.keyspan.com/products/usb/remote/

The link maz quoted was the Express Remote, it only works with the
Airport Express. This one works with Macs.

I have a friend who has this remote and seems to like it. 

- Jeff

listen to the radio.  Got 3 people here at work in my office that
listen to radio.  And to top it all off my Girlfriend listens to the
radio.  So i'm submersed in it when i dont want to be.  I noticed a
couple of weekend back when i was at my gf's house for the weekend,
that in the entire 4 day weekend that i had, i heard 2 songs i liked. 
The Last 30 seconds of No Sleep till Brooklyn and the first 30 seconds
of Rapper delight.  in 4 days of listening to the radio, 1 minute of
good music.  how whack is that?  Kinda sucks too cause the gf says she
likes hard angry music.  But what is hard and angry to her?  Linkin
Park...and Papa Roach, and those poorly pathetic covers that marilyn
manson does.  I play some hard shit for her like ministry and
metallica and old Manson and she's all that's too hard and fast..blah
blah blah.  I dont get it, linkin park is so far from being a hard
band...they're a fuckin joke, same with papa roach.  A bunch of whiney
ass bitches whining about how they're mom didnt hug them enough when
they were kids and shit.  It's crap.

I found this at a cool website-- "Stuffo: How Stuff
Works."    
http://stuffo.howstuffworks.com/music-royalties7.htm

How Music Royalties Work
by Lee Ann Obringer

Performance Royalties
How are performance royalties tracked and calculated?
Remember that performance royalties are tracked and
paid out by the performance rights organizations like
ASCAP, BMI, and SESAC. 

The royalty trail begins when the song is registered
with one of the three performing rights organizations
mentioned above. Once a song is registered, it becomes
part of that PRO's collection and is available to all
of its users. Most of those users have a "blanket
license" to use any or all of the PRO's music, however
some users license on a per program basis and only pay
for the music they actually use. (This is good for
users who don't use that much music.) The PROs deduct
money for their operating expenses and the rest goes
to the songwriters and publishers.

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright: Jamaica to the Bronx

Stage Left of Copyright: Audio 
Sampling Embraces the Public Domain
Peter Alden Sandifer
master's thesis draft


The Carribbean

     During the 1960s and 70s, the creative re-use of
recorded music developed in Jamaica and neighboring
islands of the Caribbean-- areas also inhabited by the
descendants of West African slaves.  Here, the
legendary Jamaican sound system --speakers, amplifier,
record turntables and a mixing console-- became tools
for musicians often a few dollars shy of buying
instruments.  
     
     Musical sections were cued on record players by a
DJ and released at the proper time, as an instrumental
bed over which vocalists sang.  This
re-contextualization of existing records is called
version [vair-shen] in Jamaican dialect.  The use of
instrumental sections for singing gave birth to a
reggae offshoot called dub (Connell and Gibson, p.
183).

     The Jamaican /version/ relates aesthetically to
the rules of jazz and blues in the United States,
which inherently (as a part of the social fabric)
involved the sharing and repetition of ideas, musical
riffs, and vocal toasts.  Chords, chants, and lyrics
volleyed back and forth as a cultural torch, a common
property of a people who owned little else but memory
of tradition.


To the Bronx

      When the ease of global transportation allowed a
wider migration from the Caribbean to the U.S. in the
1970s, Jamaicas seminal style of re-using recorded
music migrated to New Yorks Bronx.  

    In the ghetto, disk jockey legends in the making
like Kool Herc, Grandmaster Flash, and Afrika Bambaata
(Conell & Gibson, p. 182) selected only the funkiest
sections of disco and rock records the breaks
sometimes replaying those musical parts by alternating
duplicate copies of the same record, and sometimes by
just slamming the volume faders to the break of a new
song.  

     This style of programming the musical breaks
eventually became known as break beat music, and
along with it came the familiar terms break dance, 
b-boy and b-girl.  The break beat would become the
backbone of rap music, and later a genre of its own.

     It was the rhythmnot the writtenthat kept
African culture alive and progressing in European
colonies unable to reconcile the racist divide.  It is
somewhere here, an indefinable space straddling
continents and centuries, where I believe the communal
(yet displaced) cultures of West Africa found the
technology to preserve records of the past, and the
artistic curiosity to celebrate it.  

    That moment of discovery loops back to the
plantation fields of the Caribbean and Americas
south, where rhythm and lyrical truths took place of
the written word.  That innocent, artistic desire to
merge past recordings to tell todays stories is
fitting to the observation of Alan Korn, that Edisons
phonograph was a device intended for the preservation
of sound rather than for its mass republication
(Korn, p. 222).--


tomorrow -  White Label Records:  Sampling Under the
Radar

(c) 2004 peter sandifer

drinking, fungin, huff'n (but not roger'n), giggling like a moron under a
blanket as the sun came up and telling 12 year old girls they can't get in

happened.  Just rich... for the record, my favorite DJ name on that flyer
was "Mike'N'Ike-ron" for Micron.  :P

and it was mutual respect... his 'Purple Drums' tape was a damn good
listen as well).  Of course, maybe things have changed too much... I think
peak slot at permitted parties these days is like 9-9:50pm.

Subject: [sfraves] Factory Records Founder Starts New U.K. Label

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Factory Records Founder Starts New U.K. Label

1 hour, 24 minutes ago
  <http://us.rd.yahoo.com/dailynews/addtomy/*http://add.my.yahoo.com/content?id=6158&.src=yn&.done=http%3a//news.yahoo.com/news%3ftmpl=story%26cid=769%26e=3%26u=/nm/20050114/music_nm/music_factory_dc>Entertainment 
- Reuters

By Chris Morris

LOS ANGELES (Hollywood Reporter) - British music entrepreneur Tony Wilson, 
whose noted and notorious post-punk indie label Factory Records was the 
subject of the 2002 feature "24 Hour Party People," has started up a new 
imprint, F4 Records.

Based in Manchester, England, F4 is launching with the Jan. 31 release of 
"Where We Live," a single by the local hip-hop/garage collective Raw-T. An 
album from the group, "Realize and Witness," will be issued in March. 
Pinnacle is distributing F4 in the United Kingdom.

F4 is also mounting a download site with Pinnacle, with initial Web-only 
offerings by guitarist Vini Reilly (of the original Factory group the 
Durutti Column) and the Manchester group Young Offenders Institute.

Wilson said of his new enterprise, "This is a confession of utter failure. 
I have completely failed to either grow up or calm down."

A former host of Granada TV's alternative music show "So It Goes," Wilson 
founded Factory Records in 1979 after running a like-named Manchester club. 
Among the label's first signings was Joy Division; the gloomy quartet 
established the company. New Order, a dance-oriented unit formed by the 
surviving members of Joy Division after the 1980 suicide of singer Ian 
Curtis, became Factory's best-selling band.

In 1982, Wilson opened the Manchester club the Hacienda, which became the 
focus of the drug-infused "acid house" scene that spawned the Factory act 
Happy Mondays. Laissez-faire business practices and financial mismanagement 
ultimately scuttled the label, which went into receivership in 1992.

Steve Coogan portrayed Wilson in "24 Hour Party People," a tartly comic 
survey of Factory's chaotic history. Wilson himself took a small cameo role 
as a Granada TV director.

Reuters/Hollywood Reporter





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright: White Label Records

feel free to speak up if i'm missing anything here...
it's a bit of a murky subject.

Stage Left of Copyright: Audio Sampling 
Embraces the Public Domain
Peter Alden Sandifer
master's thesis draft


White Label Records:  Sampling Under the Radar

     Copyright law hasnt stopped musicians from using
unlicensed samples, any more than closing Napster has
stopped MP3 sharing.  As with the illicit file
sharers, there is still a healthy underground culture
distributing music with unauthorized samples.   

     White label records are a common medium in the
culture of electronic dance music (buzzwords:  techno,
rave, electronica.)  Electronic musicians tend to call
themselves producers, as if acknowledging a preference
for not guitars and musical scores, but more often
hardware, software, and a cerebral organization of
music as data. 

     White label records supply an underground market
for unauthorized remixes of copyrighted songs, or
records that use unauthorized samples.  These records
are rare (very few pressings)--  yet abundant as an
underground genre,  due to the alluring concept of
sampling without permission from the original artist. 

     The center circle of the record is literally
white, with no text to distinguish it or offer credits
to the producer or the source she sampled.  White
labels (and electronic dance music in general) are
preferably released on vinyl to serve the DJthe
conduit of music to the masses.   Dodging legal
ramifications, the white label producer takes no
credit except for the reputation generated by
underground buzz, a penned notation on the white
label, or by nearly-invisible credits engraved in the
inner circle of the vinyl.  White label records are
usually distributed through anonymous post office
boxes, underground record stores, or the Internet. 
     
     Sales are trifle next to Top 40 records, but
songs using tasteful samples in a creative way can
become popular enough in the underground to encourage
producers to continue experimenting with this audio
alchemy. 

     To DJs and audiences in the underground dance
scene, the shelf life of a hot new record is sometimes
over within a month, if not by the end of the weekend.
 With a turnover this fast, its easy to imagine a
producer with distribution connections releasing
several hundred (or thousand) copies of a sample-laden
record, with all evidence gone by the end of the
fiscal year.


next week: Conclusion

(c) 20004 peter sandifer







---------------------------------------------------------------------

Subject: [sfraves] SRR:  Columbia Law School's Music Copyright Infringement
  Project

--=====================_1354978==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

Columbia Law School's Music Copyright Infringement Project

http://www.ccnmtl.columbia.edu/projects/law/library/

"The purpose of this project is to capitalize on the distributed nature
of digital information systems to collect, organize and distribute
graphic and audio materials associated with music copyright infringement
cases in the United States from the middle of the nineteenth century on.
This documentation, especially for cases over twenty-five years old, is
difficult to obtain and has never before been systematically collected
or published in print or electronic format. Our goal is to accumulate
and publish a complete collection of music copyright infringement
opinions, comments about the musical works they consider, and graphic
and sound files of relevant portions of these works."





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Stage Left of Copyright: 
Audio Sampling Embraces the Public Domain
Peter Alden Sandifer

I.  Introduction:  Audio Sampling 

     Musicians, DJs, and audiophiles record samples
from any available media  television, films, radio,
records, tapes, speeches, CD, DVD, and the airwaves. 
Car stereos around the world share the   (   ( ((often
annoying))  ) )   )    results of plundered samples.
Hip-hop, R&B, electronica, and Top 40 music are a few
popular genres that have welcomed sampling. 

     The sample itself is a section of pre-recorded
audio (such as a jazz horn riff, a drum section, or a
recorded voice) captured from one recording and reused
as a part of a new recording.  To turn an audio sample
into a usable musical ingredient, a common technique
is to sequence a loop.   
 
     Looping involves digitally or manually repeating
a sample in accurate musical time, tempo and key to
fit the design of the new song.  Digitally, a sample
can be looped with software or electronic sampling
hardware.  Manually, a live DJ uses records and
turntables (or other audio devices), cueing and
releasing the recorded sample at a musically
appropriate time. 

     This unconventional approach to composing music
arrived in Americas consciousness as a footnote to
rap music in the 1970s, bringing with it a host of
problems concerning artistic legitimacy, copyright law
and financial compensation.

     This paper includes some conjecture and rhetoric
about the nature of ownership and the creative spirit,
but pragmatics led me in search of historical roots
that would provide a sort of cultural validity for an
artistic experimentation that is too often dismissed
as illegitimate.  It is a compelling idea that a
generation of artists, armed with technology, would
seek to appropriate the sounds of their musical
forebearsas if by instinctand even in violation of
the law.


II.  Audio Sampling and U.S. Copyright Law

United States Copyright Act Section 107-- Limitations
on Exclusive Rights:  Fair Use.  (Negativland, p. i)

Notwithstanding the provisions of sections 106 and
106A, the fair use of copyrighted work, including such
use by reproduction for purposes such as criticism,
comment, news reporting, teachingscholarship or
research, is not an infringement of copyright.  In
determining whether the use made of a work in any
particular case is a fair use the factors to be
considered shall
include

1. the purpose and character of the use, including
whether such use is of a commercial nature or is for
nonprofit educational purposes;
2. the nature of the copyrighted work;
3. the amount and substantiality of the portion used
in relation to the copyrighted work as a whole; and
4. the effect of the use upon the potential market for
or value of the copyrighted work.



     Copyright law was originally developed in
sixteenth century England as a tool of censorship
under Queen Mary Tudor (Vaidhyanathan, p. 37), but its
current directive in the United States is considerably
more honorable:  to encourage artists and creators to
continue at their craft with peace of mind (Epstein,
p.159) that their original ideas are protected from
thieves and plagiarists.  

     Still, the United States Copyright Act leaves
much to be interpreted by the music industry and the
judicial system when it comes to the creative re-use
of recorded music.  Ken Anderson and Eric Greenspan,
attorneys who separately represent a variety of rap
acts inclined to use samples, both contend that U.S.
copyright laws did not anticipate the innovation of
sampling technologies and art forms, and are therefore
unqualified to adequately serve as a judicial beacon
in current legal cases  (Marcus, p. 209).

     Recently, U.S courts have delivered conflicting
judgments about what constitutes an illegal sample. 
In 2002, a lower court determined that rap band NWAs
sample of a George Clinton riff did not rise to the
level of legally recognizable appropriation 
(Reynolds), applying a familiar de minimis (1) 
ruling:  If audiences arent likely to be confused by
the re-use, then the sample is legally clear.   

     In September 2004, that ruling was overturned by
the 6th District Federal Appeals Court, whose judges
made a blanket decree: Get a license, or do not
sample, regardless of the length or acoustic
alterations made to the borrowed audio (Rosinski). 
However, two months later, the 9th District Federal
Appeals Court reaffirmed its 2003 de minimis ruling in
favor of a Beastie Boys brief sample of a James
Newton flute recording:  that the borrowed sample was
"so meager and fragmentary that the average audience
would not recognize the appropriation" (Frederikse).

     Records store owner Robert Mooney voiced the
paradox that exists in U.S. copyright law, by
comparing sampling to scholarly research
[paraphrased]:  "You can go to the library and Xerox a
page of a book, but if you Xeroxed the whole book,
then you're breaking the law.  Theres supposed to be
room for you to cite a sentence in your paper or
book.  (Reynolds.)


1. De minimis: So minor as to be disregarded.

2. a determination of whether [a sample] is infringing
will typically focus on the issue of substantial
similarity (Korn, p. 222).



III.  History and Cultural Significance of Audio
Sampling 

     A. Negativland and the Postmodern Defense

     To some musicians and critics, sampling and
reusing copyrighted audio is not just a violation of
federal law, but a more damning accusation involving
unimaginative artists who cheat the creative process
by stealing from others for their own commercial
gain (Adams & McKibbins, p. 158). 

     To others, it is an action of artistic homage
(Theberge, p. 205), or parody, or critical commentary,
or deconstructive analysis.  "Re-contextualization" is
how the sample-happy band Negativland defends the
thousands of plundered samples they loop, mix, record
and broadcast in violation of the law.   
Negativlands artistic intent is to use captured
fragments to create something entirely newa
psychological impact based on a new juxtaposition of
diverse elements, ripped from their usual context,
chewed up and spit out as a new form of hearing the
world around us (Negativland, p. 121).

     Postmodernism  a common alibi for unusual
behavior -- is frequently employed to justify
sampling, with the argument that this
re-interpretation of previously documented media in a
novel setting (Marcus, p. 206) bears the same
legitimacy and cultural value as Andy Warhols
paintings of Campbells Soup cans. 

     Part of the movement against sampling seems to be
based on a proud Western insistence on originality,
coupled with an embarrassed denial of influence from
others.  Another obvious motivation is financial,
particularly when record labels pounce.  Folklore and
documented cases indicate that it is often record
labels (the custodians of musicians intellectual
property) who most avidly seek compensation from
copyright violators.  

     For example, when Negativland was sued for
releasing a provocative record called "U2" that
featured samples and parodies of that eponymous Irish
rock group, the band U2 apparently had no objection to
the satirical recording (Fax from Brian Eno, U2s
producer, p. 31).  Rather, it was U2s
representatives, Island Records and Warner-Chappel,
who sought to protect the bands clean-cut image
from Negativlands deceptive use of the U2 name on
the parody album cover (Excerpts from the
Island/Warner-Chappell lawsuit, p. 15). 

     Ironically, there is nothing original or
inherently private about U2 -- the Irish rockers had
lifted their name from the U-2 spy plane of the Cold
War era.  Ironically again, Negativland included a
picture of that spy plane on the cover of their U2
album, a detail which logically should have
invalidated the plaintiffs argument about dominion
over the word U2.  (Negativland, p. i- v).  
Representatives of U2 won possession of Negativlands
master tapes for the parody album, but three years
later agreed to return the reels to the tenacious
audio saboteurs on the condition that you stop
writing to us  (Negativland, p. 178).  

     As instigators and nuisance to the establishment
of creative ownership, Negativland waged an exhausting
and expensive war on the major labels. Admittedly,
this is a group of artists who, this writer witnessed
at a San Francisco concert, hacked into local cable
lines and broadcast their performance through the
Playboy Channels audio signaljust for kicks.  And
admittedly, Negativland gained more recognition from
the U2 lawsuits than they would have from their U2
album alone.  But Negativland maintains that its
motivations are to expose the problems of the
individual as a passive spectator to popular media; to
challenge our modern surrender of the age-old concept
of shared culture[to] private owners (Negativland,
p. 190).



Shared Culture:  From West Africa to the Plantations

     If shared culture, as Negativland says, is at the
heart of the sampling defense, then it is crucial to
look at the history of sampling in terms of not just
technology, but of tradition and cultural
significance.  The story of sampling and how it came
to be complicates any quick assumptions about blatant
theft.

     It is an interesting historical fact that
sampling can be traced to slave traditions in the
United States and the Caribbean, by way of the regions
of West Africa from which slaves were taken.  Digital
sampling is a mere technological upgrade of traditions
belonging to a culture and a continent beyond the
understanding of the U.S. Supreme Court.

     Differing from the linear path of intellect
that dominates European-America, West African culture
tends to view the world from a circular perspective,
in homage to creative voices of the past as well as to
a community of shared consciousness. (Vaidhyanathan,
p. 125).    

     Long before the advent of electronic samplers,
African-American artists of blues, jazz, gospel, and
oral tradition treated songs as communal property: 
melodies, guitar riffs, and lyrics are in a constant
cycle of being borrowed, altered, and re-used (Jones,
p. 28). To the Black conscience, ownership of ideas
was as alien as the promise of owning forty acres and
a mule (2).

     It wasnt until the commodification of rap music
and the subsequent sampling of recorded music in the
1980s that copyright became an issue of public debate.
(Jones, p. 92).  Its ironic to consider that liberal
African-American ownership rules invited the lucrative
mimicry of superstars like Elvis Presley, while half a
century later, American copyright law would dampen
those same shared-culture ideals that spawned music
sampling.


2.   Forty acres and a mule: General Shermans
unfulfilled promise to freed slaves at the end of the
Civil War (Special Field Order #15).



The Carribbean

     During the 1960s and 70s, the creative re-use of
recorded music developed in Jamaica and neighboring
islands of the Caribbean-- areas also inhabited by the
descendants of West African slaves.  Here, the
legendary Jamaican sound system --speakers, amplifier,
record turntables and a mixing console-- became tools
for musicians often a few dollars shy of buying
instruments.  
     
Musical sections were cued on record players by a
DJ and released at the proper time, as an instrumental
bed over which vocalists sang.  This
re-contextualization of existing records is called
version [vair-shen] in Jamaican dialect.  The use of
instrumental sections for singing gave birth to a
reggae offshoot called dub (Connell and Gibson, p.
183).

     The Jamaican /version/ relates aesthetically to
the rules of jazz and blues in the United States,
which inherently (as a part of the social fabric)
involved the sharing and repetition of ideas, musical
riffs, and vocal toasts.  Chords, chants, and lyrics
volleyed back and forth as a cultural torch, a common
property of a people who owned little else but memory
of tradition.


To the Bronx

      When the ease of global transportation allowed a
wider migration from the Caribbean to the U.S. in the
1970s, Jamaicas seminal style of re-using recorded
music migrated to New Yorks Bronx.  

    In the ghetto, disk jockey legends in the making
like Kool Herc, Grandmaster Flash, and Afrika Bambaata
(Conell & Gibson, p. 182) selected only the funkiest
sections of disco and rock records the breaks
sometimes replaying those musical parts by alternating
duplicate copies of the same record, and sometimes by
just slamming the volume faders to the break of a new
song.  

     This style of programming the musical breaks
eventually became known as break beat music, and
along with it came the familiar terms break dance, 
b-boy and b-girl.  The break beat would become the
backbone of rap music, and later a genre of its own.

     It was the rhythmnot the writtenthat kept
African culture alive and progressing in European
colonies unable to reconcile the racist divide.  It is
somewhere here, an indefinable space straddling
continents and centuries, where I believe the communal
(yet displaced) cultures of West Africa found the
technology to preserve records of the past, and the
artistic curiosity to celebrate it.  

    That moment of discovery loops back to the
plantation fields of the Caribbean and Americas
south, where rhythm and lyrical truths took place of
the written word.  That innocent, artistic desire to
merge past recordings to tell todays stories is
fitting to the observation of Alan Korn, that Edisons
phonograph was a device intended for the preservation
of sound rather than for its mass republication
(Korn, p. 222).--

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  FURIOUS 2 - Saturday, January 29th

In two weeks we get down, dirty, funky and naaaaaasty.  Evil Breaks style.  
You've been warned.  Attending this party could result in increased 
heart-rate, uncontrollable body twitching and temporary insanity.  You've 
been warned.


FURIOUS 2
January 29th, 2005
9pm - 5am

Evil Breaks is going back to the underground, and if you remember the first 
FURIOUS show, you know this party is going to go off. We've combined with 
Ill Behavior, Subscience, and the Zapatistas to bring you one of the best 
lineups you're going to see for an underground show. Located in Oakland, 
this show is all ages, and is going from 9pm - 5am, with special lasers and 
lighting provided by Stimulights and with a live VJ Satsi (Lush Camp) in the 
main room.

Featuring:

LoBudg - Live (Sober Music/Play records) - Austin, TX
Lobudg is the combination of S.O.T.E.G. aka Bil Bless and Dave Cannon, the 
man behind Carbon Community. This show will be their debut performace as 
Lobudg, as they perform for the first time for us in SF before heading out 
on a WMC tour. With their couple of releases already getting massive support 
from the breaks community, these are two artists to definitely keep your eye 
on.


Evil Breaks room:

Dragn'fly vs Aaron Jae (lovetribe/shaolin/Evil Breaks) - Special Breaks set
DJ Ripple (Subscience)
Bam (Evil Breaks/Invibe.com)
Athena vs Influence (Evil Breaks/In tha Mix)
Nick Nyquil (Evil Breaks/Ill Behavior)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Maebyn La Fey(Subscience)


Ill Behavior room:

Denise (djdenise.com/sound asylum)
Erig Riggsbee vs Clockwork (Breakthru)
Homero (Yerba Buena Records)
Hyjinx vs Ill D (Thought Crime)
Thomas Kent vs Kris Kent (Ill Behavior/Modified)
Element (Modified)
Emune vs Cmos (Ill Behavior)


Subscience DnB room:

THE INVISIBLES - LIVE
(featuring SF dnb champions Abstract, Qzen, and Kimi)
Method One (method-one.com)
dj M (Faultline/SOMA Sessions)
Bicolas (Rhythm Method/Skills)
the Hitmen (Subscience)
Matty G & Killjoy(Enter the Jungle/Tighten Up!THC/Fallen Soldiers) - Santa 
Cruz
w/ Indidjinous on didjeridoo (Enter the Jungle)
Reclipse (Bayraves, Discharge Clothing)
Yagi (otc/hcftp)


Zapatistas house room:

Felipe Avelar (House Nation/Zapatistas)
DJ Doza (BR/Zapatistas/E. Ave)
Carlos Alfonzo (Soop/Zapatistas/BR)
Elektro (Electronic Ave.)
Soul 1 (Zapatistas)
Vinyl Junkies (LFX & Nikko)
Miss Arely (Zapatistas)
Rob Base (Zapatistas)
Misha (Subscience)

Tickets are $10 presale and $15 at the door
they're now for sale online at Groovetickets.com
and in Reverb, Skills, and Solid Grooves

INFO LINE: 408.278.5211

--------------------------
< Brandon / DJ Bam >

DJ Bam - serving breaks and beats
http://www.invibe.com/bam

January 29th:  Furious II
--------------------
---------------------

If the manual of life is encoded in our DNA, where do we look to find the=
=20
blueprint of consciousness? This was a subject that fascinated Francis=20
Crick, who, along with James Watson, discovered the double-helix structure=
=20
of DNA 50 years ago.

Engrossed in the mysterious relationship between mind and body, Crick=20
later felt impelled to turn his attention from matter to mind and from=20
biology to philosophy =D1 but he persisted in believing that one day,=20
consciousness could be explained in biological terms, using the tools of=20
neuroscience.

Saturday, January 15, 2005 ** Opel presents GaBa Mood Edition **

In a town dominated by house and breaks, every once in a while we like to=
=20
offer an alternative: a vibe based exploration into more progressive=20
shades of music from some of the city's best outside of the big club=20
setting. This time GABA MOOD moves to Sublounge where we can offer a=20
second room for a more straight powerful progressive sound in addition to=
=20
the trancier shades the party is built around...

Downstairs will be a seldom heard thin slice of quality progressive=20
trance. It's the trance that walks that line between the depth and the=20
melody, the power and the pretty, the uplifting and the downright groovy.

No cheese, no over done anthems, not commercial trance, epic trance, or=20
psychedelic trance, just the high energy transcendentally inclined good=20
stuff...

Downstairs with:

Syd Gris (Opel / Opulent Temple)

Cyber Joe (1015/djcyberjoe.com)

Upstairs will feature some of the cities best progressive DJ's

with

Jonathan Ojeda (Sound AM / Spundae)

Taj (djtaj.com)

Kem (Elastiq)

Eddy Gordo (Brazil)

10pm-11pm TBA

@ Sublounge

$5 before 11:00pm $10 after

-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

rebuffering every 5 minutes for some of the music they play.

Mayan Elders Give Urgent Warning
+++ by Mitch Battros ECTV


I have just received an urgent notice from Adam Rubel of Saq Be. Adam states
he has just received word from Carlos Barrios (Mayan Elder), that earth
changing events are in motion to escalate. No, not next year, not next month,
but next week or next day.


The first thing Adam reminds us not do is hit the panic button. What is
unfolding is in perfect order and the Earth has seen this many times before.
However, it is suggested, and I am personally suggesting to you, that our
collective influence can make a difference. I believe this is what our ancestors have
told us all along. It says so in the Bible, in the Mayan Calendar, in Tibetan
Sanskrit, Hopi Petroglyphs, Egyptian Hieroglyphs and the list is endless. No,
this is not woo-woo, it is science. More on this below.

Mayan elders have specifically given warning to five continents. Three of
which are named. 1) North America 2) Europe 3) Central America .

Through the ancient techniques of divination and tools of prophecy, the Mayan
elders are calling forth to pay close attention to messages being set forth
by ongoing earth changing events. The recent destruction that manifested in
Indonesia is predicted to now occur rapidly upon five continents of the earth.
This message is not meant to induce fear, but to give warning of preparation
and remain aware of your surroundings. The elders are concerned about what has
been presented in their recent divinations and they call to all humanity to
warn their leaders and to work very hard at a spiritual level to prevent the
impending destruction.

Adam reports this message has been verified and brought forth by various
Mayan elders in Guatemala, and is meant for distribution to all humanity. Last
years record breaking hurricanes and the 9.0 mag. earthquake with following
tsunami in Indonesia have been warnings of possible coming floods in Europe and the
US West Coast.


Prayer/Meditation Not Woo-Woo But Scientifically Grounded


Professor Richard Davidson (University of Wisconsin) just released his latest
research on the power of meditation. I have sent word to Dr. Davidson to
arrange an upcoming interview on Earth Changes TV Radio Hour. In a Washington
Post article released earlier today, Professor Davidson reports over the past
few years researchers at the University of Wisconsin have been working with
Tibetan monks were able to translate those mental experiences into the scientific
language of high-frequency gamma waves and brain synchrony, or coordination.
They have pinpointed the left prefrontal cortex, an area just behind the left
forehead, as the place where brain activity associated with meditation is
especially intense. Many have long believed it is the Pineal Gland (the physical 3rd EYE).

Davidson says his newest results from the meditation study, published in the
Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences in November shows that mental
training through meditation (and presumably other disciplines) can itself
change the inner workings and circuitry of the brain. Full Article

Mayan Elders have put out a specific call for people around the world to join
in prayer, meditation or whatever method of spirituality one engages in to
unite on January 18th at the time of their local sunset (approx 6:00PM). This
date is (9) Keme according to the sacred Mayan Cholq'ij calendar available at:
http://www.sacredroad.org has the potential for protecting humanity from
disaster.

There will be many major ceremonies in the Mayan communities for this
purpose. An open invitation is extended to humanity that wish to join the Mayan
people for the Waxa'qib B'atz' ceremonies on February 12th in Guatemala.

> Subject: Candy Andy W
> 
> 
> 
> the legend of Candy Andy W
> 



i think it was radley that came up with the names on the flyer.. that party 
brings alot back..

early skills parties had a ton of heart. its very rare to have a great first 
party and an awesome vibe and a massive cult following in the span of a year 
and a half. the first skills party ended with such a positive note, it kept tom 
& jason riding the crest of a wave until on or around their first 
bblgm-scifi. at their first event people were leaving and getting bummed about the party 
being too short and there was one clique of candy kids hugging goodbye and 
then another joined and soon more kids flocked to it faster than you can spell 
katamari damaci. it was very inspiring and one of the most plur affirming 
moments in SFR history, i've never seen anything like it since. 

     alot of people like to talk smack about skills, but they are way too 
short sighted to see that skills was founded on very hard work and determination, 
and yes, the best techno & house in the bay. there's a certain delerium 
promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties. these guys had it 
bad, but not in the sense that some do.   i'd say they even changed how hand 
to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a word when 
handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up hand, -give 
flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills parties 
earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and socialize with all 
the flyer recipients, the flyer was an afterthought. though i'd have to say on 
an aside that the current street team that goes to the break in warehouse party 
with a brick of banded flyers, hucking them on the nearest coffee table and 
leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink. 

their early flyering methods were just an example of how they had impacted 
the scene, their abiltiy to bring techno to the forefront of rave massive 
culture hasn't been matched since.   in a matter of a period of 2 years, techno 
music went from hanging out in the basement of the acme gallery with a Twist mural 
overhead to these big massives where techno music was accepted as part of the 
norm and opened up alot of people to techno that normally wouldn't have ever 
heard it.   

i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/ 
trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have begun with 
cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their influence from F8 that 
cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as part of 
the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de rigueur in 
the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even though URB 
magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8 started 
to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to adopt a 
promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i think this 
drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave culture in 
general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split second of media 
history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not readily 
acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were forced to 
change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their place in the 
scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to keep the 
crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on their part 
to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost and their 
love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with their 
audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really caught up in the 
whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the djs and the 
croud became the afterthought. 

the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' apparently 
disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and   introducing 
inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its importance 
didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still talk trash 
about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to accept 
the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept it, they 
should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between what now 
seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not ashamed to admit 
it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i really like 
a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept, however 
anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i dislike 
anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of kids who run 
around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their drug 
consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant host to the 
buggers. 

guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate yourself with 
the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so people 
should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim that 
another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a raver. and 
anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.

blah blah etc.



::respect::

sean ocean
DJ Disconnect

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
www.defsf.com "communicate:inform:unite"
