Subject: [sfraves] Anderson Maclain and the Pornography Incident

Anderson Maclain and the Pornography Incident


     Anderson Maclain was sober by the time they
reached Jerry's house.  Jerry invited him in and
offered him a glass of rum, but he declined and
instead, lit a cigarette.

     Jerry got the rum from the cupboard and reached
for a glass, then hesitated and drank straight from
the bottle.

     "You sure?"  he waved the bottle in Anderson's
direction.

     "Yes, thanks anyway," Anderson said.

     Although he'd only met Jerry that evening,
Anderson Maclain took a liking to him.  Jerry was
pleasant and didn't hassle him the way a lot of people
did sometimes.  It was rare these days to find someone
you could spend time with, and not get hassled in some
way or another.  These days, Anderson had a habit of
keeping away from people.  Most folks he knew were
either overbearing or too nervous and awkward to be
any fun.

     "You've had enough, huh?"  Jerry asked.
 
    "Yes, I've had enough," Anderson agreed.  He
looked around the room at the nude pinup on the
walls.

     "I did it myself," Jerry told him.  He meant the
posters.

     "Interesting," Anderson said, without much
thought.

     "You think these chics are hot, wait'll I show
you the videos."

     "The videos?"  Anderson repeated.
  
     "Got 'em offa some guy down in Phoenix," Jerry
told him.  "They're bootlegs, but you wouldn't be able
to tell.  He uses real film, none of that video shit. 
He's got his own studio right over in Big Spring. 
Sells his movies for up to three hundred bucks apiece,
but I get most of mine for free, on account of because
I help him out in the studio."
 
    "No shit," Anderson said.

     "Yeah, man, no shit."  Jerry opened the cabinet
and took out a videotape.  Anderson figured there were
at least a hundred videos in there.
 
    "I transfer the films to video tape so I can take
them to parties and stuff, but it's still highquality
production."
   
    Anderson sat and watched as Jerry started the
tape.

     "Real highquality production," he repeated.  He
scratched his balls and took a swig from the bottle.
 
    "Do you mind if I fastforward to the good part?" 
Jerry asked.

     Anderson said nothing.

     "Here it is...watch this...can you believe it?  I
never would have thought a girl could do that, but I
was there when they filmed this motherfucker.  Okay,
here it is.  Watch."

     Anderson watched.

     Jerry snickered.

     Anderson lit another cigarette and kept watching.

     "You got another cigarette?"  Jerry asked.

     Anderson gave him one, and Jerry sat down next to
him.
 
    Jerry drank his rum and Anderson kept watching.

     "I got a tape of a woman getting it on with a
German Shepherd, but the quality isn't so good.  Hey,
you watching, man?  Look at that fat bitch.  I
wouldn't fuck her with a stolen dick."

     The woman moaned and her flesh wiggled in awkward
happiness.

     "Now the cucumber!"  Jerry howled.

     Anderson wondered if he had all of his movies
memorized.

     "Okay, watch!"

     Anderson tugged absently at his shirtsleeve and
took a deep drag from his cigarette.

     "How many do you have?"  he asked.

     "What, how many movies?  I got seventytwo on
video and another twenty on reel.  I'd show you the
reels, but my projector's broken."

     "That's too bad," Anderson replied.

     "You got another smoke?"  Jerry asked.

     Anderson had none.

     "I'm going to the store for a pack.  You want to
come along or stay here and watch the rest of this?"

     "I think I'll stay here and watch the rest of
this."

     Jerry got up, stumbled over the coffee table, and
cursed his shins.  Anderson wondered if he would make
it to the store after all the rum he'd had.  Anderson
didn't really care, though.  

     He didn't care if Jerry went off the road and
crunched his car around a telephone pole.  When he
thought about it, it really didn't matter if Jerry
made it to the store or not.

     "I'll be back in fifteen, okay?"

     "Okay," Anderson agreed.

     Jerry went out the door, and Anderson followed
him onto the porch.  He watched as Jerry started the
car and lurched into the darkness of the cool desert
night.

     When the taillights flickered away and he could
no longer hear the racing engine, he went back into
the house.

     He picked up the rum bottle from the counter, and
with one graceful sweep, crashed it through the screen
of the television.  The tubes inside the set flashed
and fizzled, and Anderson noticed that his hand was
bleeding.

     He wiped the blood on the wall, and opened the
door to the cabinet under the shattered television
set.  Using the marble ashtray from the kitchen, he
smashed the videotapes until they were nothing but a
scattered mess of broken plastic and twisted film.
 
    When his arm began to tire, he set the ashtray
into flight, toward the french doors.  Windowpanes
divided unfairly into shards and splinters, and the
ashtray hit the screen and bounced back onto the
carpet.

     Anderson bent down to the rubble on the floor and
stretched videotape from broken cassettes, flinging
the tape across the room so that it hung from the
chandelier and draped over the furniture.  The house
shone in its new decor, a mad ballroom glittered with
violent confetti and angry knots of ribbon.

     Anderson hadn't much time left.  Jerry would be
back soon, and he would kill him when he saw what he
had done.

     He kicked at the broken glass and plastic and the
confused entanglement of videotape, and left the
house.

     He got into his car and drove up into the hills,
where he could see the sparkling, hopeful lights of
the city below him.  He pulled his car to the side of
the road, overlooking a ravine, and wept.


Peter Sandifer (c) 1991

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SRR:  Columbia Law School's Music Copyright Infringement  Project

--- Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:

> Columbia Law School's Music Copyright Infringement
> Project


The John Fogerty (Creedence Clearwater Revival) court
case is particularly funny.  Fantasy Records in
Berkeley sued Fogerty for plagiarizing himself.   

The  bass line from CCR's "Run Through The Jungle"
(written by Fogerty) was mimicked on Fogerty's solo
song "The Old Man Down the Road."     

Fantasy Records owned the rights to the original CCR
track.  In court, Fogerty took the witness stand with
a guitar and played songs that demonstrated how blues
historically tends to recycle riffs & rhythms.

Jury found for Fogerty.  Thank gosh.

boomy

http://www.ccnmtl.columbia.edu/projects/law/library/cases/case_fantfogerty.html

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 24 track ::r::  (?)

quoth petersandifer@sbcglobal.net:
> were you just humoring me last night when you said you'd be down for
> 24 track-style instrumental jamming at your party?  I'd love to see
> SFRavers getting busy with drum machines and trumpets and andy's
> guitar and philip's banjo & violins and stuff like that.  

Funny you should mention this. Mochipet is putting together a
MIDI-synced "techno orchestra" for the Capricorn party at OW this
weekend, repleat with laptops, drum machines, synthesizers and samplers.
It's going to be slightly more structured without banjos and violins,
but I imagine there are going to be a few relatively cacaphonous
moments. :)

There was a more noise-oriented thing like this at the OW a couple of
months ago, which I had planned to attend but ended up flaking out on.
Did anyone else go to that? How was it?

I'm really interested in loosely organized collaborations like these.
Jamming is, for me, the best way to make music: each person focuses on
one or two instruments and just tweaks them continuously, creating an
endless chain of natural variations. The last time I performed live in
such a large group was when I played the oboe in middle school, so I'm
pretty psyched about this.

Anyway, if this ends up happening at Ryan's, count me in. I'll bring my
machinedrum or an ES-1.

Toodles,
--

  phone://+1.415.577.3961
  http://alterior.net
  aim://shawnpallen

Subject: [sfraves] Stage Left of Copyright: Compromise & Symbiosis (Conclusion)

Stage Left of Copyright: 
Audio Sampling Embraces the Public Domain
(c) 2004 Peter Sandifer
master's thesis draft


IV.  CONCLUSION     
Compromise and Symbiosis:  Aerosmith,  the Napster
Mistake, and the U.S. Postal Service

     The music industrys reflexive fondness for
lawsuits is about as productive as any world leaders
leap to settle disputes with war.  If the arts are to
survive, flourish and continue to inspire future
generations, the path taken will be by cooperation,
not attempts to legally cripple the offending party.  


     Ive always seen the case of Napster as a model
of corporate neurosis destroying a potentially
successful venture. In the late 1990s, the
file-sharing network Napster hosted a global community
of music lovers.   Napster was the peer-to-peer (P2P)
network that virtually everyone used to download 
(share, steal, pirate) copyrighted music.

     In a panic to prevent financial losses, the major
labels, led by the Recording Industry Association of
America (RIAA) called on the Supreme Court to have
Napster shut down.    After a year of public debate
about ethics and freedoms in the digital age, the plug
was pulled on Napster in 2001 (Leeds).  Every MP3
sharer on the planet, once happily confined to a
single, thriving community, then scattered and
resettled at a variety of P2P clones popping up in the
wake of the RIAA victory.

     Napster was a technological and cultural anomaly
never to be repeated.  At that one wonderful moment in
history, every music fan in the world with Internet
access was in one location. An absolute paradise of
consumer information was online for the taking-- 
personal user information, music genre preferences,
song preferences, artist preferences and frequency of
downloads.  

     Out of fear and self-preservation, the music
industry blew a golden opportunity, and all the users
scattered in different directions when Napster was
shut down.  Those users are still sharing MP3s, but
from a number of P2P networks around the globe.  If
the music industry had the foresight or patience to
consider a compromise outside of the courts, a
lucrative relationship could have been forged with
Napster.  

     Very recently, the recording industry has turned
to Napster creator Shawn Fanning for assistance in
their delayed development of legal file-sharing
networks based on the model designed by their former
nemesis.

     The difference in the Napster case is outright
music replication vs. a creative re-use of brief song
segments, but the resolution can easily be the same,
if the music industry is willing to view audio
sampling as an opportunity to forge a symbiotic
relationship with musicians and consumers.  

     In a courtroom, only one side wins.  In an open,
sharing relationship, both sides (the sampler and the
sampled) stand to benefit.  Several cases might
inspire the music industry to recognize the cultural
(that is to say, financial) value of allowing past
records to be revived in a fresh context.

     The Latin band War, which had been musically
dormant since the 1970s, issued a 1992 album called
Rap Declares War, which featured the many War songs
that had been sampled.  Reaping the benefits of heavy
sampling by rap artists, a new life was given to Wars
discography  (Jones, p. 94).
	
     Such was the case with 90s rap band Run-DMC and
the declining 70s rock band Aerosmith.  When Run-DMC
revived Aerosmiths Walk This Way, the aging rockers
made a cameo in the new rap video, and popular
interest in Aerosmith was revitalized.  

     As recently as 2002, Aerosmith guitarist Joe
Perry said the band was "still feeling the [positive]
repercussions" of Run-DMC's reconceptualization  of
Walk This Way:  "It put us back on the map...and gave
us a whole new audience."  (Cooper).

     In a recent copyright dispute (this one over a
band's name), the U.S. Postal Service in 2004 sent a
cease-and-desist letter to a rock band who called
itself Postal Service. Rather than change their name
and recall thousands of albums, the band managed to
strike a creative deal with the U.S. Postal Service: 
the government agency allowed the band to keep their
name, free of charge.  

     In exchange, the band includes literature in
their album sleeves encouraging their young, web-
happy fans to use U.S. mail as an alternative to the
Internet.  Postal Service albums are sold on the
U.S.P.S. website, and the band will appear in
advertisements for the U.S.P.S.  (Alt-rockers settle
with Post Office, p. 42.) In this clever resolution
that sidestepped the legal system, both parties
benefit.

     The simplest approach to avoiding legal wrangling
is for the modern artist to clear samples before
distribution (or wiser, before production.)  The
Beastie Boys attorney Ken Anderson gambled on the
assumption that respect and recognition (Marcus, p.
205) was the main concern for artists whose work had
been sampled.  During the 1988 production of the
Beastie Boys album Pauls Boutique, Anderson spent
hours on the telephone getting artists permission for
the 400 samples used on the recording.  The artists
permitted every sample to be used, for free or a
nominal charge (Marcus, p. 205). 

     In the history of popular culture, it usually
serves the establishment to acknowledge and adapt to
new concepts.  Rap music (like jazz before it) was
once considered unmarketablenow rap is the worlds
most popular music genre.  Napster was once pursued as
a den of piracynow its founder is consulted for the
model he created. 

     It seems odd that industries invest millions to
protect their futures, but so often fail to see the
cultural futures developing before them. 
Historically, do we celebrate entities of power that
oppose or silence new ideas, especially in the name of
the law? 

     Creative Commons is a copyright-licensing
organization that recognizes changing ownership values
(fueled by the Internets rediscovery of shared
culture.)  In recognition of new artistic intentions,
the online group offers some rights reserved
copyright licenses for authors and artists
(creativecommons.org). With these unusually specific
licenses, the artist dictates whether audiences can
copy, distribute, perform or sample their work. 

     But would Negativland have any fun here?  

     Is the party over when the forbidden becomes
licensed?

----------

Air Force proposal sought gay sex weapon

Fri Jan 14, 8:35 PM ET


Tom Musbach and Christopher Curtis, PlanetOut Network

SUMMARY: The Pentagon 
(<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://news.search.yahoo.com/search/news?fr=news-storylinks&p=%22Pentagon%22&c=&n=20&yn=c&c=news&cs=nw>news 
- 
<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://search.yahoo.com/search?fr=web-storylinks&p=Pentagon>web 
sites) once looked into making a weapon that would render enemy troops 
sexually attracted to one another, according to a document obtained by a 
watchdog group.



The Pentagon briefly looked into making a weapon that would render enemy 
troops sexually attracted to one another, according to an official document 
uncovered by a watchdog group that monitors research into biological and 
chemical weapons.

The proposed aphrodisiac was part of a weapons development plan circulated 
in 1994 at the U.S. Air Force Wright Laboratory in Dayton, Ohio. An outline 
of the plan was discovered by the Sunshine Project and posted on its Web site.

The six-year plan included development of several "non-lethal" chemical 
weapons, including one that would inflict "severe and lasting halitosis" in 
enemy combatants and a "sting me/attack me" chemical that would cause bees 
to become more aggressive.

The aphrodisiac chemical would be designed to make enemy soldiers sexually 
irresistible to each other. The resulting widespread homosexual behavior, 
the proposal suggests, would cause a "distasteful but completely non-lethal 
blow" to morale.

A spokesman for the Department of Defense 
(<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://news.search.yahoo.com/search/news?fr=news-storylinks&p=%22Department%20of%20Defense%22&c=&n=20&yn=c&c=news&cs=nw>news 
- 
<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://search.yahoo.com/search?fr=web-storylinks&p=Department%20of%20Defense>web 
sites) stressed that the 1994 outline was strictly a proposal that was 
never approved.

"None of the systems, including the alleged sex bomb, have been developed, 
nor were they ever considered up for development," Lt. Col. Barry Venable 
told the PlanetOut Network on Friday.

The proposal estimated that the cost of the project over six years would 
top $7 million.

Edward Hammond of the Sunshine Project said he has seen several dozen 
similar military weapons proposals, but this 1994 Air Force plan was the 
only one he knew about that specifically addressed an anti-gay weapon. He 
added, however, that the sentiment behind the proposed weapon is not 
uncommon in the military.

"Humiliating your enemy with gay sex sounds a lot like what happened at Abu 
Ghraib," Hammond said, referring to the prisoner abuse scandal that was 
uncovered last year in Iraq 
(<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://news.search.yahoo.com/search/news?fr=news-storylinks&p=%22Iraq%22&c=&n=20&yn=c&c=news&cs=nw>news 
- 
<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/DailyNews/manual/po/co_po/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/*http://search.yahoo.com/search?fr=web-storylinks&p=Iraq>web 
sites).

Steve Ralls, a spokesman for the Washington, D.C.-based Servicemembers 
Legal Defense Network (SLDN), said, "It is a homophobic and delusional 
proposition for the Pentagon to assume a gay opponent is any less 
formidable than a straight one."

Ralls also said that the SLDN, which is fighting the U.S. military's ban on 
openly gay military personnel, would look into the matter and would 
consider asking Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld to repudiate the proposal.

----------
If you'd like to know more, you can find 
<http://us.rd.yahoo.com/dailynews/po/co_po/storytext/airforceproposalsoughtgaysexweapon/13991922/SIG=12ns8p0t4/*http://www.planetout.com/news/search.html?related=1&search=news_articles.2005/01/14/1>stories 
related to Air Force proposal sought gay sex weapon.

on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

Main Entry: 1tala
Pronunciation: 't-l&
Function: noun
Etymology: Sanskrit tAla, literally, hand-clapping
: one of the ancient traditional rhythmic patterns of Indian music --
compare RAGA

Subject: [sfraves] SRR: Future Fashion (was EL rave clothing)

Future Fashion is a collectoin of themes or ideas
related to the future direction of clothing, clothing
and technology integration, clothing customization,
and exotic clothing manufacture.  

Some Future Fashion themes:  

Clothes that display information (or just blink a
lot!)
Clothes that share and transmit information
Clothes that aid social interaction
Clothes that monitor the body
Clothes that monitor the environment
Clothes that add security/safety
Clothes that respond to the body
Modular configurable clothes
Custom clothes in real-time
Special purpose clothing
Sustainable clothing manufacturing 

Here are some of my links...

http://www.verbforshoe.com
http://oakley.com/
http://www.cnn.com/STYLE/9807/28/miyake/
http://radio.weblogs.com/0105910/2004/06/09.html
http://www.wired.com/news/wireless/0,1382,58006,00.html?tw=wn_story_related
http://www.bodymedia.com/index.jsp
http://www.sciencentral.com/articles/view.php3?article_id=218392022&language=english
http://news.zdnet.com/2100-1009_22-939232.html
http://www.spectropolis.info/hotspot.php
http://www.we-make-money-not-art.com/archives/cat_wearable.php?page=17

http://www.space.com/businesstechnology/technology/chameleon_suit_021106.html
http://www.camo-store.com/images/Ghillie%20Suit%20Jacket%20-%20Woodland.jpg

of being a very hippie ethic'd crew with a more money/production oriented
steering/funding comittee (in Greg, Joey and Diane).  You ask anybody that
was hitting those parties back then...  Skillz was *never* underground,
but saw the rapidly expanding Harmony making money after several years of
organic growth from a South Bay candy raver crew of high school kids.

Skills threw their first events at 2nd & Jackson after Harmony had done
so, they were never really "an" underground.  They all but showed up and
started throwing 1500+ person parties.  Used pretty much the same
production contacts, and booked the same DJs as crews before them who had
done it the long way...

-&e->promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties. these guys had it
-&e->bad, but not in the sense that some do.   i'd say they even changed how hand
-&e->to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a word when

Again, not true.  There was a time before the term "street team" existed,
where rude flyering was not of any benefit and it was more about
community... you hand to handed good underground parties and people just
sorta knew that it was of a similar ethic, a similar people.  CWP, FGE and
all that existed, and those enormous sunshade flyers were a laughing stock
as undergrounds grew in quality, frequency and capacity.

-&e->handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up hand, -give
-&e->flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills parties
-&e->earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and socialize with all
-&e->the flyer recipients, the flyer was an afterthought. though i'd have to say on
-&e->an aside that the current street team that goes to the break in warehouse party
-&e->with a brick of banded flyers, hucking them on the nearest coffee table and
-&e->leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink.

True dat.  But how many Skills flyers have I taken off my car?  How many
placemat sized flyerbombings?  I don't know how you can say this except in
the most idealistic reflections of thier first year doing events.  Only
the first few Skills parties had flyers you could fit in a pocket.

-&e->their early flyering methods were just an example of how they had impacted
-&e->the scene, their abiltiy to bring techno to the forefront of rave massive
-&e->culture hasn't been matched since.   in a matter of a period of 2 years, techno
-&e->music went from hanging out in the basement of the acme gallery with a Twist mural
-&e->overhead to these big massives where techno music was accepted as part of the
-&e->norm and opened up alot of people to techno that normally wouldn't have ever
-&e->heard it.

But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to catch
up on what you missed :) ).  Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall techno
talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was
after the trance/cyber switch up)... their early model was based on low
cost local DJs with more money spent on production.  Space Children,
Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno
(Cari Lekebush, Angel Alanis, Adam Beyer, Joel Mull, Joey Beltram,
Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
definition).

-&e->i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/
-&e->trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have begun with
-&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their influence from F8 that
-&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as part of
-&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de rigueur in
-&e->the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even though URB
-&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8 started
-&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to adopt a
-&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i think this
-&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave culture in
-&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split second of media
-&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not readily
-&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were forced to
-&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their place in the

Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
elbowed out.

I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
festival, and all the compromise that entails.

At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better music,
invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
and the best party you ever went to.

-&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to keep the
-&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on their part
-&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost and their
-&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with their
-&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really caught up in the
-&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the djs and the
-&e->croud became the afterthought.

Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
"conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.

-&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' apparently
-&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and   introducing
-&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its importance
-&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still talk trash
-&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to accept
-&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept it, they
-&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between what now
-&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not ashamed to admit
-&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i really like
-&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept, however
-&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i dislike
-&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of kids who run
-&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their drug
-&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant host to the
-&e->buggers.

Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:

They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).

They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).

They didn't give credit where it belonged.

-&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate yourself with
-&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so people
-&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim that
-&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a raver. and
-&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.

I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
there is a too far.

Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.

UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
all over Soma is too far.

Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
see drugs coming out the ass is too far.

Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.

Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).

Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.

I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.

There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
due.

andyw

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy
\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/
"Nothing real can defeat us.  Nothing unreal exists." - Buckaroo Banzai

Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

I've followed this thread with interest and I think there is passion and 
eloquence on both sides of the Skills issue.  As I recall, and correct me 
if I'm wrong, the Skills flier that initiated this trip down the synapses 
of ecstatic memories referred to a party thrown in 1999.

Now I know we are all somewhat familiar with the history of 
"raving."  Brits, acid house, late eighties -- emphasis on the 
latter.  Here in the Bay most of us thought the rave thingy was over by '94 
or '95. It seems to me, if my abused mind serves me still, that lots of 
green began to flow around the growing "business" of raving by then and 
that gold digging, for me at least, had nothing to do with the DYI ethic of 
free parties, "free techno," that defined the initial rave community.  In 
addition, there were no culture-defining accessories to be made or 
purchased -- candy, phat pants, electric flashers, etc. -- 
pre-mid-nineties.  No candy kids;  no epic trance;  no thousand peeps 
parties with $5.00 water, 4-color fliers, and costly tickets.  The late 
nineties in SF were defined by the arrival of lots of folks chasing golden 
rings and this was true  also of raves and EDM in general.

I preferred the early days.  Raw, anarchic, free...free.  Things, however, 
change and everything in this land of ours eventually comes with a 
price.  I like candy kids.  I have been to Skills parties and had a very 
good time.  But, as Jeno said:  "I loved the focus in the early days of 
Wicked on the pagan aspects of life. The natural cycles of the full moons, 
being out in nature, on the beach, free, alive, unbridled, wild and 
spontaneous. There is no club, party or other sound system that has ever 
achieved anything close to that..."  Yep.  Couldn't sell or buy that.

Love and Respect,

Apollo

>the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an

>influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
>elbowed out.
>
>I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
>of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
>to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
>it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
>this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
>Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
>on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
>imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
>completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
>having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
>but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
>festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>
>At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
>trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
>people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
>note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
>that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
>where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
>been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
>denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better music,
>invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
>massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
>to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
>of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
>between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
>swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
>and the best party you ever went to.
>
>-&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to 
>keep the
>-&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on 
>their part
>-&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost 
>and their
>-&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with their
>-&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really 
>caught up in the
>-&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the 
>djs and the
>-&e->croud became the afterthought.
>
>Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
>"conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>
>-&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' apparently
>-&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , 
>and   introducing
>-&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its 
>importance
>-&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still 
>talk trash
>-&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to 
>accept
>-&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept 
>it, they
>-&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between 
>what now
>-&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not 
>ashamed to admit
>-&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i 
>really like
>-&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept, 
>however
>-&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i dislike
>-&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of 
>kids who run
>-&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their drug
>-&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant 
>host to the
>-&e->buggers.
>
>Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
>self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>
>They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
>know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
>wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>
>They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
>events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>
>They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>
>-&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate 
>yourself with
>-&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so 
>people
>-&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim 
>that
>-&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a 
>raver. and
>-&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>
>I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
>than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
>there is a too far.
>
>Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>
>UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
>all over Soma is too far.
>
>Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
>see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>
>Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
>other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
>when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>
>Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
>just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
>Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>
>Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
>be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
>the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
>had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
>parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
>than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
>return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
>there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
>mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
>and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
>scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
>killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
>all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>
>I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
>I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
>greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
>
>There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
>don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
>raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
>it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
>first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
>due.
>
>andyw
>
>andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

bummed about the party

>

too
> -&e->short sighted to see that skills was founded on very hard work and
determination,
> -&e->and yes, the best techno & house in the bay. there's a certain
delerium
>
> Dude... I was there.  Remember, my name was on that flyer and stuff?
>
> Not how I remember it, and I know.  More like fast track emulation.
> Years prior, crews were doing this in the underground all over the
> country... and I was involved with Harmony, which had the blessing/curse
> of being a very hippie ethic'd crew with a more money/production oriented
> steering/funding comittee (in Greg, Joey and Diane).  You ask anybody that
> was hitting those parties back then...  Skillz was *never* underground,
> but saw the rapidly expanding Harmony making money after several years of
> organic growth from a South Bay candy raver crew of high school kids.
>
> Skills threw their first events at 2nd & Jackson after Harmony had done
> so, they were never really "an" underground.  They all but showed up and
> started throwing 1500+ person parties.  Used pretty much the same
> production contacts, and booked the same DJs as crews before them who had
> done it the long way...
>
> -&e->promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties.
these guys had it
> -&e->bad, but not in the sense that some do.   i'd say they even changed
how hand
> -&e->to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a
word when
>
> Again, not true.  There was a time before the term "street team" existed,
> where rude flyering was not of any benefit and it was more about
> community... you hand to handed good underground parties and people just
> sorta knew that it was of a similar ethic, a similar people.  CWP, FGE and
> all that existed, and those enormous sunshade flyers were a laughing stock
> as undergrounds grew in quality, frequency and capacity.
>
> -&e->handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up
hand, -give
> -&e->flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills
parties
> -&e->earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and
socialize with all
> -&e->the flyer recipients, the flyer was an afterthought. though i'd have
to say on
> -&e->an aside that the current street team that goes to the break in
warehouse party
> -&e->with a brick of banded flyers, hucking them on the nearest coffee
table and
> -&e->leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink.
>
> True dat.  But how many Skills flyers have I taken off my car?  How many
> placemat sized flyerbombings?  I don't know how you can say this except in
> the most idealistic reflections of thier first year doing events.  Only
> the first few Skills parties had flyers you could fit in a pocket.
>
> -&e->their early flyering methods were just an example of how they had
impacted
> -&e->the scene, their abiltiy to bring techno to the forefront of rave
massive
> -&e->culture hasn't been matched since.   in a matter of a period of 2
years, techno
> -&e->music went from hanging out in the basement of the acme gallery with
a Twist mural
> -&e->overhead to these big massives where techno music was accepted as
part of the
> -&e->norm and opened up alot of people to techno that normally wouldn't
have ever
> -&e->heard it.
>
> But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
> late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to catch
> up on what you missed :) ).  Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall techno
> talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was
> after the trance/cyber switch up)... their early model was based on low
> cost local DJs with more money spent on production.  Space Children,
> Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno
> (Cari Lekebush, Angel Alanis, Adam Beyer, Joel Mull, Joey Beltram,
> Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
> definition).
>
> -&e->i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/
> -&e->trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have
begun with
> -&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their
influence from F8 that
> -&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as
part of
> -&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de
rigueur in
> -&e->the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even
though URB
> -&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8
started
> -&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to
adopt a
> -&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i
think this
> -&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave
culture in
> -&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split
second of media
> -&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not
readily
> -&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were
forced to
> -&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their
place in the
>
> Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
> 2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
> got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
> DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
> shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
> skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
> last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
> was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
> the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
> understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
> influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
> elbowed out.
>
> I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
> of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
> to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
> it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
> this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
> Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
> on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
> imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
> completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
> having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
> but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
> festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>
> At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
> trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
> people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
> note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
> that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
> where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
> been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
> denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better music,
> invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
> massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
> to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
> of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
> between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
> swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
> and the best party you ever went to.
>
> -&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to
keep the
> -&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on
their part
> -&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost
and their
> -&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with
their
> -&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really
caught up in the
> -&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the
djs and the
> -&e->croud became the afterthought.
>
> Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
> "conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>
> -&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,'
apparently
> -&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and
introducing
> -&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its
importance
> -&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still

> -&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to
accept
> -&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept
it, they
> -&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between
what now
> -&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not
ashamed to admit
> -&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i
really like
> -&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept,
however
> -&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i
dislike
> -&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of
kids who run
> -&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their
drug
> -&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant
host to the
> -&e->buggers.
>
> Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
> self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>
> They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
> know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
> wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>
> They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
> events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>
> They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>
> -&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate
yourself with
> -&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so
people
> -&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim
that
> -&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a
raver. and
> -&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>
> I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
> than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
> there is a too far.
>
> Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>
> UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
> all over Soma is too far.
>
> Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
> see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>
> Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
> other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
> when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>
> Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
> just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
> Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>
> Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
> be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
> the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
> had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
> parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
> than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
> return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
> there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
> mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
> and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
> scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
> killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
> all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>
> I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
> I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
> greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
>
> There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
> don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
> raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
> it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
> first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
> due.

>
> On Sun, 16 Jan 2005 DISCONNECT4@aol.com wrote:
> -&e->i think it was radley that came up with the names on the flyer.. that
party
> -&e->brings alot back..
>
> Might have been Radley...
>
> -&e->early skills parties had a ton of heart. its very rare to have a
great first
> -&e->party and an awesome vibe and a massive cult following in the span of
a year
> -&e->and a half. the first skills party ended with such a positive note,
it kept tom
> -&e->& jason riding the crest of a wave until on or around their first
> -&e->bblgm-scifi. at their first event people were leaving and getting
bummed about the party
> -&e->being too short and there was one clique of candy kids hugging
goodbye and
> -&e->then another joined and soon more kids flocked to it faster than you
can spell
> -&e->katamari damaci. it was very inspiring and one of the most plur
affirming
> -&e->moments in SFR history, i've never seen anything like it since.
>
> Um...
>
> -&e-> alot of people like to talk smack about skills, but they are way
too
> -&e->short sighted to see that skills was founded on very hard work and
determination,
> -&e->and yes, the best techno & house in the bay. there's a certain
delerium
>
> Dude... I was there. Remember, my name was on that flyer and stuff?
>
> Not how I remember it, and I know. More like fast track emulation.
> Years prior, crews were doing this in the underground all over the
> country... and I was involved with Harmony, which had the blessing/curse
> of being a very hippie ethic'd crew with a more money/production oriented
> steering/funding comittee (in Greg, Joey and Diane). You ask anybody that
> was hitting those parties back then... Skillz was *never* underground,
> but saw the rapidly expanding Harmony making money after several years of
> organic growth from a South Bay candy raver crew of high school kids.
>
> Skills threw their first events at 2nd & Jackson after Harmony had done
> so, they were never really "an" underground. They all but showed up and
> started throwing 1500+ person parties. Used pretty much the same
> production contacts, and booked the same DJs as crews before them who had
> done it the long way...
>
> -&e->promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties.
these guys had it
> -&e->bad, but not in the sense that some do. i'd say they even changed
how hand
> -&e->to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a
word when
>
> Again, not true. There was a time before the term "street team" existed,
> where rude flyering was not of any benefit and it was more about
> community... you hand to handed good underground parties and people just
> sorta knew that it was of a similar ethic, a similar people. CWP, FGE and
> all that existed, and those enormous sunshade flyers were a laughing stock
> as undergrounds grew in quality, frequency and capacity.
>
> -&e->handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up
hand, -give
> -&e->flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills
parties
> -&e->earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and
socialize with all
> -&e->the flyer recipients, the flyer was an afterthought. though i'd have
to say on
> -&e->an aside that the current street team that goes to the break in
warehouse party
> -&e->with a brick of banded flyers, hucking them on the nearest coffee
table and
> -&e->leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink.
>
> True dat. But how many Skills flyers have I taken off my car? How many
> placemat sized flyerbombings? I don't know how you can say this except in
> the most idealistic reflections of thier first year doing events. Only
> the first few Skills parties had flyers you could fit in a pocket.
>
> -&e->their early flyering methods were just an example of how they had
impacted
> -&e->the scene, their abiltiy to bring techno to the forefront of rave
massive
> -&e->culture hasn't been matched since. in a matter of a period of 2
years, techno
> -&e->music went from hanging out in the basement of the acme gallery with
a Twist mural
> -&e->overhead to these big massives where techno music was accepted as
part of the
> -&e->norm and opened up alot of people to techno that normally wouldn't
have ever
> -&e->heard it.
>
> But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
> late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to catch
> up on what you missed :) ). Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall techno
> talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was
> after the trance/cyber switch up)... their early model was based on low
> cost local DJs with more money spent on production. Space Children,
> Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno
> (Cari Lekebush, Angel Alanis, Adam Beyer, Joel Mull, Joey Beltram,
> Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
> definition).
>
> -&e->i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/
> -&e->trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have
begun with
> -&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their
influence from F8 that
> -&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as
part of
> -&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de
rigueur in
> -&e->the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even
though URB
> -&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8
started
> -&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to
adopt a
> -&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i
think this
> -&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave
culture in
> -&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split
second of media
> -&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not
readily
> -&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were
forced to
> -&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their
place in the
>
> Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
> 2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
> got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
> DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more. A
> shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
> skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
> last at the ever obvious mix here point. Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
> was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
> the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
> understanding of energy flow and tension and release. We had a massive
> influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
> elbowed out.
>
> I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
> of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
> to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
> it's head into the popular culture. But Skills was not "affected" by
> this, they were PART of it. Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
> Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
> on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
> imaginary onset. And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
> completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
> having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
> but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
> festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>
> At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me. I just think
> trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
> people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
> note every 11 minutes sucks). And if it's about somehting bigger than
> that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
> where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
> been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
> denied harm reduction, etc. I could stay at home, listen to better music,
> invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
> massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
> to blame should the cops show up. That's not elitism, that's the concept
> of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
> between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
> swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
> and the best party you ever went to.
>
> -&e->scene. from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to
keep the
> -&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on
their part
> -&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost
and their
> -&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with
their
> -&e->audience. but i also think that after a fashion they got really
caught up in the
> -&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the
djs and the
> -&e->croud became the afterthought.
>
> Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
> "conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>
> -&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,'
apparently
> -&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and
introducing
> -&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its
importance
> -&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still
talk trash
> -&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to
accept
> -&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept
it, they
> -&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between
what now
> -&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not
ashamed to admit
> -&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i
really like
> -&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept,
however
> -&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i
dislike
> -&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of
kids who run
> -&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their
drug
> -&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant
host to the
> -&e->buggers.
>
> Well, I love music. And I love music being an honest extension of one's
> self. I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>
> They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
> know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
> wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>
> They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
> events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>
> They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>
> -&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate
yourself with
> -&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so
people
> -&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim
that
> -&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a
raver. and
> -&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>
> I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
> than what you are. But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
> there is a too far.
>
> Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>
> UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
> all over Soma is too far.
>
> Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
> see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>
> Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
> other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
> when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>
> Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
> just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
> Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>
> Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
> be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
> the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
> had risen up from the UG before them at best). I've played free for more
> parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
> than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
> return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
> there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
> mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
> and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
> scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
> killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
> all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>
> I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
> I can say. They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
> greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
>
> There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
> don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
> raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
> it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
> first started out. Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
> due.
>
> andyw
>
> andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy
