Dude... I was there.  Remember, my name was on that flyer and stuff?


so was i..that was my pioneer mixer.


> Not how I remember it, and I know.  More like fast track emulation.
> Years prior, crews were doing this in the underground all over the
> country... and I was involved with Harmony, which had the blessing/curse
> of being a very hippie ethic'd crew with a more money/production oriented
> steering/funding comittee (in Greg, Joey and Diane).  You ask anybody that
> was hitting those parties back then...  Skillz was *never* underground,
> but saw the rapidly expanding Harmony making money after several years of
> organic growth from a South Bay candy raver crew of high school kids.
> 

i totally agree, i'm not sure if i said skills was underground, don't think i 
did. sorry if i implied it. i think what i was getting at was that skills, 
regardless of the position it stood, was still a rave outfit and loosely defined 
as a rave. i guess there was more of a difference between the originators of 
the scene who chose to remain underground and the next generation. undeniably 
there were the original heads still doing their thing, and skills certainly 
took the best aspects of their events or the most profitable ones. you still 
have to credit skills for making the raves that were on the commercial front more 
streamlined and influencing the entire next generation. not saying that's a 
good thing. i actually enjoyed going to raves more where there was at least one 
dog, a naked guy, anime looped visuals, batik buddha banners, and dj dan's 
loose caboose was played inadvertantly three times in a night.


> Skills threw their first events at 2nd & Jackson after Harmony had done
> so, they were never really "an" underground.  They all but showed up and
> started throwing 1500+ person parties.  Used pretty much the same
> production contacts, and booked the same DJs as crews before them who had
> done it the long way...
> 

maritime was before but it's inconsequential, they're not underground either. 
 yr right though, it sucks that the people that popularize anything in this 
world, always get the credit.


> -&e->promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties. 
> these guys had it
> -&e->bad, but not in the sense that some do.   i'd say they even changed how 
> hand
> -&e->to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a word 
> when
> 
> Again, not true.  There was a time before the term "street team" existed,
> where rude flyering was not of any benefit and it was more about
> community... you hand to handed good underground parties and people just
> sorta knew that it was of a similar ethic, a similar people.  CWP, FGE and
> all that existed, and those enormous sunshade flyers were a laughing stock
> as undergrounds grew in quality, frequency and capacity.
> 

i agree.. i should have said that in my experience i saw skills adapt a 
common practice among their predecessors and influenced current massive culture.  
although the rude flyering and decopage-ing of entire cars is on the rise 
again. 


> -&e->handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up hand, 
> -give
> -&e->flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills 
> parties
> -&e->earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and socialize 
> with all
> -&e->the flyer recipients, the flyer was an afterthought. though i'd have to 
> say on
> -&e->an aside that the current street team that goes to the break in 
> warehouse party
> -&e->with a brick of banded flyers, hucking them on the nearest coffee table 
> and
> -&e->leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink.
> 
> True dat.  But how many Skills flyers have I taken off my car?  How many
> placemat sized flyerbombings?  I don't know how you can say this except in
> the most idealistic reflections of thier first year doing events.  Only
> the first few Skills parties had flyers you could fit in a pocket.
> 

i think this had alot to do with elemental leaving the outfit. also the 
smaller flyers were more economic. i think that alot of younger ravers who aren't 
too tuned in yet like to see bigger more over the top flyers because it makes 
the whole idea of going to a rave more fantastic and exciting to them.. i'd 
assume that if you were a promoter marketing to a younger crowd eventually you'd 
succome to that aspect yourself and identify with your attendees. the whole 
idea of flyers being as big as maps and dissentegrating like toilet paper on a 
rave floor to me is vile. but i can identify a little because if there's any 
way to make your flyers cheaper and generate the maximum amount of hype, a 
promoters first tendency is to go for it. but there's always the questions of 
class, style, & decency to take in account. if yr going to do a great party and 
have the money, do something that will really be memorable and is really 
original. 


> 
> 
> But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
> late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to catch
> up on what you missed :) ).

yep, i'm definitley not a johnny come lately newbe fascist though. `;) it's 
funny how in the massive / trance circuit, if you've been going to parties for 
3 years yr oldschool and if you've been going to them for 10 or so in the 
techno scene yr still a new comer. haha. `;) 

  Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall techno
> 
> talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was
> after the trance/cyber switch up)... their early model was based on low
> cost local DJs with more money spent on production.  Space Children,
> Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno
> (Cari Lekebush, Angel Alanis, Adam Beyer, Joel Mull, Joey Beltram,
> Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
> definition).
> 

skills was definitely trying to keep the pace though. i guess i should 
retract quite a bit what i said and toss it to harmony. i think harmony, besides the 
area 51 event was the only crew i've seen pull together and keep an entire 
warehouse room filled with candy kids dancing to techno. i must say though the 
area 51 party was very inspiring. it would be pretty hard to repeat that 
success currently. 

> Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
> 2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
> got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
> DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
> shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
> skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
> last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
> was playing DJ Dan style, 

and Jason sounded like well... me, 

(dude that's so andy)

they lacked
> 
> the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
> understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
> influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
> elbowed out.
> 
i concur also what i was really getting at with my first post was that their 
first parties were a success that influenced their generation, and although it 
turned out negative in the end, you can't deny their impact. if you go to any 
other event now that is massive in style now they look like skills events. 
sure i agree that trance makes a ropey mixer sound great but i also think that's 
what guaranteed their commercial success. not that commercial success equates 
success by any means.


> At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
> trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
> people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
> note every 11 minutes sucks). 
> 
> Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
> self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
> 
> They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
> know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
> wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
> 
> They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
> events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
> 
> They didn't give credit where it belonged.
> 


> I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
> than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
> there is a too far.
> 
> Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
> 
> UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
> all over Soma is too far.
> 
> Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
> see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
> 
> Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
> other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
> when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
> 
> Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
> just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
> Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
> 
> I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
> I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
> greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
> 
> There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
> don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
> raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
> it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
> first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
> due.
> 
> andyw


i'm not aligning myself with skills or anybody here on this. everything 
you've said has been right on and i was wrong about a few things. but there are 
real people behind any crew and they have their reasons. i think that as a person 
as well as a raver (dare i mention the term), you should try to identify. but 
if some person in your scene is gone astray, try to educate and encourage 
unity with them. but i also think that if they don't listen or don't care, go out 
there and show and prove. be the example and make the path for others to 
follow. i really think friends and family and moksha tribe have shown this to be 
true. i feel totally positive about what they are doing to make the bay area 
rave scene the best its been since i've had the pleasure to know it.

there hasn't been a person on this list who hasn't been alienated by the 
whole bay area massives concept including myself. there are even alot of people in 
the 'former skills crew' club who when you mention skills to them they have a 
distressed frown.  `;)  but its time people got over it already.not only 
because its petty but because, the massive itself seems to be fading out (though i 
might b wrong) 
       the next wave of kids that are throwing parties now are doing it 
smaller and with more unknown talented acts. the emphasis of their parties relies 
on their enthusiasm to make a rave come alive more than to make money. if the 
elder scene members give an example of what raves are all about as well as 
embrace the new generation there's nothing but good that can come of it. if 
everybody gives off the oldschooler cliche, "ah raves aren't what they used to be" 
then doesn't do anything, that's like shooting yourself in the foot. i should 
make clear though that's not directed to andy but everybody who's ever griped 
or made fun of massives and the naive kids that go to them. personally i think 
andy rocks, is a solid dj with a very unique style, and been known to blush 
like a schoolgirl if you give him a compliment. lol JK `;P `;)

peace & utmost respect to andy and anybody who's had the patience to sit 
through the ranting.


++spects++
-Sean Ocean-

>-&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their

>-&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as

>-&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de

>-&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8 
>started
>-&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to 
>adopt a
>-&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i 
>think this
>-&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave 
>culture in
>-&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split 
>second of media
>-&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not 
>readily
>-&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were forced 
>to
>-&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their 
>place in the
>
>Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
>2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
>got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
>DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
>shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
>skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
>last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
>was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
>the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
>understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
>influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
>elbowed out.
>
>I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
>of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
>to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
>it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
>this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
>Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
>on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
>imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
>completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
>having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
>but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
>festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>
>At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
>trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
>people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
>note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
>that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
>where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
>been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
>denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better music,
>invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
>massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
>to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
>of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
>between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
>swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
>and the best party you ever went to.
>
>-&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to keep 
>the
>-&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on 
>their part
>-&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost 
>and their
>-&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with their
>-&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really 
>caught up in the
>-&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the 
>djs and the
>-&e->croud became the afterthought.
>
>Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
>"conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>
>-&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' 
>apparently
>-&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and   
>introducing
>-&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its 
>importance
>-&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still 
>talk trash
>-&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to 
>accept
>-&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept 
>it, they
>-&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between 
>what now
>-&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not 
>ashamed to admit
>-&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i 
>really like
>-&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept, 
>however
>-&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i 
>dislike
>-&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of kids 
>who run
>-&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their 
>drug
>-&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant 
>host to the
>-&e->buggers.
>
>Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
>self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>
>They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
>know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
>wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>
>They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
>events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>
>They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>
>-&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate 
>yourself with
>-&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so 
>people
>-&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim 
>that
>-&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a 
>raver. and
>-&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>
>I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
>than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
>there is a too far.
>
>Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>
>UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
>all over Soma is too far.
>
>Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
>see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>
>Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
>other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
>when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>
>Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
>just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
>Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>
>Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
>be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
>the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
>had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
>parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
>than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
>return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
>there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
>mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
>and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
>scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
>killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
>all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>
>I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
>I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as

>
>There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please

>raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Getting out of jury duty...

So yeah, I know this is so TOTALLY nrr; but I'm kind of out of ideas 
here.  Our city's resident pack of slimy ambulence-chasers have decided 
to screw up my day tomorrow (Actually, my whole week; but tomorrow's 
when I actually have to go into the court.) by summoning me for jury 
duty.  And I was wondering if anyone here has any effective tips on how 
to get out of it?

The thing is, it appears from the summons information that it's for a 
civil court, not a criminal one; so everything that's successfully 
enabled me to dodge the bullet in the past is pretty much useless this 
time around.  And it's definitely too late to quit bathing long enough 
to build up a smell that'd set me free, or the other obvious escape 
routes.

I'm here in The City itself, if that matters versus other parts of the 
bay.

Any suggestions?

Well if you are a contributing citizen not just a leech, and you want to
make sure that what you call "Ambulance Chasers" don't get away with what I
am assuming you are saying are frivolous lawsuits.... Then it's even more of
a reason for you to sit on the jury. Be an active part of the positive
change, rather than bitching about the way things are.....

In my daughters lawsuit........ When she was 4 months old and was SEVERLY
burned and in the hospital for a week in the intensive care burn unit, and
the store that was at fault would not pay the $30k+ hospital bill for the
overheated soup that was spilled on my little princess at their store...... 

We had no other choice but to sue! That's why the system is in place! So for
people that have gone threw what we have, PARTICIPATE. I have sat on a jury,
it was a wonderful experience and I learned allot, maybe you will too!

Pronunciation: 't=E4-l&
Function: noun
Etymology: Sanskrit tAla, literally, hand-clapping
: one of the ancient traditional rhythmic patterns of Indian music --
compare RAGA

>> Dude... I was there.  Remember, my name was on that flyer and stuff?
>> 
>> Not how I remember it, and I know.  More like fast track emulation.
>> Years prior, crews were doing this in the underground all over the
>> country... and I was involved with Harmony, which had the blessing/curse
>> of being a very hippie ethic'd crew with a more money/production oriented
>> steering/funding comittee (in Greg, Joey and Diane).  You ask anybody that
>> was hitting those parties back then...  Skillz was *never* underground,
>> but saw the rapidly expanding Harmony making money after several years of
>> organic growth from a South Bay candy raver crew of high school kids.
>> 
>> Skills threw their first events at 2nd & Jackson after Harmony had done
>> so, they were never really "an" underground.  They all but showed up and
>> started throwing 1500+ person parties.  Used pretty much the same
>> production contacts, and booked the same DJs as crews before them who had
>> done it the long way...
>> 
>> -&e->promoters get when they are passing out flyers for their parties.

>> -&e->bad, but not in the sense that some do.   i'd say they even changed 
>> how hand
>> -&e->to hand flyering is executed today. people used to not ever say a word 
>> when
>> 
>> Again, not true.  There was a time before the term "street team" existed,
>> where rude flyering was not of any benefit and it was more about
>> community... you hand to handed good underground parties and people just
>> sorta knew that it was of a similar ethic, a similar people.  CWP, FGE and
>> all that existed, and those enormous sunshade flyers were a laughing stock
>> as undergrounds grew in quality, frequency and capacity.
>> 
>> -&e->handing out flyers, stone cold frankenstein demeanor... hold up hand,

>> -&e->flyer.hold up hand, -give flyer.repeat.. the kids that flyered skills

>> -&e->earliest on were encouraged to foster a friendly persona and socialize

>> warehouse party

>> -&e->leaving is a disservice + waste of paper & ink.
>> 
>> True dat.  But how many Skills flyers have I taken off my car?  How many
>> placemat sized flyerbombings?  I don't know how you can say this except in
>> the most idealistic reflections of thier first year doing events.  Only
>> the first few Skills parties had flyers you could fit in a pocket.
>> 
>> -&e->their early flyering methods were just an example of how they had 
>> impacted
>> -&e->the scene, their abiltiy to bring techno to the forefront of rave 
>> massive
>> -&e->culture hasn't been matched since.   in a matter of a period of 2 
>> years, techno
>> -&e->music went from hanging out in the basement of the acme gallery with a 
>> Twist mural
>> -&e->overhead to these big massives where techno music was accepted as part 
>> of the
>> -&e->norm and opened up alot of people to techno that normally wouldn't 
>> have ever
>> -&e->heard it.
>> 
>> But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
>> late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to catch
>> up on what you missed :) ).  Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall techno
>> talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was
>> after the trance/cyber switch up)... their early model was based on low
>> cost local DJs with more money spent on production.  Space Children,
>> Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno
>> (Cari Lekebush, Angel Alanis, Adam Beyer, Joel Mull, Joey Beltram,
>> Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
>> definition).
>> 
>> -&e->i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/
>> -&e->trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have 
>> begun with
>> -&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their 
>> influence from F8 that
>> -&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being as 
>> part of
>> -&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de 
>> rigueur in
>> -&e->the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even 
>> though URB
>> -&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years, F8 
>> started
>> -&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting to 
>> adopt a
>> -&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i 
>> think this
>> -&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave 
>> culture in
>> -&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split 
>> second of media
>> -&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not 
>> readily
>> -&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were forced 
>> to
>> -&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep their 
>> place in the
>> 
>> Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out throwing
>> 2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
>> got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
>> DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
>> shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
>> skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
>> last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
>> was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
>> the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
>> understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
>> influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
>> elbowed out.
>> 
>> I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
>> of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
>> to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking up
>> it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
>> this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that Tori
>> Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
>> on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
>> imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
>> completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
>> having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
>> but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
>> festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>> 
>> At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
>> trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
>> people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
>> note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
>> that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
>> where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
>> been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
>> denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better music,
>> invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
>> massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only myself
>> to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
>> of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
>> between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
>> swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
>> and the best party you ever went to.
>> 
>> -&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to keep 
>> the
>> -&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on 
>> their part
>> -&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost 
>> and their
>> -&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with their
>> -&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really 
>> caught up in the
>> -&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the 
>> djs and the
>> -&e->croud became the afterthought.
>> 
>> Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
>> "conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>> 
>> -&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' 
>> apparently
>> -&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and 
>> introducing
>> -&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its 
>> importance
>> -&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still 
>> talk trash
>> -&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have to 
>> accept
>> -&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot accept 
>> it, they
>> -&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between 
>> what now
>> -&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not 
>> ashamed to admit
>> -&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i 
>> really like
>> -&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept, 
>> however
>> -&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i 
>> dislike
>> -&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of kids 
>> who run
>> -&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their 
>> drug
>> -&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant 
>> host to the
>> -&e->buggers.
>> 
>> Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
>> self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>> 
>> They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
>> know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
>> wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>> 
>> They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
>> events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>> 
>> They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>> 
>> -&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate 
>> yourself with
>> -&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc.. so 
>> people
>> -&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who claim 
>> that
>> -&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a 
>> raver. and
>> -&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>> 
>> I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to accept
>> than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
>> there is a too far.
>> 
>> Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>> 
>> UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
>> all over Soma is too far.
>> 
>> Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
>> see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>> 
>> Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
>> other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
>> when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>> 
>> Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others is
>> just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups like
>> Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>> 
>> Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
>> be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong (esp
>> the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
>> had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
>> parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
>> than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
>> return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
>> there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are not
>> mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
>> and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
>> scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
>> killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can go
>> all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>> 
>> I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about all
>> I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
>> greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
>> 
>> There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
>> don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
>> raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
>> it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
>> first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit is
>> due.
>> 
>> andyw
>>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR:  Getting out of jury duty...

Heh... you seem to have been right.

The first line of questions, by the judge actually, was a sort of basic 
"who are you" list of stuff like "what part of SF do you live in?", 
"for how long?", "married/single/divorced", etc.; along with "what is 
your educational background?".

The fact that I answered, to the last: "BS in Computer Science", (Not 
that I get to USE it in my current "survival" job.) actually DID seem 
to torque off both lawyers enough that they questioned me about it 
later on.  Though I got off light compared to this one lady.  She, 
having gone through law school, passed the bar, practiced law for a 
while, and not having found that challenging enough; had actually gone 
back to MEDICAL school, and is now a practicing MD!  Now THAT's 
hardcore!  She REALLY got the third degree during the selection 
questions; especially as it was a personal injury case.  Oddly enough, 
she wasn't the first one booted off.  And I thought, for sure, that she 
was WAY too educated and intelligent to pass muster.

I was the third though.  The plaintiff's lawyer didn't particularly 
like my answers.  And I wasn't even trying at that point; having pretty 
much resigned myself to being stuck in the situation.  I guess I'm just 
naturally too ornery and opinionated to make a good jurist.  No 
complaints on that count though.

So, it appears I've dodged the bullet this time around.


cya,
john

>> -&e->heard it.
>> 
>> But it had been matched prior, and you're dating yourself prety bad as a
>> late arrival (nothing wrong with that, except that it's important to
catch
>> up on what you missed :) ).  Skills NEVER brought balls to the wall
techno
>> talent to the Bay (they did start bringing in bigger names, but this was

>> cost local DJs with more money spent on production.  Space Children,
>> Harmony, and Area51 _did_ bring out bigger names that were proper techno

>> Christian Smith, Laidback Luke, Juan Atkins... techno by any true heads'
>> definition).

>> -&e->i think that alot of the rift that developed between the oldshool/
>> -&e->trueschool/SFR/scenester crowd and the massive newbe sect might have

>> begun with
>> -&e->cyberfest originally, but it might have been skills with their 
>> influence from F8 that
>> -&e->cinched it off. coolworld prod. was still quasi construed as being
as 
>> part of
>> -&e->the old guard as their huge massive styled events were almost de

>> -&e->the early-mid 90s, so it shouldn't be totally theirs to blame (even 
>> though URB
>> -&e->magazine recently said the last coolworld sucked). in later years,
F8 
>> started
>> -&e->to take on & influence skills,while the skills heads were starting
to 
>> adopt a
>> -&e->promoting style similar to the LA massives they were raised on. i 
>> think this
>> -&e->drew in alot more people who were unfamiliar with the whole rave 
>> culture in
>> -&e->general and were on the bandwagon of hype generated from the split 
>> second of media
>> -&e->history when 'electronica' was cool. so alot of people found the not

>> readily
>> -&e->acceptible forms of house and techno abrasive and dull and were
forced 
>> to
>> -&e->change their focus to an easier to digest trance format to keep
their 
>> place in the
>> 
>> Or... maybe the crowds were liking it just fine, and starting out
throwing
>> 2000ish person parties could have been enough... but then Jason and Tom
>> got to working behind the register at F8 and saw something interesting...
>> DJs bought more cybertrance than anyhting because it changed up more.  A
>> shittier DJ could still keep the interest of a crowd with little or no
>> skill, barely mixing the fronts of the next record to the backs of the
>> last at the ever obvious mix here point.  Sorry, but even when Tom Slik
>> was playing DJ Dan style, and Jason sounded like well... me, they lacked
>> the kind of thunder you hear from a veteran party rocker, they lacked an
>> understanding of energy flow and tension and release.  We had a massive
>> influx of so-so DJs clogging the pipes, while seriously wicked DJs were
>> elbowed out.
>> 
>> I think trance happened to be very compatible with E and a massive influx
>> of newbies who came partially by whatever reasons brought any music lover
>> to the scene, but also a massive rising trend as electronica was poking
up
>> it's head into the popular culture.  But Skills was not "affected" by
>> this, they were PART of it.  Before Skills' first party remember that
Tori
>> Amos' Professional Widow rmx, Underworld, Sneaker Pimps, Orbital were all
>> on the global and national scene... they came on at the peak, not at some
>> imaginary onset.  And where Skills succeeded, and others failed, was to
>> completely burn all bridges to this ever having been about freedom, ever
>> having been illegal... Skills was one of the latest arrivals on the scene
>> but first ones in the charge to bridge the gap from rave to music
>> festival, and all the compromise that entails.
>> 
>> At that point, if it's all about the music, they lost me.  I just think
>> trance and NRG suck, they are a diss to DJing as an artform the way most
>> people play it (the same way I'd think a pianist who only played a new
>> note every 11 minutes sucks).  And if it's about somehting bigger than
>> that, like maybe proving to people that we can love each other in a place
>> where we are free to be ourselves... well, hard to be myself when I've
>> been charged to stay alive (water) and violated (excessive search) and
>> denied harm reduction, etc.  I could stay at home, listen to better
music,
>> invite some friends I like a lot more than some of the assholes I see at
>> massives, and bring all the drugs I want through the door with only
myself
>> to blame should the cops show up.  That's not elitism, that's the concept
>> of personal liberty that holds up the roof on my TAZ... the difference
>> between 1015 (where despite totally violating searches, I keep seeing
>> swarms of retards giving each pother backrubs and people getting jumped)
>> and the best party you ever went to.
>> 
>> -&e->scene.   from a dj's perspective it's necessary above all else to
keep 
>> the
>> -&e->crowd happy ,and i think that it wasn't a planned strategic move on 
>> their part
>> -&e->to just start playing trance. the skills crew were/are djs foremost 
>> and their
>> -&e->love of their musik stemmed mostly from how they interacted with
their
>> -&e->audience.   but i also think that after a fashion they got really 
>> caught up in the
>> -&e->whole dj thing that their massives started becoming parties for the 
>> djs and the
>> -&e->croud became the afterthought.
>> 
>> Um, F8 was the template for the music, and that ugly ugly cliche of
>> "conducting" the crowd over cheese ass breakdowns, etc.
>> 
>> -&e->the whole image of skills 'not staying true to their music,' 
>> apparently
>> -&e->disregarding their principals of expected rave cultural values , and

>> introducing
>> -&e->inexperienced newbes to a scene without an understanding of its 
>> importance
>> -&e->didn't really settle in with the rest of the scene. and people still

>> talk trash
>> -&e->about skills, f8, bayraves etc. but i think that people still have
to 
>> accept
>> -&e->the changes to their scene and if they don't like it or cannot
accept 
>> it, they
>> -&e->should try to change, educate, or try to improve the bonds between 
>> what now
>> -&e->seems like a dissentigrating and fractured rave scene. i am not 
>> ashamed to admit
>> -&e->it, i like candy kids, especially ones who dress like that 24/7. i 
>> really like
>> -&e->a well done massive despite who or what is playing. i cannot accept,

>> however
>> -&e->anyone who disses another person to make themself look better. i 
>> dislike
>> -&e->anyone who can't deal with change. i can't stand the ignorance of
kids 
>> who run
>> -&e->around acting like ravers for a year and getting burnt out on their 
>> drug
>> -&e->consumption without the knowledge of the scene that plays reluctant 
>> host to the
>> -&e->buggers.
>> 
>> Well, I love music.  And I love music being an honest extension of one's
>> self.  I never had a problem with anybody in the rave scene until:
>> 
>> They were fake (maybe one day I'll wake up loving epic trance, but you
>> know what... if I was working the cash register at F8 when it happened, I
>> wouldn't expect many people to understand my reasons past what they saw).
>> 
>> They put others at risk (not having free water at $20 over capacity
>> events at 2nd and jackson when it cost around $.10 a bottle in bulk).
>> 
>> They didn't give credit where it belonged.
>> 
>> -&e->guess bottom line is, if you read these threads, you associate 
>> yourself with
>> -&e->the rave aesthetics of open mindedness peace & understanding etc..
so 
>> people
>> -&e->should at least start trying to follow it. even when people who
claim 
>> that
>> -&e->another raver is less of a raver they themselves become less of a 
>> raver. and
>> -&e->anyway that's a punk aesthetic not rave.
>> 
>> I really think the rave ethic is more about what you are willing to
accept
>> than what you are.  But again, there are lines that have been crossed,
>> there is a too far.
>> 
>> Packing 2500 people into 2nd and Jackson is too far.
>> 
>> UV coated flyers that measure 8 x 25 unfolded strewn all over back alleys
>> all over Soma is too far.
>> 
>> Flyering high schools for parties where you KNOW DAMN WELL you're gonna
>> see drugs coming out the ass is too far.
>> 
>> Contributing to a musical creativity deadlock circle jerk where you and 4
>> other promoters keep booking the same 6 DJs for every party is too far
>> when there are hundreds of DJs worthy of being booked.
>> 
>> Trying to build a for profit enterprise on the volunteer work of others
is
>> just janky (not so much a Skills comment as it is a comment on groups
like
>> Vorg trying to gank the SFRaves name and shit like that).
>> 
>> Sean, I hear you, I respect you, but I know some of the things you say to
>> be at least substantially up to interpretation if not downright wrong
(esp
>> the stuff about Skills being pioneers, they were a hybrid of crews that
>> had risen up from the UG before them at best).  I've played free for more
>> parties than most djs have played, I've done free sound for more parties
>> than a lot of the people on this list have been to, and all I ask in
>> return is to give what I learned when I came to this a chance... that
>> there are wrong ways of doing it, that there need to be lines that are
not
>> mutable, that every promoter needs to throw parties that they would go to
>> and never make a seperation between the promoter, the crew, the dj, the
>> scenester and the newbie in terms of what they deserve besides a night of
>> killer music, a reasonable effort to make it a safe place where you can
go
>> all night, and some people that want to be there as much as you do.
>> 
>> I'd say Skills is better than most massive promoters, but that's about
all
>> I can say.  They do good sound, they do good lights, and they aren't as
>> greedy or lame as some... but they're no UG either.
>> 
>> There has been some massive techno coming out of the Bay Area, please
>> don't give Skills the credit for having the integrity and supreme
>> raverness to invent, preserve or present a stage for it... cause well,
>> it's just not true besides booking some Harmony and Mhz guys when they
>> first started out.  Not trying to be divisive, just credit where credit
is
>> due.
>>

Subject: [sfraves] Pick your Poison and Pick your game

What do you perfer to drink?  What are some of the drinking games you
or your friends play?  What are some drinking games you've made up?

I love to drink just about anything, so long as it's mixed decently. 
I try to stay away from vodka (it tastes like death).  I used to be on
a big whiskey kick, but i recently switched to rum.  *The Great and
Almighty Computerus* has gotten me to start enjoying Gin and Tonics, i
hated them for a long time, cause they tasted like pine needles, but i
guess same thing happened with beer, i didnt like how it tasted, but i
kept drinking it anyway, and now i actually enjoy the taste.  And
those of you who know me, know i'm generally never with out a 40 of
something (usually Mickeys, but there an occasional 211, or Ol E) in
my hand.  i figure 40's are good ways to start the night off, takes
the edge of and prepares your stomach for whatever else ends up in the
by the end of the night.

ERF (Egyptian Rat Fuck) - Take a couple of decks of cards, depending
on how many players.  Shuffle them up, deal them all out.  It's kinda
like war, i'm sure everyone here's played this game.  The drinking
twist, when you lay down a face card and the other person cannot beat
that card in the required number of cards, they drink for however many
seconds the number is on the card.  in the case of 2 cards being laid
down that are of the same value, the slapper is the only one who
doesnt drink, the rest do for how ever many seconds the number on the
card is.

Some friends and I figured out how to play baseball in a garage and
turn it into a drinking game but i cant remember for the life of me
what the rules were.  i think it was kinda like kegball, seems rather
logical.  Playing baseball in a 2 car garage is a good way to get
hurt.

New One i made up the other week.

Running with the Bulls - The goal is to drink 10 22's of Shlitz malt
liquor in an hour.
-- 
Chester Copperpot

"Goonies never say die!"
"Meth Monsters are my Anti-Drug"
"I feel like I'm taking crazy pills"

Subject: [sfraves] [BSP] Mon 1/24 - Meet Grand Wizard Theodore, inventor of scratching

NorCalDJMPA presents...
Meet Grand Wizard Theodore

Inventor of Scratching to Give Demonstration at NorCal DJ and Music
Production Academy

Grand Wizard Theodore, the inventor of scratching, will appear at the
NorCal DJ and Music Production Academy to give a demonstration on the
evening of Monday, January 24, at 7:30 p.m.

In 1975, Grand Wizard Theodore invented scratching, the fundamental DJ
technique of rhythmically moving a record back and forth, which is one of
the most recognizable aspects of DJing.  Theodore is generally
acknowledged as a pioneering hip-hop DJ, along with the legendary DJs Kool
Herc, Grandmaster Flash, and Afrika Bambaataa.  His demonstration on
Monday will be given during the last half hour of NorCalDJMPAs DJ101:
Turntable Basics for the Art of DJing course.

Please contact the NorCalDJMPA to attend, or for more information on the
event.  Free and open to the public.

NorCalDJMPA
600 Townsend St, Suite 190W, SF

http://www.norcaldjmpa.com
info@norcaldjmpa.com
415-278-0813

About the NorCalDJMPA:

The NorCal DJ and Music Production Academy, located in the heart of San
Francisco, provides professional, personalized instruction in a
comfortable environment for those who want to master the art of DJing and
Electronic Music Production.

The NorCalDJMPA was founded by an experienced team of DJs and music
production veterans from across all genres and scenes including champion
turntablists, internationally touring techno DJs and producers with dozens
of successful releases.  NorCalDJMPA provides quality instruction in DJing
and music production in an academic and professional environment
unparalleled by any other school of its type.

> like war, i'm sure everyone here's played this game.
>  The drinking
> twist, when you lay down a face card and the other
> person cannot beat
> that card in the required number of cards, they
> drink for however many
> seconds the number is on the card.  in the case of 2
> cards being laid
> down that are of the same value, the slapper is the
> only one who
> doesnt drink, the rest do for how ever many seconds
> the number on the
> card is.
> 
> Some friends and I figured out how to play baseball
> in a garage and
> turn it into a drinking game but i cant remember for
> the life of me
> what the rules were.  i think it was kinda like
> kegball, seems rather
> logical.  Playing baseball in a 2 car garage is a
> good way to get
> hurt.
> 
> New One i made up the other week.
> 
> Running with the Bulls - The goal is to drink 10
> 22's of Shlitz malt
> liquor in an hour.

Poison ---> Jagermeister

Game --->  Ok this will totally reveal me for the nerd
I am, but back in my undergrad days me and friends
came up with a big sheet of character events for
drinking to Star Trek .... so let's say one day my
character was Spok, I'd have to take a shot everytime
he said the word illogical, but might get stuck taking
four shots if I get the rare episode where he shows
emotion.  No matter what character you got though,
everyone was pretty much smashed by the end of a
couple of episodes.


Biggum Nerdy Dork,
Penny

--- Chester Copperpot <chester.copperpot420@gmail.com>
wrote:

> What do you perfer to drink?  What are some of the
> drinking games you
> or your friends play?  What are some drinking games
> you've made up?
> 
> I love to drink just about anything, so long as it's
> mixed decently. 
> I try to stay away from vodka (it tastes like
> death).  I used to be on
> a big whiskey kick, but i recently switched to rum. 
> *The Great and
> Almighty Computerus* has gotten me to start enjoying
> Gin and Tonics, i
> hated them for a long time, cause they tasted like
> pine needles, but i
> guess same thing happened with beer, i didnt like
> how it tasted, but i
> kept drinking it anyway, and now i actually enjoy
> the taste.  And
> those of you who know me, know i'm generally never
> with out a 40 of
> something (usually Mickeys, but there an occasional
> 211, or Ol E) in
> my hand.  i figure 40's are good ways to start the
> night off, takes
> the edge of and prepares your stomach for whatever
> else ends up in the
> by the end of the night.
> 
> ERF (Egyptian Rat Fuck) - Take a couple of decks of
> cards, depending
> on how many players.  Shuffle them up, deal them all
> out.  It's kinda
> like war, i'm sure everyone here's played this game.
>  The drinking
> twist, when you lay down a face card and the other
> person cannot beat
> that card in the required number of cards, they
> drink for however many
> seconds the number is on the card.  in the case of 2
> cards being laid
> down that are of the same value, the slapper is the
> only one who
> doesnt drink, the rest do for how ever many seconds
> the number on the
> card is.
> 
> Some friends and I figured out how to play baseball
> in a garage and
> turn it into a drinking game but i cant remember for
> the life of me
> what the rules were.  i think it was kinda like
> kegball, seems rather
> logical.  Playing baseball in a 2 car garage is a
> good way to get
> hurt.
> 
> New One i made up the other week.
> 
> Running with the Bulls - The goal is to drink 10
> 22's of Shlitz malt
> liquor in an hour.
> -- 
> Chester Copperpot

Subject: Re: [sfraves] just got the mac mini

Apparently, according to the experts (i.e. George), the Logic nodes
don't do real-time processing, so the lack of Gig might not be such a
bottleneck, especially considering the 167 Mhz FSB and fairly
inadequate cache on the Mini.  That said, I'd really like to see
someone come up with a USB 2.0 / Firewire Gig Ethernet adapter for the
Mac; my 12" G4 lappy is similarly lacking Gig, and spending 40 minutes
copying my iTunes library is a giant PITA.  Even though it wouldn't
run at line speed, the 4x improvement over Fast Ethernet would be well
worth it, IMHO.

Now if we could just get Chairman Steve to release a Logic node daemon
for Darwin / FreeBSD, we'd be _all_ set.

-- Jonathan

NorCal DJ and Music Production Academy to give a demonstration on the=20
evening of Monday, January 24, at 7:30 p.m.

In 1975, Grand Wizard Theodore invented scratching, the fundamental DJ=20
technique of rhythmically moving a record back and forth which is one of=20
the most recognizable aspects of DJing. Theodore is generally acknowledged=
=20
as a pioneering hip-hop DJ, along with the legendary DJs Kool Herc,=20
Grandmaster Flash, and Afrika Bambaataa. His demonstration on Monday will=
=20
be given during the NorCalDJMPA~Rs DJ101: Turntable Basics for the Art of=
=20
DJing course.

Please contact the NorCalDJMPA to attend, or for more information on the=20
event. Open to the public and free.=20
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf/calendar2/events/view?identifier=3D1868=

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Mighty Breaks 1/21

Dunno if any of you nasty basshedz made it out to Mighty Breaks last night..
but the teamup of spacecowboys and sistersf is straight up wicked.
Everybody grooves so hard and well together, beautiful crowd, great dancing,
dirty breaks.. and so many, many friends.  Check it!

Highlights.. I got to record some sets with my MD yeah!

Samira w/ audioangel live pa  : Samira puts it down. I have danced to this
girl on the beach at 5am.. waking to music so phat I could justify sleeping
on the beach any longer and had to get my samara fix.. she is such a freakin
player these days.. up there reeking havic on the decks and looking like a
superstar!~   Hit me up if you wanna digicopy.

The Geomatrist: spacecowboys have a lock on the breaks scene right now..
imho, and for good reason.. they turn it out so damn hard.. My MD recorder
lost this set because he turnup up the system so loud.. the recorder clipped
and errored out :(  it was bumpin thogh.. so tech heavy, with hip-hop soul..
and raunchy bass bombs.. peoplz were freakin proper!

Kap'n Kirk: (spacecowboys) gave me a disk that he recreated from his epic
set at Breakfast of Champions 2005.  He acknowledge that it was pretty evil
in there at 9am.. lol.. so dark, deep, fucking erotic as hell on that dance
floor.. I hear laird actually got blown during his set.. haha.. he is such
the man.. props to his girl!!  Anyway.. I got the disk!!

My new favorite SC on the scene is mancub.. I am so bummed this disk never
even started.. doh!  This dude rips it so damn hard.. I discovered some new
dance steps I didn't even know I had :) Got a disk from him too :)

The BreaKbeat Junkie,

~Ranger

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Flip off a Hummer for mother Earth

I'm responding more to the subject than the contents of the original
email here. Let me just say that flipping off a Hummer is generally a
good idea and very satisfying, but be weary of where you are in the Bay
Area when you do it. I flipped off a little Hispanic dude in his H2
while he was driving with his wife and kids, and he made a point to
follow me off the freeway, pull alongside me and scream, then throw fast
food trash out his window into my sunroof. Not particularly frightening,
but it wasn't really worth the trouble either.

Alternatively, you can always make the "teenie weenie" sign by holding
your thumb and forefinger about an inch apart. Usually people
(especially people dense enough to own an H2) just don't get it, and
they just drive on by.

Toodles,
-- 
shawn allen

  aim://shawnpallen

X-Originating-IP: 66.47.248.108

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: Flip off a Hummer for mother Earth

On Jan 24, 2005, at 4:02 PM, shawn allen wrote:

>
>> H1's are the bomb...  but H2's are total poser vehicles.
>
> Agreed, but I still think you'd have to be an asshole to drive anything
> that big and inefficient unless you need to scale 45 degree grades and
> jagged boulders. But if you can figure out a way to get decent gas
> mileage out of the thing, more power to ya! :)


running a diesel engine on waste vegetable oil (non-hydrogenated), 
you'll get the same MPG as if you were burning nasty petro-diesel.  in 
addition, you'd be using a 'waste' from the restaurant industry that 
the restaurant would normally have to pay to have disposed.  
restaurants will usually give it to you for free.  yup - FREE FUEL.  
another great thing about SVO conversions is that your fuel will be 
sulphur-free.  no sulphur = no acid rain.

but really - my point in all of this is that it's not the hummers that 
are the problem.  i think back to the protests at the start of the Iraq 
war, and seeing images of people bashing up SUVs made me sick.  I'll 
bet that some of the owners of those cars were families with kids, and 
an SUV was the vehicle that made the most sense for them. the trick 
isn't to tell people that they're wrong - nobody likes hearing that.  
you need to change their minds instead.

i decided long ago that the way to get the revolution started was to 
start with myself, and to set an example that would inspire others.  
flipping people off, or smashing their cars in protest, or generally 
being confrontational, doesn't get your point across.

philip

no one's mind with insult. More likely, you'll make them more
determined.

betray your own standards of how to act right.

Sean

quoth Steve Osteen:
> I thought the whole thing about Raves/ravers was the ideas of
> open-mindedness and acceptance.

That's only one half of it. As I see it, the yang of raving is rejection
of authority, the DIY ethic--wanting to change the world from the ground
up with your own two hands.

Sometimes wanting change means being honest and telling people when they
piss you off. And people that drive over the bridge to and from work
every day in giant 10mpg trucks that they can write off on their tax
returns *really* piss me off.

>you'll get the same MPG as if you were burning nasty petro-diesel.  in

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  21 years ago today Mac introduced -- lost 1984 video

--=====================_1820177==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

The lost 1984 video

Never seen video footage of the introduction of the Macintosh in January 
1984 was published for the first time on the Internet today. Renowned Mac 
user <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott Knaster kept that Betamax 
video tape for 21 years, and German media agency 
<http://www.textlab.de>TextLab has unearthed this only surviving video tape 
of the launch.

21 years ago today, on January 24th 1984, Apple introduced the Macintosh. 
And we've seen that 1984 wasn't like 1984.

What we've never seen indeed, was the big day itself. Lots of historic 
stuff has been preserved - images, texts, even sounds, and the saga has 
been told on and on. However only very few people have actually seen how 
Steve Jobs pulls the first Mac out of this bag, how the Mac introduces 
itself to the public, Steves biggest grin ever, and how he is obviously 
overwhelmed by this moment in the Cupertino Flint Center.

Fear not, faithful Mac believers. We have found it. We have found what 
seems to be the only copy of a public TV broadcast on that very day. It was 
recorded and preserved by <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott 
Knaster, the "legendary Mac hacker", as 
<http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0764569848/ref=ase_foodisworse-20/104-1915426-5710319>Amazon 
puts it. Scott kept the tape (a NTSC Betamax III longplay) for 21 years 
since he keeps everything. Andy Hertzfeld saw it when he wrote the story 
"<http://www.folklore.org/StoryView.py?project=Macintosh&story=The_Times_They_Are_A-Changin.txt>The 
Times They Are A-Changin'" on folklore.org. From there we followed the 
hints, and that's how we found it.

We worked with Scott to convert it from NTSC to PAL, we've polished it, 
cleaned it, huged it and digitzed it. Here it is. It goes back to the 
people who've made the Macintosh, and to the world. The complete material 
of about 2 hours is returned to Scott, Andy and the 
<http://www.folklore.org/>folklore.org people, and this weblog will report 
the story of the "missing 1984 video" in detail. We'll release other clips 
in the coming days, so bookmark and check back.

But now, Ladies and Gentlemen: please welcome - the 1984 Macintosh 
introduction video. A travel back in time...

There are mirrors at <http://www.macnews.de/news/58099>macnews.de, 
<http://www.php-schmiede.de/1984macintro_2.mov>php-schmiede.de, 
<http://www.ppcnux.de/pub/MacOSX/1984-macintro/>ppcnux.de, ftp.ppcnux.de, 
<http://www.mac-software-updates.de/1984macintro.mov>MacTechNews.de and 
<http://homepage.mac.com/sdomanske/.Movies/The_First_Mac.mov>elbewerk.

<http://www.textlab.de>TextLab is a small but noted media and PR agency 
located near Cologne, Germany, with a subsidiary company in England. We 
work for challenging clients in industry, politics and science. And we run 
one of the most popular weblogs in Germany with the somewhat unlikey name 
"<http://www.industrial-technology-and-witchcraft.de>Industrial Technology 
& Witchcraft", or IT&W.





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

At 06:30 PM 1/24/2005, scosol@scosol.org wrote:

><quote who="J.C.">
> > On 24 January 2005, Steve Osteen wrote:
> >
> >> I thought the whole thing about Raves/ravers was the ideas of
> >> open-mindedness and acceptance.
> >>
> >> You guys are acting just like the people that beat up homosexuals
> >> because they have different beliefs then you.
> >
> > I was going to answer this, but Shawn answered it quite eloquently.  And
> > I hope you don't REALLY feel that's a valid comparison.  Try floating
> > another one and I might be able to be convinced.
>
>Like it or not, it's still judging people based on personal lifestyle choice-

homosexuality is not really a complete choice in the way that choosing a
vehicle is.  And in the largest sense, homosexuals have less of an impact 
on my life
and the environment than someone driving a gas guzzling waste of metal.
In the most shallow sense, both may be a lifestyle choice, but the comparison
falls apart when you look deeper.

And since we're in the 21st century now, we must drag some quantum theory into
this.  The personal values of the observer relative to the observee are a 
factor.
I don't care about the personal values of homosexuals (i.e. that they are 
homosexual)
but I don't much like the personal values of someone who bought a SUV just 
because
it was fashionable.  If they actually do go offroading and drive thru miles 
and miles
of mud, then they're actually using a SUV for what it's for - the problem I 
have with
SUV owners is that I don't think many actually do that.


>"You kissing that other guy is disgusting and offends me."
>"Your vehicle uses too much gas and that offends me."
>
>Guess what- the response to both of those attitudes is "Fuck off, it's
>none of your goddamn business".

well, it's all in how you state your position.  One must learn (and many don't,
hence all the BS in politics) how to be objective and not make it personal.

doug

On 24 January 2005, Philip.X.Diaz wrote:

> shitty gas milage on free, waste vegetable oil?   i think i could live
> with that. :-)

Not truly "free".  Thus my comment regarding mileage (see below.)

>
>
> > If you were driving a nice MB sedan with an SVO conversion.....
> >
>
> um, an SVO-converted H1 has the same impact on the atmosphere as a
> Mercedes sedan - for reals!  NO NET CARBON added to the air... and no
> sulphur compounds.
>
> so the question then becomes:  is it better to use LESS of a waste
> product as fuel, or MORE?   chew on that one.

True, veg-oil is a waste product currently.  But it is one that comes
via a production process that utilizes petrol-based fuels.  Factor that
in please.  Then, since this is such a great way to fuel ones vehicle,
more and more people will certainly want to make the switch (especially
once fossil-fuel prices start going way up) and guess what, I doubt the
veg-oil from the freedom fry fryers will continue to be free
(supply/demand, basically.)  So your free waste product will no longer
be free.  And even so, there is an inherent energy usage in the
production of that waste product (which HAS to be factored in, and
spread out amongst it's use if you like) which is why I made the MPG
comment.  I still stick by it.

Big picture my friend.

>
> and yes, i would only get an H1 to haul shite to my 100 acre community
> event / campground space in the mountains...  no city driving for me!

Hopefuly there's lots of solar, green buildings, composting toilets,
and all those good things! :)

> be a MB diesel wagon (not sedan)...

On Mon, 24 Jan 2005 18:09:40 -0800, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
> The lost 1984 video
> 
> Never seen video footage of the introduction of the Macintosh in January
> 1984 was published for the first time on the Internet today. Renowned Mac
> user <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott Knaster kept that Betamax
> video tape for 21 years, and German media agency
> <http://www.textlab.de>TextLab has unearthed this only surviving video tape
> of the launch.
> 
> 21 years ago today, on January 24th 1984, Apple introduced the Macintosh.
> And we've seen that 1984 wasn't like 1984.
> 
> What we've never seen indeed, was the big day itself. Lots of historic
> stuff has been preserved - images, texts, even sounds, and the saga has
> been told on and on. However only very few people have actually seen how
> Steve Jobs pulls the first Mac out of this bag, how the Mac introduces
> itself to the public, Steves biggest grin ever, and how he is obviously
> overwhelmed by this moment in the Cupertino Flint Center.
> 
> Fear not, faithful Mac believers. We have found it. We have found what
> seems to be the only copy of a public TV broadcast on that very day. It was
> recorded and preserved by <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott
> Knaster, the "legendary Mac hacker", as
> <http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0764569848/ref=ase_foodisworse-20/104-1915426-5710319>Amazon
> puts it. Scott kept the tape (a NTSC Betamax III longplay) for 21 years
> since he keeps everything. Andy Hertzfeld saw it when he wrote the story
> "<http://www.folklore.org/StoryView.py?project=Macintosh&story=The_Times_They_Are_A-Changin.txt>The
> Times They Are A-Changin'" on folklore.org. From there we followed the
> hints, and that's how we found it.
> 
> We worked with Scott to convert it from NTSC to PAL, we've polished it,
> cleaned it, huged it and digitzed it. Here it is. It goes back to the
> people who've made the Macintosh, and to the world. The complete material
> of about 2 hours is returned to Scott, Andy and the
> <http://www.folklore.org/>folklore.org people, and this weblog will report
> the story of the "missing 1984 video" in detail. We'll release other clips
> in the coming days, so bookmark and check back.
> 
> But now, Ladies and Gentlemen: please welcome - the 1984 Macintosh
> introduction video. A travel back in time...
> 
> There are mirrors at <http://www.macnews.de/news/58099>macnews.de,
> <http://www.php-schmiede.de/1984macintro_2.mov>php-schmiede.de,
> <http://www.ppcnux.de/pub/MacOSX/1984-macintro/>ppcnux.de, ftp.ppcnux.de,
> <http://www.mac-software-updates.de/1984macintro.mov>MacTechNews.de and
> <http://homepage.mac.com/sdomanske/.Movies/The_First_Mac.mov>elbewerk.
> 
> <http://www.textlab.de>TextLab is a small but noted media and PR agency
> located near Cologne, Germany, with a subsidiary company in England. We
> work for challenging clients in industry, politics and science. And we run
> one of the most popular weblogs in Germany with the somewhat unlikey name
> "<http://www.industrial-technology-and-witchcraft.de>Industrial Technology
> & Witchcraft", or IT&W.
> 
> Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
> 
> House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm
> 
> "The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands
> of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible
> empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
> -Woodrow Wilson
> 
> "Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look
> on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have
> bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his
> face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be
> willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
> -Daniel Berrigan
> 
> "Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the
> rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become
> visible."
> -Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"
> 
>

> On Mon, 24 Jan 2005 18:09:40 -0800, Apollo

> > The lost 1984 video
> > 
> > Never seen video footage of the introduction of the
> Macintosh in January
> > 1984 was published for the first time on the Internet
> today. Renowned Mac
> > user <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott Knaster
> kept that Betamax
> > video tape for 21 years, and German media agency
> > <http://www.textlab.de>TextLab has unearthed this only
> surviving video tape
> > of the launch.
> > 
> > 21 years ago today, on January 24th 1984, Apple introduced
> the Macintosh.
> > And we've seen that 1984 wasn't like 1984.
> > 
> > What we've never seen indeed, was the big day itself. Lots
> of historic
> > stuff has been preserved - images, texts, even sounds, and
> the saga has
> > been told on and on. However only very few people have
> actually seen how
> > Steve Jobs pulls the first Mac out of this bag, how the Mac
> introduces
> > itself to the public, Steves biggest grin ever, and how he
> is obviously
> > overwhelmed by this moment in the Cupertino Flint Center.
> > 
> > Fear not, faithful Mac believers. We have found it. We have
> found what
> > seems to be the only copy of a public TV broadcast on that
> very day. It was
> > recorded and preserved by
> <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott
> > Knaster, the "legendary Mac hacker", as
> >
>
<http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0764569848/ref=ase_foodisworse-20/104-1915426-5710319>Amazon
> > puts it. Scott kept the tape (a NTSC Betamax III longplay)
> for 21 years
> > since he keeps everything. Andy Hertzfeld saw it when he
> wrote the story
> >
>
"<http://www.folklore.org/StoryView.py?project=Macintosh&story=The_Times_They_Are_A-Changin.txt>The
> > Times They Are A-Changin'" on folklore.org. From there we
> followed the
> > hints, and that's how we found it.
> > 
> > We worked with Scott to convert it from NTSC to PAL, we've
> polished it,
> > cleaned it, huged it and digitzed it. Here it is. It goes
> back to the
> > people who've made the Macintosh, and to the world. The
> complete material
> > of about 2 hours is returned to Scott, Andy and the
> > <http://www.folklore.org/>folklore.org people, and this
> weblog will report
> > the story of the "missing 1984 video" in detail. We'll
> release other clips
> > in the coming days, so bookmark and check back.
> > 
> > But now, Ladies and Gentlemen: please welcome - the 1984
> Macintosh
> > introduction video. A travel back in time...

Dj Adnan! www.djadnan.com care/leaf/PR2/Sunburn/tarantic

In a sea of dj's trying to sound like each other, Adnan sets himself apart by throwing down grooves that stimulate your mind body and soul. Palestinian, Brazilian-born, Adnan Sharif?s
introduction to music began with the magical
Rhythm of Samba, and soulful rhythms and
grooves have defined his music ever since.
In 1985 Adnan immigrated to the USA and
found a new home in the city of San Francisco. 
DJ Adnan is one of the rising stars of the
San Francisco House music scene, with releases on major labels.
His musical styles include all genres of House music with smooth percussion.
with your residents Gabriel Black and Dj Leks 

Next week we have Greg Eversoul!
Come down, have a drink, shoot some pool, get yer groove on!

This is House Music the way it was meant to be heard and felt. 
Come support underground Housemusic in the southbay! 

We hope to see you on the dancefloor!
Audience is free and can be found at Scruffy Murphy's 
187 S Murphy Ave, Sunnyvale, CA 94086 

AUDIENCE Helping you fall in love with House Music all over again
