Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR:  21 years ago today Mac introduced -- lost 1984
 video

Ah, memories. My grandmother was in the audience as an Apple employee 
during this clip shot at Flint Center in Cupertino. Ten years later I 
would find myself working for them during the time of their first dual 
processor machines, licensing of the OS to IBM/Motorola/Daystar/UMAX, 
and the release of Quicktime VR 1.0. I remember using MPW to stitch 
panoramas together because we hadn't developed or released the consumer 
level tools to do authoring yet.

I am really happy to see Apple full of life again and back on a path of 
innovation in areas where they have always been strong. I am a windows 
developer by profession but there is a soft spot in my heart for Apple 
products especially with their current product line.

donb



Apollo wrote:

> The lost 1984 video
>
> Never seen video footage of the introduction of the Macintosh in 
> January 1984 was published for the first time on the Internet today. 
> Renowned Mac user <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott Knaster 
> kept that Betamax video tape for 21 years, and German media agency 
> <http://www.textlab.de>TextLab has unearthed this only surviving video 
> tape of the launch.
>
> 21 years ago today, on January 24th 1984, Apple introduced the 
> Macintosh. And we've seen that 1984 wasn't like 1984.
>
> What we've never seen indeed, was the big day itself. Lots of historic 
> stuff has been preserved - images, texts, even sounds, and the saga 
> has been told on and on. However only very few people have actually 
> seen how Steve Jobs pulls the first Mac out of this bag, how the Mac 
> introduces itself to the public, Steves biggest grin ever, and how he 
> is obviously overwhelmed by this moment in the Cupertino Flint Center.
>
> Fear not, faithful Mac believers. We have found it. We have found what 
> seems to be the only copy of a public TV broadcast on that very day. 
> It was recorded and preserved by 
> <http://foodisworse.typepad.com/this/>Scott Knaster, the "legendary 
> Mac hacker", as 
> <http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0764569848/ref=ase_foodisworse-20/104-1915426-5710319>Amazon 
> puts it. Scott kept the tape (a NTSC Betamax III longplay) for 21 
> years since he keeps everything. Andy Hertzfeld saw it when he wrote 
> the story 
> "<http://www.folklore.org/StoryView.py?project=Macintosh&story=The_Times_They_Are_A-Changin.txt>The 
> Times They Are A-Changin'" on folklore.org. From there we followed the 
> hints, and that's how we found it.
>
> We worked with Scott to convert it from NTSC to PAL, we've polished 
> it, cleaned it, huged it and digitzed it. Here it is. It goes back to 
> the people who've made the Macintosh, and to the world. The complete 
> material of about 2 hours is returned to Scott, Andy and the 
> <http://www.folklore.org/>folklore.org people, and this weblog will 
> report the story of the "missing 1984 video" in detail. We'll release 
> other clips in the coming days, so bookmark and check back.
>
> But now, Ladies and Gentlemen: please welcome - the 1984 Macintosh 
> introduction video. A travel back in time...
>
> There are mirrors at <http://www.macnews.de/news/58099>macnews.de, 
> <http://www.php-schmiede.de/1984macintro_2.mov>php-schmiede.de, 
> <http://www.ppcnux.de/pub/MacOSX/1984-macintro/>ppcnux.de, 
> ftp.ppcnux.de, 
> <http://www.mac-software-updates.de/1984macintro.mov>MacTechNews.de 
> and 
> <http://homepage.mac.com/sdomanske/.Movies/The_First_Mac.mov>elbewerk.
>
> <http://www.textlab.de>TextLab is a small but noted media and PR 
> agency located near Cologne, Germany, with a subsidiary company in 
> England. We work for challenging clients in industry, politics and 
> science. And we run one of the most popular weblogs in Germany with 
> the somewhat unlikey name 
> "<http://www.industrial-technology-and-witchcraft.de>Industrial 
> Technology & Witchcraft", or IT&W.
>
>
>
>
>
> Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org
>
> House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm
>
>
> "The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the 
> hands of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An 
> invisible empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
> -Woodrow Wilson
>
> "Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the 
> look on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might 
> have bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look 
> on his face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you 
> might be willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
> -Daniel Berrigan

Subject: [sfraves] Thomas Fehlmann in SF on Saturday...

nice!  more techno/dub goings on.... i'm glad to see
it.   i got to see Thomas Fehlmann at Movement in
Detroit a few years ago and i as i recall he was
rather good....

SODA presents
Thomas Fehlmann (The Orb/Kompakt/Plug Research)

Berlin's Thomas Fehlmann makes a rare SF appearance on
Saturday, Jan 29, playing live from his new album,
Lowflow (Plug Research) - a 
masterpiece of swirling mid-tempo, psychedelic dub,
and deep techno.

Fehlmann has helped define the shape of electronic
music since his groundbreaking Teutonic Beats
compilations for Brian Eno's Editions EG  label in
1989. Most recently he's been known for his
productions for Kompakt and for his collaborations
with The Orb, co-producing their latest album,
Bicycles & Tricycles.

Fehlmann's reach spans from Detroit to Berlin --
together with Mauritz Von Oswald (Maurizio) and Juan
Atkins, Fehlmann launched the legendary 3MB project in
the early 90s. With remixes for Orbital, Sun Electric,
Yello, Erasure, Einstrzende Neubauten, Infiniti,
Apparat, Blake Baxter, and 
many more, Fehlmann has recorded for dozens of labels
including R&S/Apollo, Tresor, MUTE, ~scape, and
Shitkatapult; most recently
he's been known for his productions for Kompakt, where
he first appeared on Michael Mayer's
classic mix CD Immer.

Supporting Fehlmann is Gudrun Gut, his longtime
accomplice in Berlin's radio show and club night Ocean
Club. An early member of Einstrzende Neubauten, Gut
is today the founder of Monika Enterprise, a Berlin
label whose discography includes contributions from
Barbara Morgenstern, Quarks, Superpitcher, T.
Raumschmiere, and the Postal Service's Jimmy
Tamborello, aka Dntel.

with SODA residents
The Fresh Blend (IRIS Distribution)
Philip Sherburne (flavorpill, XLR8R)

Saturday January 29
9pm-2am
Rx Gallery
132 Eddy St
$10

http://www.freshblend.com/soda/

::::Saturday, January 29 2005
::::::::::DEF Presents,

{{{-{{{-{{{ IS-AS }}}-}}}-}}}
"boing, boom-tchuk"


Part 1a. "Techno Muzik Non-Stop"

DJ Disconnect is to (DEF) as
DJ Jakub is to (TeknoFunk, Seattle).

Forest Green is to (Sister, Cloud Factory, Tech-On) as
Macadio is to (First Light).

Nikita is to (Mezzanine, Mechanix)
as gubernatorial is to __________?


Part 1b. "Anxiety Deprivation Chamber"

Cubik y Origami is to (Wide Hive, newstylesound) as
Drop is to (Butterzone, Ambient Mafia).

MC Boomerang Fidget is to (HATFYR, Ambient Mafia) as
Red Stickman is to (Friends & Family, Thumpchill, Ambient
Mafia).

64k is to (Subterranean, RS23, Ambient Mafia) as
Skye is to (Stargaze, Ambient Mafia).

2. "Info"
a. 9pm - 5am

Rhythm of Samba, and soulful rhythms and
grooves have defined his music ever since.
In 1985 Adnan immigrated to the USA and
found a new home in the city of San Francisco.

with your residents Gabriel Black and Dj Leks

AUDIENCE Helping you fall in love with House Music all over again

Subject: [sfraves] she gives  ..(nrr)..

i.

She gives.
You sit, a selfish idiot.

You sit in yesterday
You sit in selfish shit.

And gone
and gone
and gone for sure--
Her train's done been and gone.


ii.

I havent been outside since
she fell apart my heart,  and
Im startin to fall apart in 
this darkened apartment.


iii.

Afternoon, and blinds are frowned
You fade like ancient pages.
Afternoon; and windows down
Patience waits in stages.

Railway platforms spared us space,
Then resembled stages.
Summer fades on goodbye trains,
then harvest moons engage us.


iv.

Its morning.  Your eyes are open.
Forget for a second your heart is broken
Forget you forgot you believed in hope, and
Nope, she wont unspeak whats spoken.


b.fidget
2004
ambient mafia

Well, the name of the event gives a humorous nod to an aspect of my DJ
personality (see http://tinyurl.com/5yfb5 or
http://www.jcthedj.com/DC2005.php from the 2:30-3:00 point in the film

dose of beats this Saturday night at SubLounge that you won't want to
miss.  Hope to see you all there!  And when we're done, you can head on
over to Furious 2 or is-as.

Subject: [sfraves] (BSP) sat 1/29: thomas fehlmann @ Rx gallery

hey everyone,
excuse the BSP but i figured this would appeal to plenty of heads in the
audience. if you want to check a serious pioneer of the scene who has
remained absolutely vital for over 25 years, don't miss this show...!

SODA presents
Thomas Fehlmann (The Orb/Kompakt/Plug Research)

Berlin's Thomas Fehlmann makes a rare SF appearance on Saturday, Jan 29,
playing live from his new album, Lowflow (Plug Research) - a masterpiece of
swirling mid-tempo, psychedelic dub, and deep techno.

Fehlmann has helped define the shape of electronic music since his
groundbreaking Teutonic Beats compilations for Brian Eno's Editions EG labe=
l
in 1989. Most recently he's been known for his productions for Kompakt and
for his collaborations with The Orb, co-producing their latest album,
Bicycles & Tricycles.

Fehlmann's reach spans from Detroit to Berlin -- together with Mauritz Von
Oswald (Maurizio) and Juan Atkins, Fehlmann launched the legendary 3MB
project in the early 90s. With remixes for Orbital, Sun Electric, Yello,
Erasure, Einst=FCrzende Neubauten, Infiniti, Apparat, Blake Baxter, and many
more, Fehlmann has recorded for dozens of labels including R&S/Apollo,
Tresor, MUTE, ~scape, and Shitkatapult; most recently he's been known for
his productions for Kompakt, where he first appeared on Michael Mayer's
classic mix CD Immer.

Supporting Fehlmann is Gudrun Gut, his longtime accomplice in Berlin's radi=
o
show and club night Ocean Club. An early member of Einst=FCrzende Neubauten,
Gut is today the founder of Monika Enterprise, a Berlin label whose
discography includes contributions from Barbara Morgenstern, Quarks,
Superpitcher, T. Raumschmiere, and the Postal Service's Jimmy Tamborello,
aka Dntel.

with SODA residents
The Fresh Blend (IRIS Distribution)
Philip Sherburne (flavorpill, XLR8R)

Saturday January 29
9pm-2am
Rx Gallery
132 Eddy St
$10
=20


----

philip sherburne
full sentences on demand

a blog: http://www.philipsherburne.com
subscribe: http://www.flavorpill.net
subscribe: http://www.earplug.cc

References: <1106858543.41f9522fe0a35@rootmonkey.com>
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Planning another trip to sf

Weather is best in the late September range. SF is usually foggy and
overcast during the summer while in the east bay (other side of the
bay bridge) is sunny, warm and nice. So. If you come here in summer -
bring clothes for colder days and colder nights. All it takes is 30
minutes outside of SF to the East and you get 80+ degree days and 60+
degree nights.

As far as parties and events. Late spring through mid-september is the
peak season. Really there is always stuff going on so long as you
don't show up now. Valentines day and beyond seems to be about when
things pick up a bit. In March the first Pacific Sound
(www.pacificsound.net) Sunset outdoor parties start. The first one of
the year is always epic. Last year it was something like 2000 people
and the park it's held in North of SF is gorgeous. Good house musik.
Good people. Good times.

:: r ::

hello, this is a continuation of a fictional piece:
 
for a very long, long time, there was a man and that man was looking for a woman, and then he realized that there was nothing special or unique about that at all, and then, he began a quest for knowledge, realized that there was nothing unique or special about that at all either, and then he began to wonder, like many men do, and then suddenly he realized that all the things that he'd been doing were exactly like all of the things that many women do, and that made him feel even less unique and special, so then he decided to just climb into his cheap car and drive.  that was when jane drove past him on the freeway:
 
"hey, that guy was just way to usual for me, but what is up with that skinny neck and bulging eyes in the next car up front. boy is that one ugly. just how i like them. can't tell if it is a man or  a woman though. wow, this is just like polishing my favorite rock from my rock collection from the last hike i took in the mountains." :)

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Results of Washington Post's Mensa Invitational 

--=====================_11890377==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed

The Washington Post's Mensa Invitational once again asked readers to
take any word from the dictionary, alter it by adding, subtracting, or
changing one letter, and supply a new definition.

Here are this year's winners. (None of them get through spellcheck)


1. Intaxication: Euphoria at getting a tax refund, which lasts until you
realize it was your money to start with.

2. Reintarnation: Coming back to life as a hillbilly.

3. Bozone (n.): The substance surrounding stupid people that stops
bright ideas from penetrating. The bozone layer, unfortunately, shows
little sign of breaking down in the near future.

4. Foreploy: Any misrepresentation about yourself for the purpose of
getting laid.

5. Cashtration (n.): The act of buying a house, which renders the
subject financially impotent for an indefinite period.

6. Giraffiti: Vandalism spray-painted very, very high.

7. Sarchasm: The gulf between the author of sarcastic wit and the person
who doesn't get it.

8. Inoculatte: To take coffee intravenously when you are running late.


9. Hipatitis: Terminal coolness.

10. Osteopornosis: A degenerate disease. (This one got extra credit.)

11. Karmageddon: It's like, when everybody is sending off these bad
vibes, right? And then, like, the Earth explodes and it's like, a
serious bummer.

12. Decafalon (n.): The grueling event of getting through the day
consuming only things that are good for you.

13. Glibido: All talk and no action.

14. Dopeler effect: The tendency of stupid ideas to seem smarter when
they come at you rapidly.

15. Arachnoleptic fit (n.): The frantic dance performed just after
you've accidentally walked through a spider web.

16. Beelzebug (n.): Satan in the form of a mosquito, that gets into your
bedroom at three in the morning and cannot be cast out.

17. Caterpallor (n.): The color you turn after finding half a worm in
the fruit you're eating.

And the pick of the literature:

18. Ignoranus: A person who's both stupid and an asshole.





Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] NRR:  Education secretary condemns public show with gay
  characters

--=====================_12388944==.ALT
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="us-ascii"; format=flowed



Education secretary condemns public show with gay characters

WASHINGTON (AP) -- The nation's new education secretary denounced PBS on 
Tuesday for spending public money on a cartoon with lesbian characters, 
saying many parents would not want children exposed to such lifestyles.

The not-yet-aired episode of "Postcards From Buster" shows the title 
character, an animated bunny named Buster, on a trip to Vermont -- a state 
known for recognizing same-sex civil unions. The episode features two 
lesbian couples, although the focus is on farm life and maple sugaring.

A PBS spokesman said late Tuesday that the nonprofit network has decided 
not to distribute the episode, called "Sugartime!," to its 349 stations. 
She said the Education Department's objections were not a factor in that 
decision.

"Ultimately, our decision was based on the fact that we recognize this is a 
sensitive issue, and we wanted to make sure that parents had an opportunity 
to introduce this subject to their children in their own time," said Lea 
Sloan, vice president of media relations at PBS.

However, the Boston public television station that produces the show, WGBH, 
does plan to make the "Sugartime!" episode available to other stations. 
WGBH also plans to air the episode on March 23, Sloan said.

PBS gets money for the "Postcards from Buster" series through the federal 
Ready-To-Learn program, one aimed at helping young children learn through 
television.

http://www.cnn.com/2005/EDUCATION/01/26/education.secretary.pbs.ap/



The local Bay Area PBS stations WILL be airing this episode.

> Weather is best in the late September range. SF is usually foggy and
> overcast during the summer while in the east bay (other side of the
> bay bridge) is sunny, warm and nice. So. If you come here in summer -
> bring clothes for colder days and colder nights. All it takes is 30
> minutes outside of SF to the East and you get 80+ degree days and 60+
> degree nights.
>
> As far as parties and events. Late spring through mid-september is the
> peak season. Really there is always stuff going on so long as you
> don't show up now. Valentines day and beyond seems to be about when
> things pick up a bit. In March the first Pacific Sound
> (www.pacificsound.net) Sunset outdoor parties start. The first one of
> the year is always epic. Last year it was something like 2000 people
> and the park it's held in North of SF is gorgeous. Good house musik.
> Good people. Good times.
>

scedule. Ill would definitely like to meet as many people while i am down there

Revenge of the Right Brain

Logical and precise, left-brain thinking gave us the Information Age. Now 
comes the Conceptual Age - ruled by artistry, empathy, and emotion.
By Daniel H. Pink

When I was a kid - growing up in a middle-class family, in the middle of 
America, in the middle of the 1970s - parents dished out a familiar plate 
of advice to their children: Get good grades, go to college, and pursue a 
profession that offers a decent standard of living and perhaps a dollop of 
prestige. If you were good at math and science, become a doctor. If you 
were better at English and history, become a lawyer. If blood grossed you 
out and your verbal skills needed work, become an accountant. Later, as 
computers appeared on desktops and CEOs on magazine covers, the youngsters 
who were really good at math and science chose high tech, while others 
flocked to business school, thinking that success was spelled MBA.

Tax attorneys. Radiologists. Financial analysts. Software engineers. 
Management guru Peter Drucker gave this cadre of professionals an enduring, 
if somewhat wonky, name: knowledge workers. These are, he wrote, "people 
who get paid for putting to work what one learns in school rather than for 
their physical strength or manual skill." What distinguished members of 
this group and enabled them to reap society's greatest rewards, was their 
"ability to acquire and to apply theoretical and analytic knowledge." And 
any of us could join their ranks. All we had to do was study hard and play 
by the rules of the meritocratic regime. That was the path to professional 
success and personal fulfillment.

But a funny thing happened while we were pressing our noses to the 
grindstone: The world changed. The future no longer belongs to people who 
can reason with computer-like logic, speed, and precision. It belongs to a 
different kind of person with a different kind of mind. Today - amid the 
uncertainties of an economy that has gone from boom to bust to blah - 
there's a metaphor that explains what's going on. And it's right inside our 
heads.

MORE:  http://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.02/brain.html




Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm


"The government, which was designed for the people, has got into the hands 
of the bosses and their employers, the special interests.  An invisible 
empire has been set up above the forms of democracy."
-Woodrow Wilson

"Sometime in your life, hope that you might see one starved man, the look 
on his face when the bread finally arrives.  Hope that you might have 
bought it or baked it or even kneaded it yourself.  For that look on his 
face, for your meeting his eyes across a piece of bread, you might be 
willing to lose a lot, or suffer a lot, or die a little, even."
-Daniel Berrigan

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the 
rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become 
visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!

Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,

I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a 
community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful 
accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental, 
innovative, creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be 
cherished. Happy Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a 
birthday party for SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)

http://www.sfraves.org/history/
http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf

SFRaves History:

A Brief History of SFRaves

1992: SFRaves Connects

     * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The 
address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs. 
the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves 
button, now a collector's item :).
     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin 
Miller Park.
     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for Bonny 
Doon.
     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a 
better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod u+x, 
Contact, Outernet.
     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. Word 
eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of 
also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear 
that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu 
(aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the Berkeley 
Marina. The grass is never the same again.
     * 11.92 - vrave is born
     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to 
"ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"

Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity, 
Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith, 
Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
1993

     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana 
ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while skiing 
the back country in Yosemite.
     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain 
forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into 
Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala 
Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers 
who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a while, 
leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still 
have tapes :)
     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefit 
party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party 
early in March.
     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was 
at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a 
bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This 
started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends 
and Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs included 
Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La Gassa.
     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection Earth, 
an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.

Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar, 
Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
1994

     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube. 
Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning 
the ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub 
Komotion with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the 
Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.

Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
1995: SFR: Friends & Family

     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over 
the month.
     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first 
of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows 
to many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets 
for the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate 
Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are 
married the next day.

Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8, 
Area 51.
1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
SFR

     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award 
for Best Local Online Rave Resource!

2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century

     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992

2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century

     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved 
taz3.hyperreal.org is born
     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, CA
     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves many 
fond memories in the mind of Karina
     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous 
party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindig 
called Sunday of Slack
     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary 
party
     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists

2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
# SFR-P throws Amalagamation
# 09.29.02 -
SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and 
celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves 
over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression 
of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of 
flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by 
Neuroscience Creations.
Your lineup is as follows:

     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records) 
[www.viberation.com]
     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique, 
Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)

This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm 
@ the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
* Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
# SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for the 
calendar are launched.
SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes


SFR Calendar

Calendar

Groups

People profiles

Polls

2003

     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people and 
size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are 
updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar 
Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.

2004

     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR 
calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden 
scope and improved Quality standards.
     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups, 
User/People profiles
     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as 
of September 2004!
     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @ 
Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves 
Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!

2005

     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users, 
Groups and features.
     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community 
has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on 
various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth 
of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups and 
1985 people as of January 2005!
     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ 
Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @ 
Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!

Would you like to add to SFRaves.org history? Please send comments, 
suggestions and other stories to karina@hyperreal.org

Thanks!

Karina

Subject: [sfraves] News: New Rave Drug Have Experts Concerned

http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=366370&page=1

New Rave Drugs Have Experts Concerned
Use of Synthetic Hallucinogens Is on the Rise, But Health Effects Are 
Unknown

Dec. 30, 2004 . A new class of drugs is getting increased attention from 
police and partyers alike.

Synthetic hallucinogens, which are growing in popularity at nightclubs and 
rave parties, are so new that many don't even have street names yet.

Top Stories

     * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
     * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
     * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage

Usually manufactured in small home-based laboratories, these drugs have 
law enforcement and health officials concerned because their long-term 
health effects are virtually unknown.

'Colors Were Really Brilliant and Crisp'

The drugs reportedly have effects similar to the popular rave drug 
ecstasy: feelings of euphoria, emotional empathy and colorful 
hallucinations. The typical user is a young, white, college-educated and 
Web-savvy person who finds that these drugs complement the dance music 
heard at nightclubs and raves.

"It's kind of mildly hallucinogenic and visual," said Gregory, a graphic 
designer from California who tried one of these drugs for the first time 
last year. "Colors were really brilliant and crisp, and I became really 
relaxed."

Most synthetic hallucinogens are still referred to by a confusing alphabet 
soup of names based on their chemical compounds.

2C-B is considered one of the most popular of these drugs. 2C-T-7 is often 
compared to LSD for its colorful hallucinations. AMT was originally 
developed in the 1960s for antidepressant research, but was abandoned 
shortly thereafter. 5-MEO-DiPT, also referred to as "Foxy," is sometimes 
used as a substitute for ecstasy.

Buyer Beware

"Because these drugs are unstudied in the medical literature, we don't 
know all of the side effects or all of the dangers involved in the use of 
these drugs," said Paula Berezansky, intelligence analyst for the National 
Drug Intelligence Center, a component agency of the U.S. Department of 
Justice.

The illicit way in which synthetic hallucinogens are sold presents another 
problem. "A user may not know what they're buying," Berezansky added. 
"Something sold as one drug may be another."

Most synthetic hallucinogens fall into two general categories, 
phenethylamines and tryptamines. Both chemical compounds occur in nature 
and are found in common plants and foods . small amounts of phenethylamine 
are even found in chocolate.

Nationwide, a handful of overdoses and hospital admissions have been 
attributed to synthetic hallucinogens. But because many of these drugs are 
mixed with other drugs or their actual chemical nature is unknown even to 
the users, accurate records are difficult to gather.

Top Stories

     * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
     * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
     * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage

Health Effects Are Unknown

"We've actually had patients come in with a condition called monoamine 
oxidase toxicity from taking combinations of drugs that include 
tryptamines," said Dr. Edward Boyer, director of toxicology at the 
University of Massachusetts Medical Center in Worcester.

"What concerns me . is that kids are turning to psychoactive drugs at a 
younger age," Boyer added. "We simply don't know what these tryptamines do 
to a developing neurological system. Tryptamines are powerful 
hallucinogens."

"People can't even decide what the long-term effects of a common drug like 
ecstasy are, let alone something like 2C-B," said Boyer.

Law enforcement officials echo the concerns of the medical community.

"It's a young group of people who are using this and half the time they 
don't know what they're using . they're going on what a friend says," said 
Lt. Patrick J. Garey, a member of the Community Narcotics Enforcement Team 
of the New York State Police.

"There's so much poly-drug mixing of drugs that occurs, you could be 
taking ecstasy mixed with a bunch of other drugs," he said.

Psychonauts Surfing the Web

"One of the reasons we've seen these drugs increase in use over the last 
few years is the use of the Internet," said Berezansky. "The abusers can 
find out a lot about these drugs very easily."

She refers to users by the name law enforcement officials have coined for 
those who surf the Web for drug information: "psychonauts."

But drug users aren't the only ones surfing the Internet for drug 
information.

When Garey was called to participate in a recent seizure of a 2C-B lab at 
a home in Tioga County in upstate New York, he told ABCNews.com: "It kind 
of came out of the blue. We'd never seen it before. I'd never even heard 
of it. I had to go on the Internet to find out what it was."

The DEA is also using the Internet, but to snare the dealers who profit 
from the sale of synthetic hallucinogens. In July, the DEA announced the 
conclusion of "Operation Web Tryp," named for the tryptamines that were 
part of the operation's focus.

Operation Web Tryp targeted five Web sites and resulted in the arrest of 
10 individuals from across the United States.

But many of these drugs are so new their legal status is a matter of some 
confusion. 5-MEO-DiPT, for example, was not even permanently placed on the 
Federal Register as a Schedule I controlled substance until September of 
this year.

A User's Experience

Rod, a computer hardware engineer in the San Francisco Bay area who 
preferred to use an assumed name, has experimented with the synthetic 
hallucinogen 2C-B.

Top Stories

     * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
     * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
     * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage

"Initially, a friend of mine at a rave told me about it when he was 
tripping pretty hard on it," Rod said. "Then I followed up on it by 
reading this book by a guy named Shulgin."

Alexander Shulgin is widely credited with fostering the popularity of 
synthetic hallucinogens through his 1990 book, "Pihkal: A Chemical Love 
Story." (The name "Pihkal" is an acronym for Phenethylamines I Have Known 
and Loved.)

Rod describes his experience as interesting but not especially exciting. 
"It was just mildly hallucinogenic . it made everything sharper and more 
vivid, and there was a slight hallucinogenic effect," he said. "It was all 
visual for me."

But when asked if he would try the drug again, Rod said, "No, probably 
not."

Subject: [sfraves] News (old) - Interesting Concept: The Safety Dance

http://www.eye.net/eye/issue/issue_12.16.99/news/raves.html

The safety dance
City sets rules for raves
BY NATE HENDLEY

Rave promoters, politicians and emergency services staff gathered Dec. 10 
at the Queen West Community Health Centre to agree on voluntary 
regulations for rave parties. The protocol says promoters should provide 
free water, adequate ventilation and ample medical and security personnel 
at dance parties. The document also says promoters should notify city 
staff of upcoming parties, and adhere to building and fire codes, and 
occupancy rules.

"The idea for guidelines, for self-regulation, started in the rave 
community itself months and months ago," said Kim Stanford, acting chair 
of the Dance Safety Committee, which put together the protocol.

Stanford, who also serves as coordinator of the Toronto Raver Info Project 
(TRIP), a drug awareness organization, said the committee has been meeting 
since August to discuss rave regulations.

Last summer, Toronto's decade-old scene experienced its first reported 
death after a young raver overdosed at a party at the Warehouse. Two other 
rave-related deaths have been reported in Ontario this year and a backlash 
has been brewing against noise, crowds and drugs at rave parties.

A high-volume rave at the Docks this fall woke up residents across the 
east end, infuriating area councillor Tom Jakobek, who vowed to put 
restrictions on raves. Ontario Consumer Affairs Minister Bob Runciman, 
meanwhile, threatened to stamp them out altogether.

York Humber city councillor Frances Nunziata doesn't want to go that far. 
"We don't want to spoil your fun. We just want to make raves safe," said 
the councillor at the Health Centre meeting.

In late November, Nunziata put forward a motion at city council aimed at 
"regulating dance/rave parties." The motion was in response to a 
Thanksgiving Hullabaloo party, at which a Ryerson University student died. 
An amendment to the motion also directed the city to set up a task force 
on raves.

Not that a task force was really necessary -- the Dance Safety Committee 
has spent months preparing its "Protocol for the Operation of Safe Dance 
Events" with party promoters, cops and city staff.

Final drafts of the protocol were approved at the Community Health Centre 
meeting, which was attended by Nunziata and fellow councillor Olivia Chow. 
While the protocol doesn't have the force of law, party promoters were 
strongly encouraged to obey its contents. "If you choose not to follow it, 
we will pay close attention to you," said James Ridge, acting commissioner 
for the Urban Planning department.

Promoters promised to assist city staff in closing raves that don't follow 
the protocol. "We will help you find these parties beforehand," vowed Sean 
Scanlan, of the promotional company EmaiL.

In case anyone didn't get the message, Detective Court Booth of the 
Central Drug Information Unit said police are setting up an "enforcement 
program" aimed at cracking down on illicit raves. "We will be coordinating 
the efforts of all the enforcement areas of the city, as well as the fire 
department, to bring about the closure of what's termed illegal, or 
undesirable, events," said the detective.

The initiative, which is being chaired by 14 Division Superintendent Keith 
Cowling, is designed to provide a "made-in-Toronto solution" to the issue 
of local raves, said Det. Booth. His desire for a local solution was 
reflected by everyone at the meeting except Nunziata, who suggested 
getting the Tory government involved in regulating Toronto raves.

This suggestion was shot down by Chow. "I'm not interested in provincial 
legislation," she said. "The city of Toronto can handle this without 
getting the province involved."

Nunziata will present the protocol to council this week. If it passes, the 
city will likely check in on the rave scene in six months or so to see how 
the protocol is working out. It'll be a tough half-year, as protocol 
backers find out if self-regulation alone can restore the image of the 
local rave scene.

  --

& in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.

>From: Karina <karina@hyperreal.org>
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!
>Date: Fri, 28 Jan 2005 00:36:55 -0800 (PST)
>
>Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,
>
>I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a 
>community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful 
>accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental, innovative, 
>creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be cherished. Happy 
>Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a birthday party for 
>SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)
>
>http://www.sfraves.org/history/
>http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf
>
>SFRaves History:
>
>A Brief History of SFRaves
>
>1992: SFRaves Connects
>
>     * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The 
>address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
>     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs. 
>the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves 
>button, now a collector's item :).
>     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin 
>Miller Park.
>     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
>     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for Bonny 
>Doon.
>     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a 
>better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod u+x, 
>Contact, Outernet.
>     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. Word 
>eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of 
>also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
>     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear 
>that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
>     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu 
>(aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
>     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the Berkeley 
>Marina. The grass is never the same again.
>     * 11.92 - vrave is born
>     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to 
>"ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
>
>Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity, 
>Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith, 
>Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
>1993
>
>     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana 
>ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while skiing 
>the back country in Yosemite.
>     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
>     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain 
>forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into 
>Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala 
>Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers 
>who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a while, 
>leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still have 
>tapes :)
>     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefit 
>party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party 
>early in March.
>     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was 
>at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a 
>bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
>     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
>     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This 
>started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends and 
>Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs included 
>Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La Gassa.
>     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection Earth, 
>an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.
>
>Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar, 
>Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
>1994
>
>     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube. 
>Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning the 
>ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub Komotion 
>with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
>     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the 
>Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
>     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.
>
>Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
>1995: SFR: Friends & Family
>
>     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
>     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over 
>the month.
>     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first 
>of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows to 
>many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets for 
>the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
>     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate 
>Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are 
>married the next day.
>
>Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8, 
>Area 51.
>1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
>SFR
>
>     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award 
>for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
>
>2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century
>
>     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992
>
>2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century
>
>     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
>     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
>     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
>     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved 
>taz3.hyperreal.org is born
>     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
>     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, CA
>     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves many 
>fond memories in the mind of Karina
>     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous 
>party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
>     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
>     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindig 
>called Sunday of Slack
>     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary 
>party
>     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists
>
>2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
># SFR-P throws Amalagamation
># 09.29.02 -
>SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
>A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
>*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
>Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and 
>celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves 
>over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression 
>of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of 
>flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by 
>Neuroscience Creations.
>Your lineup is as follows:
>
>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
>     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records) 
>[www.viberation.com]
>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique, 
>Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
>     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
>
>This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm @ 
>the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
>* Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
>* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
># SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for the 
>calendar are launched.
>SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes
>
>
>SFR Calendar
>
>Calendar
>
>Groups
>
>People profiles
>
>Polls
>
>2003
>
>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people and 
>size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are 
>updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar 
>Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.
>
>2004
>
>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR 
>calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden scope 
>and improved Quality standards.
>     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups, 
>User/People profiles
>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as 
>of September 2004!
>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @ 
>Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves 
>Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
>
>2005
>
>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users, 
>Groups and features.
>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
>     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community 
>has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on 
>various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth 
>of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups and 
>1985 people as of January 2005!
>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ 
>Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @ 
>Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!
>
>Would you like to add to SFRaves.org history? Please send comments, 
>suggestions and other stories to karina@hyperreal.org
>
>Thanks!
>
>Karina

Subject: RE: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!


Yeah, and the gap at 1997-2000 is a weird one, seeing as list membership
was highest during those years.

I'd like to sit down with some people that were active during that period
that I don't really know all that well and figure out what should be
added.

Considering some of the most incredible parties I ever attended happened
during that time period...

Gateway Systems - Chrysalis (gateway wasn't too into SFR, but you saw a
lot of SFR kids at Gateway events)

Harmony - Wrinkle in Time, Beautiful People, Freaky People, 3 year at Camp
Swig, Spring Massive

FnF's first campouts and expanding underground offerrings

Cloud Factory growing outside the Monterey/Salinas roots

Viberation - in many ways the most SFR involved collective (terry + mikem
+ andyw + siphon + science + micron + li... all active SFR netizens).

ASR - Always a balancing act between Jeremy (and later Tony's) vision and
a collective wtih a lot of, the result was a lot of good parties.

Happy Kids - while I had issues with the crew at the time, they really did
come up with some of the best spaces and had a fanatical following.

NBC - Petaluma / Sonoma / San Rafael freaks.

Children of the Sun - While burning a few bridges in the process, COTS
managed to bust a party every couple weeks for a while there, and managed
to create a lot of memories.

Warmth - I was never a big Spencer fan, but lots of people "got it"  in
the crew, and they did have their hearts in the right place.

BBQ & Beats - Not too many parties, but one of my favorite completely
illegal renegades of all time... a 3 day free outdoor campout with ZERO
permits, $10 for meals all weekend from a champion BBQ cook, and the
craziest mix of genres I've ever heard at one party.

Orphan - East bay nutters.

Oh shit, and that first light where $20 got you Entrance.

The crackhouse on 13th.  Acme warehouse, the old dance studio, the old
clementina alley spot, psytrance, casa z, the old f8 studio/hangar in
north bay, the phoenix, 2nd and jax, homebase, richmond point molate,
static, mad, sabotage, eklectic, bass kru...

How good were those parties?  I'll put it this way... so many of the
people I met at those events, are still going... while I've seen people
that got into it years later totally fall out after a year or two.  Could
it have been that the parties back then were *that* good?  I dunno, seems
like a strange ommission as far as time stretch... this was the second
underground that came out of the cave-in that started in 94.  Everybody
had given up on it, but it was still going... not running on nostalgia...
we were still mentally young but wiser than newbies, still loving it, the
scene had a great cross section of it with people from 15 to 65 attending
the same parties with the same enthusiasm, there were parties where "vibe"
was not a glassy eyed dream but a tangible fog of friendly sweat and
intentions, and we were just high as fark on what we were doing.

In the end, not sure how much of an effect it had as a movement or
whatever, but I know a lot of people that are forever changed.  Some for
worse, most for better I think.  The big parties nowadays are still
plagued by the same cost cutting, limits on freedom and ethical
shortcuts... but there was a period where several thousand people were
involved in a very alive, very optimistic and vital underground that I'm
not sure will ever happen again here.

andyw

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy
\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/
"Nothing real can defeat us.  Nothing unreal exists." - Buckaroo Banzai

-&e->
-&e->DJ Bam - serving breaks and beats
-&e->http://www.invibe.com/bam
-&e->
-&e->January 29th:  Furious II
-&e->February 19th:  Dirty
-&e->March 19th:  Evil Breaks One Year Anniversary Party
-&e->April 29th:  Lee Coombs @ Mighty
-&e->--------------------
-&e->---------------------
-&e->
-&e->
-&e->>From: Karina <karina@hyperreal.org>
-&e->>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
-&e->>Subject: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!
-&e->>Date: Fri, 28 Jan 2005 00:36:55 -0800 (PST)
-&e->>
-&e->>Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,
-&e->>
-&e->>I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a
-&e->>community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful
-&e->>accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental, innovative,
-&e->>creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be cherished. Happy
-&e->>Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a birthday party for
-&e->>SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)
-&e->>
-&e->>http://www.sfraves.org/history/
-&e->>http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf
-&e->>
-&e->>SFRaves History:
-&e->>
-&e->>A Brief History of SFRaves
-&e->>
-&e->>1992: SFRaves Connects
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The
-&e->>address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
-&e->>     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs.
-&e->>the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves
-&e->>button, now a collector's item :).
-&e->>     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin
-&e->>Miller Park.
-&e->>     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
-&e->>     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for Bonny
-&e->>Doon.
-&e->>     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a
-&e->>better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod u+x,
-&e->>Contact, Outernet.
-&e->>     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. Word
-&e->>eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of
-&e->>also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
-&e->>     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear
-&e->>that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
-&e->>     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu
-&e->>(aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
-&e->>     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the Berkeley
-&e->>Marina. The grass is never the same again.
-&e->>     * 11.92 - vrave is born
-&e->>     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to
-&e->>"ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
-&e->>
-&e->>Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity,
-&e->>Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith,
-&e->>Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
-&e->>1993
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana
-&e->>ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while skiing
-&e->>the back country in Yosemite.
-&e->>     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
-&e->>     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain
-&e->>forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into
-&e->>Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala
-&e->>Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers
-&e->>who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a while,
-&e->>leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still have
-&e->>tapes :)
-&e->>     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefit
-&e->>party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party
-&e->>early in March.
-&e->>     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was
-&e->>at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a
-&e->>bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
-&e->>     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
-&e->>     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This
-&e->>started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends and
-&e->>Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs included
-&e->>Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La Gassa.
-&e->>     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection Earth,
-&e->>an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.
-&e->>
-&e->>Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar,
-&e->>Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
-&e->>1994
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube.
-&e->>Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning the
-&e->>ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub Komotion
-&e->>with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
-&e->>     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the
-&e->>Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
-&e->>     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.
-&e->>
-&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
-&e->>1995: SFR: Friends & Family
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
-&e->>     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over
-&e->>the month.
-&e->>     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first
-&e->>of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows to
-&e->>many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets for
-&e->>the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
-&e->>     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate
-&e->>Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are
-&e->>married the next day.
-&e->>
-&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8,
-&e->>Area 51.
-&e->>1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
-&e->>SFR
-&e->>
-&e->>     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award
-&e->>for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
-&e->>
-&e->>2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992
-&e->>
-&e->>2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century
-&e->>
-&e->>     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
-&e->>     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
-&e->>     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
-&e->>     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved
-&e->>taz3.hyperreal.org is born
-&e->>     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
-&e->>     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, CA
-&e->>     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves many
-&e->>fond memories in the mind of Karina
-&e->>     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous
-&e->>party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
-&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
-&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindig
-&e->>called Sunday of Slack
-&e->>     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary
-&e->>party
-&e->>     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists
-&e->>
-&e->>2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
-&e->># SFR-P throws Amalagamation
-&e->># 09.29.02 -
-&e->>SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
-&e->>A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
-&e->>*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
-&e->>Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and
-&e->>celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves
-&e->>over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression
-&e->>of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of
-&e->>flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by
-&e->>Neuroscience Creations.
-&e->>Your lineup is as follows:
-&e->>
-&e->>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
-&e->>     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
-&e->>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
-&e->>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records)
-&e->>[www.viberation.com]
-&e->>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique,
-&e->>Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
-&e->>     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
-&e->>
-&e->>This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm @
-&e->>the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
-&e->>* Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
-&e->>* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
-&e->># SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for the
-&e->>calendar are launched.
-&e->>SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes
-&e->>
-&e->>
-&e->>SFR Calendar
-&e->>
-&e->>Calendar
-&e->>
-&e->>Groups
-&e->>
-&e->>People profiles
-&e->>
-&e->>Polls
-&e->>
-&e->>2003
-&e->>
-&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people and
-&e->>size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are
-&e->>updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar
-&e->>Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
-&e->>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.
-&e->>
-&e->>2004
-&e->>
-&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR
-&e->>calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden scope
-&e->>and improved Quality standards.
-&e->>     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups,
-&e->>User/People profiles
-&e->>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as
-&e->>of September 2004!
-&e->>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @
-&e->>Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves
-&e->>Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
-&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
-&e->>
-&e->>2005
-&e->>
-&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users,
-&e->>Groups and features.
-&e->>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
-&e->>     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community
-&e->>has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on
-&e->>various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth
-&e->>of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
-&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups and
-&e->>1985 people as of January 2005!
-&e->>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @
-&e->>Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @
-&e->>Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
-&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!
-&e->>
-&e->>Would you like to add to SFRaves.org history? Please send comments,
-&e->>suggestions and other stories to karina@hyperreal.org
-&e->>
-&e->>Thanks!
-&e->>
-&e->>Karina
-&e->>
-&e->>--
-&e->>**************************************************************
-&e->>******************>karina@hyperreal.org<**********************
-&e->>If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so
-&e->>much in despairing of life as in hoping for another life
-&e->>& in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.
-&e->>-- Albert Camus -- *******************************************

to put forth the effort to make things happen.
unfortunately, those people are few and far between.
for me im willing to put forth the effort to throw
parties etc...but i think a group of people need to
come together to do this and make it happen. its that
simple. (not in the process of throwing a party but
the idea of unifying to make a movement in the scene).

-Delia

> -&e->>     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts:
> Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs.
> -&e->>the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the
> first time. I get my SFRaves
> -&e->>button, now a collector's item :).
> -&e->>     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over
> in the East Bay at Joaquin
> -&e->>Miller Park.
> -&e->>     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to
> soda.berkeley.edu.
> -&e->>     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big
> SFRaves bash, planned for Bonny
> -&e->>Doon.
> -&e->>     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian
> realizes "Connection" is a
> -&e->>better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected
> names: DeepByte, chmod u+x,
> -&e->>Contact, Outernet.
> -&e->>     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big
> way at Bonny Doon Beach. Word
> -&e->>eventually reaches the full moon massive,
> which hold a series of
> -&e->>also-legendary parties there in the coming
> months.
> -&e->>     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the
> basement of 1015. We fear
> -&e->>that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but
> they don't show.
> -&e->>     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is
> moved to medisg.stanford.edu
> -&e->>(aka sfraves.stanford.edu and
> techno.stanford.edu)
> -&e->>     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE
> squarish open space" in the Berkeley
> -&e->>Marina. The grass is never the same again.
> -&e->>     * 11.92 - vrave is born
> -&e->>     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv
> phasers". Niels refers to
> -&e->>"ravers with...forehead mounted
> love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
> -&e->>
> -&e->>Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full
> Moon parties, Come/Unity,
> -&e->>Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project,
> the Gathering, Deep Faith,
> -&e->>Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe,
> New Year's Eve Gathering.
> -&e->>1993
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves
> X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana
> -&e->>ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen
> to Spun's tape while skiing
> -&e->>the back country in Yosemite.
> -&e->>     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last
> Come/Unity.
> -&e->>     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a
> spot in northwest SF. Rain
> -&e->>forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but
> it is busted partway into
> -&e->>Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling,
> and a regrouping at the Cala
> -&e->>Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley
> Marina and rewards the SFRavers
> -&e->>who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays
> on one turntable for a while,
> -&e->>leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and
> Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still have
> -&e->>tapes :)
> -&e->>     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets
> together to throw a benefit
> -&e->>party for Malachy, who was seriously injured
> after the full moon party
> -&e->>early in March.
> -&e->>     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch
> begins. I think the first one was
> -&e->>at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed
> that it works better as a
> -&e->>bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
> -&e->>     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar
> from Brian.
> -&e->>     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field
> in San Francisco. This
> -&e->>started a string of Liquid Air parties,
> leading up to the first Friends and
> -&e->>Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of
> Liquid Air DJs included
> -&e->>Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee
> An, and Laura La Gassa.
> -&e->>     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and
> Bryce throw Connection Earth,
> -&e->>an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in
> Golden Gate Park.
> -&e->>
> -&e->>Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie
> Buffet, Together, Zanzibar,
> -&e->>Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid
> Groove
> -&e->>1994
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family
> goes off in the Blue Cube.
> -&e->>Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it
> all together after learning the
> -&e->>ropes with fluid groove and liquid air.
> Subsequent F&F's pack Klub Komotion
> -&e->>with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
> -&e->>     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the
> SFR-organized party "In the
> -&e->>Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
> -&e->>     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is
> moved to it.
> -&e->>
> -&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
> -&e->>1995: SFR: Friends & Family
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the
> web
> -&e->>     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a
> record 1080 messages over
> -&e->>the month.
> -&e->>     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows
> Komotion and produces the first
> -&e->>of two stellar parties in an Oakland
> warehouse. The F&F Collective grows to
> -&e->>many dozen people. The first is so wildly
> successful that 600 tickets for
> -&e->>the next F&F sell out in advance, in one
> weekend.
> -&e->>     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the
> country gather and celebrate
> -&e->>Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at
> Bonny Doon Beach. They are
> -&e->>married the next day.
> -&e->>
> -&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the
> Gardening Club, Frequency 8,
> -&e->>Area 51.
> -&e->>1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
> -&e->>SFR
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian
> Best Of The Bay 1999 Award
> -&e->>for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
> -&e->>
> -&e->>2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th
> Century
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B.
> March 1992
> -&e->>
> -&e->>2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st
> Century
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the
> Mix
> -&e->>     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
> -&e->>     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a
> party to Remember
> -&e->>     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is
> retired, new and improved
> -&e->>taz3.hyperreal.org is born
> -&e->>     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house
> party called Mexicon
> -&e->>     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable
> Renegade Party in Berkeley, CA
> -&e->>     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at
> the Oxygen Bar, leaves many
> -&e->>fond memories in the mind of Karina
> -&e->>     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and
> Michael Liu throw a fabulous
> -&e->>party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
> -&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in
> GGP
> -&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net

> -&e->>called Sunday of Slack
> -&e->>     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has
> a three year anniversary
> -&e->>party
> -&e->>     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a
> place for Junglists
> -&e->>
> -&e->>2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade
> Anniversary
> -&e->># SFR-P throws Amalagamation
> -&e->># 09.29.02 -
> -&e->>SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
> -&e->>A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY
> in the Park !!!
> -&e->>*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives
> ****
> -&e->>Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable
> day in the Sun, to enjoy and
> -&e->>celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship
> and experiences of SFRaves
> -&e->>over the past 10 years. Experience the
> celebration through the expression
> -&e->>of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a
> diverse memorabilia of
> -&e->>flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992
> - 2002. Sound provided by
> -&e->>Neuroscience Creations.
> -&e->>Your lineup is as follows:
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection,
> Hyperreal.org)
> -&e->>     * Ethan (Friends and Family)
> [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
> -&e->>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
> -&e->>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation,
> Resource Records)
> -&e->>[www.viberation.com]
> -&e->>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister,
> DNA, sfr-p, Teknique,
> -&e->>Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) &
> [www.djdragnfly.com]

> Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
> -&e->>
> -&e->>This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free
> refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm @
> -&e->>the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San
> Francisco, CA
> -&e->>* Map and Directions:
> http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
> -&e->>* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236
> **http://www.sfraves.org**

> Hyperreal/SFR interface for the
> -&e->>calendar are launched.

> -&e->>2003
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows
> in functionality, people and
> -&e->>size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with
> multiple features. Features are
> -&e->>updated to include enhancements in the Events
> Calendar, Event Calendar
> -&e->>Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
> -&e->>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years
> of age.
> -&e->>
> -&e->>2004
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface
> reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR
> -&e->>calendar features continue enhancement and
> shift direction to broaden scope
> -&e->>and improved Quality standards.
> -&e->>     * Updated features: Events Calendar,
> Event calendar Groups,
> -&e->>User/People profiles
> -&e->>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to
> 258 groups and 1666 people as
> -&e->>of September 2004!
> -&e->>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking
> revolution: SFRaves @
> -&e->>Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves
> @ Friendster.com, SFRaves
> -&e->>Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and
> SFRaves @ Orkut.com
> -&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12
> years strong!
> -&e->>
> -&e->>2005
> -&e->>
> -&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in
> reach, registration of Users,
> -&e->>Groups and features.
> -&e->>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13
> years and counting...
> -&e->>     * SFRaves continues branches out and
> networks nonstop. The community
> -&e->>has grown by leaps and bounds to include
> direct networking connections on
> -&e->>various sites on the web. As a result, both
> the user base and the breadth
> -&e->>of our community has an extended reach and
> continues to grow.
> -&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has
> skyrocketed to 310 groups and
> -&e->>1985 people as of January 2005!
> -&e->>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @
> Livejournal.com, SFRaves @
> -&e->>Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves
> Myspace Group, SFRaves @
> -&e->>Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
> -&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13

hello, this is a continuation of a fictional piece:
 
for a very long, long time, there was a man and that man was looking 
for a woman, and then he realized that there was nothing special or 
unique about that at all, and then, he began a quest for knowledge, realized 
that there was nothing unique or special about that at all either, and 
then he began to wonder, like many men do, and then suddenly he 
realized that all the things that he'd been doing were exactly like all of the 
things that many women do, and that made him feel even less unique and 
special, so then he decided to just climb into his cheap car and drive.  
that was when jane drove past him on the freeway:
 
"hey, that guy was just way to usual for me, but what is up with that 
skinny neck and bulging eyes in the next car up front. boy is that one 
ugly. just how i like them. can't tell if it is a man or  a woman 
though. wow, this is just like polishing my favorite rock from my rock 
collection from the last hike i took in the mountains." :)
