Subject: Re: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!

I agree and not because I was a part of it for a few years. That night was 
the unofficial SFRaves weekly party. I kinda feel the same about Progress @ 
Liquid in 1999 along with Eklektic @ 78 Minna. I met a LOT of people (Andy W 
with long hair) at 78 Minna before its unfortunate demise. The summer that I 
took control of things and sold the place out was unforgettable. No I'm not 
bragging it was really just an amazing few weeks of fun and good music. The 
first month was Epiphany, Viberation, Math Sound Workshop, and Liquid 
Mercury. Good f'ing times. It had to die for many reasons, but when it was 
at it's peak the night was magical. =)

>>Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,
>>
>>I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a 
>>community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful 
>>accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental, innovative, 
>>creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be cherished. Happy 
>>Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a birthday party for 
>>SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)
>>
>>http://www.sfraves.org/history/
>>http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf
>>
>>SFRaves History:
>>
>>A Brief History of SFRaves
>>
>>1992: SFRaves Connects
>>
>>     * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The 
>> address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
>>     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs. 
>> the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves 
>> button, now a collector's item :).
>>     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin 
>> Miller Park.
>>     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
>>     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for 
>> Bonny Doon.
>>     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a 
>> better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod 
>> u+x, Contact, Outernet.
>>     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. 
>> Word eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of 
>> also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
>>     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear 
>> that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
>>     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu 
>> (aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
>>     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the 
>> Berkeley Marina. The grass is never the same again.
>>     * 11.92 - vrave is born
>>     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to 
>> "ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
>>
>>Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity, 
>>Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith, 
>>Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
>>1993
>>
>>     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana 
>> ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while 
>> skiing the back country in Yosemite.
>>     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
>>     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain 
>> forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into 
>> Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala 
>> Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers 
>> who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a 
>> while, leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may 
>> still have tapes :)
>>     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefit 
>> party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party 
>> early in March.
>>     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was 
>> at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a 
>> bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
>>     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
>>     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This 
>> started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends 
>> and Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs 
>> included Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La 
>> Gassa.
>>     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection 
>> Earth, an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.
>>
>>Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar, 
>>Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
>>1994
>>
>>     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube. 
>> Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning 
>> the ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub 
>> Komotion with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
>>     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the 
>> Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
>>     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.
>>
>>Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
>>1995: SFR: Friends & Family
>>
>>     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
>>     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over 
>> the month.
>>     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first 
>> of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows 
>> to many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets 
>> for the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
>>     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate 
>> Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are 
>> married the next day.
>>
>>Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8, 
>>Area 51.
>>1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
>>SFR
>>
>>     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award 
>> for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
>>
>>2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century
>>
>>     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992
>>
>>2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century
>>
>>     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
>>     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
>>     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
>>     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved 
>> taz3.hyperreal.org is born
>>     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
>>     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, 
>> CA
>>     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves many 
>> fond memories in the mind of Karina
>>     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous 
>> party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
>>     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
>>     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindig 
>> called Sunday of Slack
>>     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary 
>> party
>>     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists
>>
>>2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
>># SFR-P throws Amalagamation
>># 09.29.02 -
>>SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
>>A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
>>*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
>>Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and 
>>celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves 
>>over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression 
>>of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of 
>>flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by 
>>Neuroscience Creations.
>>Your lineup is as follows:
>>
>>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
>>     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
>>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
>>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records) 
>> [www.viberation.com]
>>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique, 
>> Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
>>     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
>>
>>This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm 
>>@ the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
>>* Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
>>* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
>># SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for the 
>>calendar are launched.
>>SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes
>>
>>
>>SFR Calendar
>>
>>Calendar
>>
>>Groups
>>
>>People profiles
>>
>>Polls
>>
>>2003
>>
>>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people and 
>> size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are 
>> updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar 
>> Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
>>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.
>>
>>2004
>>
>>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR 
>> calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden 
>> scope and improved Quality standards.
>>     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups, 
>> User/People profiles
>>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as 
>> of September 2004!
>>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @ 
>> Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves 
>> Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
>>
>>2005
>>
>>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users, 
>> Groups and features.
>>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
>>     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community 
>> has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on 
>> various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth 
>> of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
>>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups 
>> and 1985 people as of January 2005!
>>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ 
>> Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @ 
>> Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!
>>
>>Would you like to add to SFRaves.org history? Please send comments, 
>>suggestions and other stories to karina@hyperreal.org
>>
>>Thanks!
>>
>>Karina
>>
>>--
>>**************************************************************
>>******************>karina@hyperreal.org<**********************
>>If there is a sin against life, it consists perhaps not so
>>much in despairing of life as in hoping for another life
>>& in eluding the implacable grandeur of this life.
>>-- Albert Camus -- *******************************************
>>**************************************************************
>>

>>For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] BSP:  Furious 2 - Tomorrow! Saturday!

if you want techno and downtempo on saturday, i highly recommend "Is-As" 
from DEF:SF (www.defsf.com).


if you want breaks, dnb and house on saturday, i openly invite you to...

FURIOUS 2
Saturday, January 29th
9pm-5am
4 rooms rockin' to the breakadawn

Lasers and lighting provided by Stimulights - www.stimulights.com
Live visuals provided by Satsi (Lush Camp)

Featuring:

Lobudg - Live (Sober Music/Play records) - Austin, TX
Lobudg is the combination of S.O.T.E.G. aka Bil Bless and Dave Cannon, the 
man behind Carbon Community. This show will be their debut performace as 
Lobudg, as they perform for the first time for us in SF before heading out 
on a WMC tour. With their couple of releases already getting massive support 
from the breaks community, these are two artists to definitely keep your eye 
on.

Evil Breaks room:
Drag'nfly vs Aaron Jae (Love Tribe/Shaolin/Evil Breaks) - Special Breaks set
DJ Ripple (Subscience)
Bam (Evil Breaks/Invibe.com)
Nick Nyquil (Evil Breaks/Ill Behavior)
Athena vs Influence (Evil Breaks/In tha Mix)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)
Maebyn La Fey(Subscience)

Subscience DnB room:
THE INVISIBLES - LIVE - Check em out
(featuring SF dnb champions Abstract, Qzen, and Kimi)
Method One (www.method-one.com)
dj M (Faultline/SOMA Sessions)
Bicolas (Rhythm Method/Skills)
the Hitmen (Subscience)
MC Souljah
MC Manny Vibes

Cruz
w/ Indidjinous on didjeridoo (Enter the Jungle)
Reclipse (Bayraves, Discharge Clothing)
Yagi (OTC, HCFTP)

Ill Behavior room:
Denise (djdenise.com/sound asylum)
Erig Riggsbee vs Clockwork (Breakthru)
Homero (Yerba Buena Records)
Hyjinx vs Ill D (Thought Crime)
Thomas Kent vs Kris Kent (Ill Behavior/Modified)
Element (Modified)
Emune vs Cmos (Ill Behavior)

Zapatistas house room:
Felipe Avelar (House Nation/Zapatistas)
DJ Doza (BR/Zapatistas/E. Ave)
Carlos Alfonzo (Soop/Zapatistas/BR)
Elektro (Electronic Ave.)

Misha (Subscience)

Tickets are now available online at:
www.groovetickets.com
and in Skills, Reverb, and Solid Grooves.

tonight at 1015.

>> the expression of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse 
>> memorabilia of flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. 
>> Sound provided by Neuroscience Creations.
>> Your lineup is as follows:
>>
>>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
>>     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
>>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
>>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records) 
>> [www.viberation.com]
>>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique, 
>> Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
>>     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance 
>> (Drag'nfly)
>>
>> This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 
>> 12pm-6pm @ the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
>> * Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
>> * Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
>> # SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for 
>> the calendar are launched.
>> SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes

>> SFR Calendar

>> Calendar
>>
>> Groups
>>
>> People profiles
>>
>> Polls

>> 2003
>>
>>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people 
>> and size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. 
>> Features are updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, 
>> Event Calendar Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
>>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.
>>
>> 2004
>>
>>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR 
>> calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden 
>> scope and improved Quality standards.
>>     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups, 
>> User/People profiles
>>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people 
>> as of September 2004!
>>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @ 
>> Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, 
>> SFRaves Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
>>
>> 2005
>>
>>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of 
>> Users, Groups and features.
>>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
>>     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The 
>> community has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking 
>> connections on various sites on the web. As a result, both the user 
>> base and the breadth of our community has an extended reach and 
>> continues to grow.
>>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 
>> groups and 1985 people as of January 2005!
>>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ 
>> Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @ 
>> Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!

dah when I first went to Ascension it was to meet Ryan and I had just moved 
here and didn't know anyone and I just wandered around asking folk who Ryan 
was and where he was and they just laughed at me cuz it was Ryan.  That's 
how I met everyone basically.  Had some of the best times of my life playing 
there, so much youthful energy and most everyone knew each other, even 
impressed on my current lady though I didn't know it at the time, so 
Ascension is still paying me dividends three years later.  :)

I remember one night after he played there Joey Mazzola told me about how 
that first summer I lived there had been a bit slow but once next summer 
rolled around and kicked in like years past and I knew more people I'd be 
playing like 7 nights a week.  Then everything imploded on itself and he 
moved to Vegas.  Wouldn've been fun to actually live out here during the 
rise and peak of things but I guess I got to see it in my own way back 
home...but yeah Ascension was my introduction to just about everyone on 
here.

---------- Forwarded message ----------
Date: Sat, 29 Jan 2005 00:52:57 UT
From: norcaldjmpa-news@norcaldjmpa.com
To: karina@hyperreal.org
Subject: [NorCalDJMPA] Qbert, Jazzy Jeff, Grand Wizard Theodore this Saturday

Please go to http://www.norcaldjmpa.com/newsletter3jan05.htm for the HTML version of the newsletter.

     Whether you're into turntablism, house, hip-hop, or breaks, some of the
     world's best DJs will be coming to the Bay Area in the next week! Check out
     the details below.

     [DNA_Jan_29]

     History of Scratch Tour with Qbert, Jazzy Jeff, Grand Wizard Theodore this
     Saturday:

     The History of Scratch Tour hits San Francisco's DNA Lounge this Saturday,
     January 29. Three legendary DJs representing the pinnacle of scratch DJing in
     their respective generations will be performing: Grand Wizard Theodore, the
     creator of scratch technique; DJ Jazzy Jeff, the master of the transformer
     style; and DJ Qbert, scratch DJ supreme. Also performing will be DJ Flare and
     DJ Jumi. Catch the NorCalDJMPA's table at the event, and chat with some of
     our instructors about our DJ and electronic music production programs!

     History of Scratch Tour featuring Qbert, Jazzy Jeff, and Grand Wizard
     Theodore
     Saturday, January 29. 10pm-2am.
     21 and up. $20 presale tickets @ DNALounge.com.
     375 11th Street
     San Francisco, CA 94103

     NorCalDJMPA Open House featuring free seminars, Wednesday, February 16:

     The NorCalDJMPA Open House seminar series continues in February with free
     seminars by DJ Goldenchyld and DJ Dimitris Mykonos! DJ Goldenchyld, a member
     of the Fingerbangerz DJ crew, is one of the best battle DJs the Bay Area has
     produced, with a record including DMC and ITF championships. DJ Dimitris
     Mykonos is one of the most prominent DJs in the San Francisco dance music
     scene, continually packing clubs whereever he spins.

     Following the seminars there will be an open scratch session!

     NorCalDJMPA Open House featuring free seminars by DJ Goldenchyld and DJ
     Dimitris Mykonos
     Wednesday, February 16. 6pm-8pm.
     600 Townsend St. Suite 190W
     San Francisco, CA 94103
     Building doors lock at 8:00pm, call (415) 255-8789 after hours.

     DJDreamteam 2005 @ Ruby Skye, Thursday, February 3: The Bay Area's Top 10 DJs
     as selected by Nitevibe.com will be spinning at the third annual DJDreamteam
     event at San Francisco's Ruby Skye! Some of San Francisco's best house and
   _ breaks DJs will be under one roof this night at this sure-to-sell-out event,
     including Miguel Migs, Mark Farina, Lorin, M3, Laird, Jeno, Ellen Ferrato,
     Smoove, and Jondi & Spesh!

     DJDreamteam 2005 @ Ruby Skye
     Thursday, February 3. 7:30pm-afterhours.
     21 and up. $20.
     420 Mason Street @ Geary
     San Francisco, CA 94102

     B-side Showdown, Sunday, January 30: The first B-side Records Monthly
     Showdown of the year is this Sunday, proudly sponsored by the NorCalDJMPA and
     U.C. Berkeley Students for Hip Hop. The Bay Area's best top up-and-coming
     turntablists will be showcasing their best, and there will also be a mixing
     competition this month! To enter the competition, contact B-side Records at
     (510) 548-4882.

     B-Side Records Showdown
     Sunday, January 30.1:00-5:00pm.
     All ages. Free admission.
     2128 Dwight Way
     Berkeley, CA, 94704
     -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

     Grand Wizard Theodore visits NorCalDJMPA, January 24: Grand Wizard Theodore,
     the inventor of scratching, gave a guest lecture during the NorCalDJMPA's
     DJ101: Turntable Basics for the Art of DJing class this week. Bringing along
     his friend, fellow scratching legend DJ Qbert, Grand Wizard Theodore spoke
     about the creation of scratching and DJ history, as well as gave a
     demonstration of the DJ techniques he pioneered - scratching and needle
     dropping.

     NorCalDJMPA Open House, January 13: Every month, the NorCal DJ Academy
     features free seminars by innovative DJs and cutting-edge electronic music
     producers. January's Open House event featured a seminar by DJ Spair,
     award-winning mixtape DJ, and veteran of numerous mix competitions. During
     his seminar on the Art of the Mixtape, DJ Spair discussed techniques for
     making a mix set and gave a live demonstration of his trick-mixing skills.
     Visit the NorCalDJMPA on February 16 for seminars from DJ Goldenchyld and DJ
     Dimitris Mykonos. Details are above.

AndyW wrote:

>Yeah, and the gap at 1997-2000 is a weird one, seeing as list membership
>was highest during those years.
>
>I'd like to sit down with some people that were active during that period
>that I don't really know all that well and figure out what should be
>added.
>
>Considering some of the most incredible parties I ever attended happened
>during that time period...
>
>Gateway Systems - Chrysalis (gateway wasn't too into SFR, but you saw a
>lot of SFR kids at Gateway events)
>
>Harmony - Wrinkle in Time, Beautiful People, Freaky People, 3 year at Camp
>Swig, Spring Massive
>
>FnF's first campouts and expanding underground offerrings
>
>Cloud Factory growing outside the Monterey/Salinas roots
>
>Viberation - in many ways the most SFR involved collective (terry + mikem
>+ andyw + siphon + science + micron + li... all active SFR netizens).
>
>ASR - Always a balancing act between Jeremy (and later Tony's) vision and
>a collective wtih a lot of, the result was a lot of good parties.
>
>Happy Kids - while I had issues with the crew at the time, they really did
>come up with some of the best spaces and had a fanatical following.
>
>NBC - Petaluma / Sonoma / San Rafael freaks.
>
>Children of the Sun - While burning a few bridges in the process, COTS
>managed to bust a party every couple weeks for a while there, and managed
>to create a lot of memories.
>
>Warmth - I was never a big Spencer fan, but lots of people "got it"  in
>the crew, and they did have their hearts in the right place.
>
>BBQ & Beats - Not too many parties, but one of my favorite completely
>illegal renegades of all time... a 3 day free outdoor campout with ZERO
>permits, $10 for meals all weekend from a champion BBQ cook, and the
>craziest mix of genres I've ever heard at one party.
>
>Orphan - East bay nutters.
>
>Oh shit, and that first light where $20 got you Entrance.
>
>The crackhouse on 13th.  Acme warehouse, the old dance studio, the old
>clementina alley spot, psytrance, casa z, the old f8 studio/hangar in
>north bay, the phoenix, 2nd and jax, homebase, richmond point molate,
>static, mad, sabotage, eklectic, bass kru...
>
>How good were those parties?  I'll put it this way... so many of the
>people I met at those events, are still going... while I've seen people
>that got into it years later totally fall out after a year or two.  Could
>it have been that the parties back then were *that* good?  I dunno, seems
>like a strange ommission as far as time stretch... this was the second
>underground that came out of the cave-in that started in 94.  Everybody
>had given up on it, but it was still going... not running on nostalgia...
>we were still mentally young but wiser than newbies, still loving it, the
>scene had a great cross section of it with people from 15 to 65 attending
>the same parties with the same enthusiasm, there were parties where "vibe"
>was not a glassy eyed dream but a tangible fog of friendly sweat and
>intentions, and we were just high as fark on what we were doing.
>
>In the end, not sure how much of an effect it had as a movement or
>whatever, but I know a lot of people that are forever changed.  Some for
>worse, most for better I think.  The big parties nowadays are still
>plagued by the same cost cutting, limits on freedom and ethical
>shortcuts... but there was a period where several thousand people were
>involved in a very alive, very optimistic and vital underground that I'm
>not sure will ever happen again here.
>
>andyw
>
>andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy
>\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/\/
>"Nothing real can defeat us.  Nothing unreal exists." - Buckaroo Banzai

>-&e->>Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,
>-&e->>
>-&e->>I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a
>-&e->>community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful
>-&e->>accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental, innovative,
>-&e->>creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be cherished. Happy
>-&e->>Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a birthday party for
>-&e->>SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)
>-&e->>
>-&e->>http://www.sfraves.org/history/
>-&e->>http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf
>-&e->>
>-&e->>SFRaves History:
>-&e->>
>-&e->>A Brief History of SFRaves
>-&e->>
>-&e->>1992: SFRaves Connects
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The
>-&e->>address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
>-&e->>     * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs.
>-&e->>the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves
>-&e->>button, now a collector's item :).
>-&e->>     * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin
>-&e->>Miller Park.
>-&e->>     * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
>-&e->>     * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for Bonny
>-&e->>Doon.
>-&e->>     * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a
>-&e->>better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod u+x,
>-&e->>Contact, Outernet.
>-&e->>     * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. Word
>-&e->>eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of
>-&e->>also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
>-&e->>     * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear
>-&e->>that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
>-&e->>     * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu
>-&e->>(aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
>-&e->>     * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the Berkeley
>-&e->>Marina. The grass is never the same again.
>-&e->>     * 11.92 - vrave is born
>-&e->>     * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to
>-&e->>"ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity,
>-&e->>Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith,
>-&e->>Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
>-&e->>1993
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dana
>-&e->>ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while skiing
>-&e->>the back country in Yosemite.
>-&e->>     * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
>-&e->>     * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain
>-&e->>forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into
>-&e->>Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala
>-&e->>Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers
>-&e->>who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a while,
>-&e->>leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still have
>-&e->>tapes :)
>-&e->>     * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefit
>-&e->>party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party
>-&e->>early in March.
>-&e->>     * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was
>-&e->>at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a
>-&e->>bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
>-&e->>     * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
>-&e->>     * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This
>-&e->>started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends and
>-&e->>Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs included
>-&e->>Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La Gassa.
>-&e->>     * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection Earth,
>-&e->>an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar,
>-&e->>Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
>-&e->>1994
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube.
>-&e->>Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning the
>-&e->>ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub Komotion
>-&e->>with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
>-&e->>     * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the
>-&e->>Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
>-&e->>     * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
>-&e->>1995: SFR: Friends & Family
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
>-&e->>     * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over
>-&e->>the month.
>-&e->>     * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first
>-&e->>of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows to
>-&e->>many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets for
>-&e->>the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
>-&e->>     * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate
>-&e->>Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are
>-&e->>married the next day.
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8,
>-&e->>Area 51.
>-&e->>1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
>-&e->>SFR
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award
>-&e->>for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
>-&e->>     * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
>-&e->>     * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
>-&e->>     * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved
>-&e->>taz3.hyperreal.org is born
>-&e->>     * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
>-&e->>     * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, CA
>-&e->>     * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves many
>-&e->>fond memories in the mind of Karina
>-&e->>     * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous
>-&e->>party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
>-&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
>-&e->>     * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindig
>-&e->>called Sunday of Slack
>-&e->>     * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary
>-&e->>party
>-&e->>     * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
>-&e->># SFR-P throws Amalagamation
>-&e->># 09.29.02 -
>-&e->>SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
>-&e->>A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
>-&e->>*** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
>-&e->>Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and
>-&e->>celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves
>-&e->>over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression
>-&e->>of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of
>-&e->>flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by
>-&e->>Neuroscience Creations.
>-&e->>Your lineup is as follows:
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
>-&e->>     * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
>-&e->>     * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
>-&e->>     * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records)
>-&e->>[www.viberation.com]
>-&e->>     * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique,
>-&e->>Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
>-&e->>     * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
>-&e->>
>-&e->>This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm @
>-&e->>the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
>-&e->>* Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
>-&e->>* Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**
>-&e->># SFR Calendar is redesigned and a new Hyperreal/SFR interface for the
>-&e->>calendar are launched.
>-&e->>SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface includes
>-&e->>
>-&e->>
>-&e->>SFR Calendar
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Calendar
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Groups
>-&e->>
>-&e->>People profiles
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Polls
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2003
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people and
>-&e->>size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are
>-&e->>updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar
>-&e->>Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls
>-&e->>     * SFRaves continues to grow at 11 years of age.
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2004
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR
>-&e->>calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden scope
>-&e->>and improved Quality standards.
>-&e->>     * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups,
>-&e->>User/People profiles
>-&e->>     * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as
>-&e->>of September 2004!
>-&e->>     * SFRaves has joined the Networking revolution: SFRaves @
>-&e->>Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves
>-&e->>Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>-&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
>-&e->>
>-&e->>2005
>-&e->>
>-&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users,
>-&e->>Groups and features.
>-&e->>     * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
>-&e->>     * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community
>-&e->>has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on
>-&e->>various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth
>-&e->>of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
>-&e->>     * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups and
>-&e->>1985 people as of January 2005!
>-&e->>     * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @
>-&e->>Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @
>-&e->>Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>-&e->>     * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Would you like to add to SFRaves.org history? Please send comments,
>-&e->>suggestions and other stories to karina@hyperreal.org
>-&e->>
>-&e->>Thanks!

I've een scrolling through SFR gems I saved over the
years.  Here's one from Brian B when the list was
going through some growing pains.

-boom
.....................
Date: Tue, 25 Nov 1997 
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
From: Brian Behlendorf <brian@hyperreal.org>
Subject: about this list


To paraphrase Tim Leary,

  What SFRAVES is,

     is UP TO YOU.

Just as you could really never throw a party to make
everyone happy, it's
impossible to have a mailing list which covers such a
wide range as SFRaves
where everyone feels every message was worth the time
it took to download.
However, splintering the list sounds like a really bad
idea too.  

SO....

We need to learn how to get along with each other.  We
need to recognize
that this isn't just an events notification service
(if you want that,
subscribe to sfraves), isn't just a DJ-identification
service or
ride-to-party service.  This is a discussion forum for
rave culture in the
northern california SF bay area.  What is discussion
about culture?  It's
talk about the parties, it's talk about the music and
DJ's, but it's also
talk about the personalities, both off and on the
list, and in the best of
all worlds, it's its own culture, one which
fractalizes into new parties
and communities.  

This list is going to be noisy, by necessity; raving
is about far more than
just showing up at a warehouse one night and dancing. 
Raving is far more
personal than most other endeavors, and as the
ultimate subjective
experience, set, setting, and state of mind are all
necessary for context.
Anecdotes are the lifeblood of the list.  Remember
that what's noise to you
could be a trigger for another person's
earth-shattering thought.

Fortunately, there are a wide array of tools, even
free ones, to filter the
"noise" - almost any mail client out there can filter
out messages based on
the sender or content of the message.   Do yourself a
favor and seek them
out and learn how to use them.

HOWEVER

The fact that there are such tools isn't an excuse to
be thoughtless about
what you post.  "Just hit delete" is also not entirely
a solution, since
everyone has to download it anyways, and we're not all
on ISDN connections
yet!  (I'm still on 28.8 at home, btw).  Before you
hit that "send" button,
please think about what you're sending, and if it
might be better as a
private message.  Realize there are 475 people on the
sfraves list who will
be getting your message.  With that tremendous power
of distribution also
comes a degree of responsibility.  

Overall I'm *extremely* happy with what SFRaves is,
and has been over the
last 5 years.  I'm still subscribed and reading it
obviously :)  The thread
on "respect" has been tremendously cool, as have been
many other recent
messages.  

Thoughts?

        Brian


--=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=--
"it's a big world, with lots of records to play."-sig 
 brian@hyperreal.org

From: "petersandifer@sbcglobal.net" <petersandifer@sbcglobal.net>

Subject: [sfraves] "Harmony is back to throwing smaller parties."  --andyw, 1998

here's another keeper.  it's easy to get lost in the
nostalgia.  i might have re-posted this once before.

boom
...................


Date: Wed, 7 Jan 1998 
From: AndyW <andy@saturn5.com>
To: Faro <Faro@usa.net>
cc: SFRaves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: What is Right in the Scene.

On Wed, 7 Jan 1998, Faro wrote:

>       It seems that there are a lot of things that
are WRONG in the 
> scene right now. Could someone please tell me what
is RIGHT in the 
> scene.
> 
> Thanks
> -Faro
> 

The music is at times amazing.

Some people are still down to earth.

Harmony is back to throwing smaller parties (even
though I loved John Williams at the Massive like I
have never loved a sober set before or
since).

E is still $20, despite several years of inflation.

House parties.

Cari Lekebush is still making records.

There is no single cool thing to do.

Really clean sounding sound reinforcement equipment is
dropping in price.

Digital recording can be done at home for almost
nothing if you have a PC.

Vinyl is still alive and well.

Friends and Family, Cloud Factory, BBQ & Beats,
Viberation, Lepidoptera,
Gateway (and all the other collectives!).

Baggy clothes made of soft fabrics.

Small parties can sometimes still play host to big
names.

Cabin parties.

A genuine smile from someone you know you'll end up
being friends with.

There are more subgenres of techno than there are
ravers, I think.

WBL still plays once in a blue moon.

If you're in a good mood, you can still show up to
just about any party
and have a good time.

Night air coming into a hot, sweaty building through a
window.

Free water.

Love.

Ridiculously heavy bass.

Leaving your backpack on the floor, and not really
worrying about it.

We still have chill rooms at some parties.

Mendecino/Humboldt's finest.

ReBirth-338.

Bill Gates can't see you... yet.

Green Extra still glows under blacklight.

Dancing makes more sense as I get older.

There is a part of the scene that really doesn't care
about money.

It's still possible to wake up on Saturday morning,
and decide to throw a renegade that night.

I have a photo of Greg and Micron in drag.

People are usually much nicer in person than on the
net.

You can use SFRaves as a shrink, paging service, info
line, support group,
or record hunting tool anytime day or night.

Less random psychedlic bullshit, more thematic party
decorations.

Hyperreal goes down less often than our corporate E
mail server (uh... I don't administer that one,
okay?).

People's Park, the Marina and Point Molate still go
great with Sunday afternoon sunshine and good house
music.

Most ravers are still going at 5am.

Some promoters still base their lineups on musical
flow rather than on
draw vs. cost.

I'm hearing the word "drama" less now... and seeing
less meth use.

The Primal used bin, and the techno section at Solid
Grooves.

Sooner or later, good or bad, people tend to get what
they deserve.

Power bars and blow pops are both available at Costco
(as well as 5000
watt generators for $500).

Smiling shows no signs of becoming illegal despite
recent conservative trends in government.

I think we haven't seen the last of parties that serve
fresh fruit in the morning.

Not everybody concentrates on the negative.

Peace,
AndyW


---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Date: Tue, 11 Aug 1998 
From: Arthur Chandler <arthurc@sfsu.edu>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: BB Makes The Big Time!

   I was reading through the online edition of
*Forbes* magazine, when I
came across this passage:

   "Apache, the group that IBM coveted, is an example
of the informality that rules in the freeware world. 
Brian Behlendorf, 25, helped to start
it all. Back in 1991 he was organizing all-night
techno dance parties known as "raves." "The first day
50 people signed up.  I knew there was
something there." At one rave on Bonny Doon beach near
Santa Cruz, Calif. 3,000 people showed up. The only
promotion was via E-mail and word of mouth."

      "After finding a job building Wired magazine's
Web site through a rave acquaintance, Behlendorf
decided the Web server software he was using  needed
improvement. He made a few of his own,
then posted the new version, with source code, on the
Internet. Code contributionspoured in and thus was
born Apache, which today serves up more than 50% of
the Internet's Web sites, including those of Internet
top dog Yahoo!. Apache knocked Netscape's
closed-source Web server out of the running for the
cornerstone of IBM's Web commerce package." 
---------------

  The whole essay can be found at:
     
http://www.forbes.com/forbes/98/0810/6209094a.htm

Hello to all Morgellons Research Foundation Registrants.

We are pleased to announce the following upcoming media events:

Sunday February 6, 2005 there will be yet another FOX news health report =
on Morgellons Disease aired by KTVU Oakland/San Francisco California at =
10pm Pacific.  This is the third in an ongoing series on this disease by =
KTVU.  KTVU will continue to follow this story until the answer is at =
hand. I can assure you that the people at KTVU are very troubled by the =
suffering caused by this disease. This report will focus on the death of =
Dillon King, a Morgellons' registrant who died on January 5, 2005.  =
Sadly, Dillon took his own life.  His girlfriend Elizabeth Strong, as =
well as his personal physician, will express their concerns about the =
lack of official recognition of this disease, as well as the difficult =
time Dillon had getting a parade of physicians to investigate his skin =
lesions. Dillon had been told repeatedly that fibers emerging from his =
lesions were suture material from old surgical wounds.   In addition, a =
nurse and also a microbiologist, who are both personally affected by =
this disease were interviewed for this news segment.
http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2005/January/12/obit/obit.htm

Monday, February 7, 2005 there will be a FOX News health report on =
Morgellons Disease in Florida which will air in Jacksonville. This =
report will air the day after the Super Bowl, which will take place in =
Jacksonville.  Promotional teaser ads for the news report will be shown =
on the two stadium Jumbotrons (giant display screens) during the Super =
Bowl on February 6 in Alltel Stadium. The ads will not be seen at home, =
but will be seen by 76,000 Super Bowl spectators.
http://www.jaxevents.com/alltelstadium/

Links for these two reports will be sent to you, once the stations have =
sent the links to us.

Big hug to all.
Love,
Mary Leitao,  Executive Director
Douglas Buckner, Ph.D.,  Associate Director
Kenneth Cowles,  Media and Public Relations Director
Morgellons Research Foundation
http://www.morgellons.org/

> --- AndyW <andy@saturn5.com> wrote:
> > In the end, not sure how much of an effect it had as a movement or
> > whatever, but I know a lot of people that are forever changed.

True enuff!!

> > Some for
> > worse, most for better I think.  The big parties nowadays are still
> > plagued by the same cost cutting, limits on freedom and ethical
> > shortcuts... but there was a period where several thousand people
> > were
> > involved in a very alive, very optimistic and vital underground that
> > I'm
> > not sure will ever happen again here.

The guy who wrote "Generation Ecstasy" had a great turn of phrase for
it, he called a scene a magical cocktail of chemicals, music, people,
and moments, or something like that.

But --

After the summer of love in the late 80s people in England were saying
that "it" would never happen again.

In LA after the early 90s people were saying "it" would never happen again.

In Chicago after the MID 80s people were saying "it" would never happen again.

"It" is always happening. "It" comes and "it" goes.

There's a great book on black magic, also known as left-hand-path
magic, which gives some fascinating exercises in mind control. Before
you piss your pants in terror, I mean mind control in the sense of
being able to control your own mind. Not being able to control your
own mind is like not being able to drive your own car -- it's a very
dangerous situation, you can see it on the highway any day of the
week, and most people who have the problem are absolutely certain that
they don't.

Anyway -- the exercise I'm thinking of is called "Travel without
moving." It's got nothing to do with Astral Projection, or even astral
projection. It's about the fact that very few people ever truly
explore the world they live in. Even a single block in a city will
have countless worlds you never enter. The idea of "Travel without
moving" is to take a vacation from being who you are. It's a neat
exercise.

I'm going to offer a stripped-down, simplified version which carries
absolutely no risk of obsession, psychosis, hallucination, or bad
breath.

(Because I know some of you out there have no fear of diving down
mountains headfirst or even SMOKING CRACK, yet you quail at the idea
of a mental exercise.)

The simplified, risk-free version for sweet little ravers is this: if
you think the scene is stagnant, or less alive, or less vibrant, then
IMMEDIATELY, the next time someone says "are you going to blah blah
blah party?" say NO and find some other party to go to instead.

Because --

"It" is always happening. "It" is ALWAYS vibrant, "it" is always
alive, and "it" is always UNDERGROUND.

And "it" can never die.

The ever-vibrant underground actually **left** sfraves@hyperreal.org
during the dot-com boom, when the list had so many subscribers that
BSPing an underground here was not safe any longer. (It may have come
back since then.) Many people at that time, myself included,
interpreted that disappearance as the death of the underground, but
that was not the case. As I said, "it" cannot die.

"It" is always SOMEWHERE.

"It" COMMANDS ME to drink more COFFEE.


Giles

---------------------------------------------------------------------

For additional commands, e-mail: sfraves-help@hyperreal.org

Subject: [sfraves] another blast from the past....

Good stuff to recall and remember.... this community was never the
same...

Hello sfr,
Sent on Tue 9/1/1998 from ascend@ix.netcom.com Greg/Harmony...

"As some of you have heard already, my roomate/ partner (Harmonics
Records and Clothing Store), Erik Brown was a passenger in a head on
collision last Sunday morning. I don't know the gorry details of what
happened, who's fault, etc. But I do know that Erik is now in Intesive
Care with a broken back and torn tummy, his driver got his face ripped
off (but was quikly put back together, and looks ok), and the other
driver involved has died. Erik's broken back has affected his lower
portion of his spinal cord, and right now he is completely paralized
from the waist down. He had some sort of surgury today, and we are
awaiting the results for tomorrow. (Cross your
fingers)

Appearently, the other driver was extreemly intoxicated, while Erik's
driver was not at all, but still we don't know who was the one that
drifted over the median and caused the accident. This is a really big
blow to the Sonoma County scene. All of our friends have been outting in
a huge amount of positive energy to this situation, and we would all
apprieciate it if you could just send some love to Erik (and everyone
else involved). Everyone could use it right now.  

We will be organizing a series of benefit parties for him in the very
near future, so keep your ears open, and please support them. (100% of
proceeds will go straight to Erik)

Stay tuned,

Peace and love,

Greg = )

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SFRaves makes history! SFR is a te0enager!

Whoa, I'm born in March too!=20

As is Alexander Graham Bell, Jacqueline Joyner-Kersee, Tone Loc, (the
four of us share the same-B-day, the 3rd), Albert Einstein, Theodor
Seuss Giesel, Desi Arnaz, Jane Goodall, Michelangelo, Piet Mondrian,
Amerigo Vespucci, Leland Stanford, (founder of a school Brian was at
during SFRaves gestation period), Rupert Murdock, Josef Mengele,
Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, (can't avoid a little evil in the
mix I guess), Edward Franklin Albee, Spike Lee, Andrew Lloyd Webber,
Elton John, Tennessee Williams, Cy Young, Pearl Bailey, Vincent van
Gogh, Rene Descartes, and Elected President of the United States,
2000, Albert Gore.

For the most part, that's good company all.....

Now, if SFRaves is a Pisces baby, (is it? that part isn't clear), then
you can add Kurt Cobain to the above as having something in common,
since he was born in late February.

DCRaves is almost as old as SFRaves and maybe we can have mirror
parties to celebrate, on both coasts, Raverg has a member who is
itching to do real-time, video-conferencing between parties at remote
locations, and this strikes me as a great way to do a run through on a
project like that.

Suggestion:

In Jewish Culture they have a way of acknowledging that you've come of
age at the age of 13, via a ritual party that they call a Bar/Bat
Mitzvah.

Mebbe we can theme the party out along those lines, if one was so inclined.

I'm just sayin...'

On Fri, 28 Jan 2005 00:36:55 -0800 (PST), Karina <karina@hyperreal.org> wro=
te:
> Dear SFRaves Community and Brian Behlendorf,
>=20
> I wanted to take the time to appreciate the fact that SFRaves as a
> community and a resource is turning 13 this year! What a wonderful
> accomplishment. Thank you for being such an instrumental,
> innovative, creation. SFRaves and Hyperreal are a treasure to be
> cherished. Happy Birthday! (coming in March) SFRaves! We should have a
> birthday party for SFRaves / Hyperreal .org :)
>=20
> http://www.sfraves.org/history/
> http://www.hyperreal.org/raves/sf
>=20
> SFRaves History:
>=20
> A Brief History of SFRaves
>=20
> 1992: SFRaves Connects
>=20
>      * 3.92 - SFRaves is born. Brian Behlendorf is the proud daddy. The
> address at the time is sfraves@petrus.berkeley.edu.
>      * 4.11.92 - Battle of the Juggernauts: Toon Town's UFO's are Real vs=
.
> the Gathering. Many SFRavers meet for the first time. I get my SFRaves
> button, now a collector's item :).
>      * 5.2.92 - The first SFRaves picnic, over in the East Bay at Joaquin
> Miller Park.
>      * 5.92 - SFRaves moves to soda.berkeley.edu.
>      * 7.92 - Plans begin for the first big SFRaves bash, planned for Bon=
ny
> Doon.
>      * 7.30.92 - After some prodding, Brian realizes "Connection" is a
> better name than "Conn-X-tion". Other rejected names: DeepByte, chmod u+x=
,
> Contact, Outernet.
>      * 8.20.92 - Connection goes off in a big way at Bonny Doon Beach. Wo=
rd
> eventually reaches the full moon massive, which hold a series of
> also-legendary parties there in the coming months.
>      * 9.25.92 - SFR produces Alternity in the basement of 1015. We fear
> that the show "48 Hours" would film there, but they don't show.
>      * 9.92 - SFRaves outgrows soda and is moved to medisg.stanford.edu
> (aka sfraves.stanford.edu and techno.stanford.edu)
>      * 11.92 - Brian discovers a "HUGE squarish open space" in the Berkel=
ey
> Marina. The grass is never the same again.
>      * 11.92 - vrave is born
>      * 12.9.92 - first-known reference to "luv phasers". Niels refers to
> "ravers with...forehead mounted love-phasers...enforcing positive vibes"
>=20
> Other highlights: Sundays in Marx Meadow, Full Moon parties, Come/Unity,
> Wicked, Woopy Ball, Osmosis, Housing Project, the Gathering, Deep Faith,
> Sharon, Equinox, Basics, Funky Tekno Tribe, New Year's Eve Gathering.
> 1993
>=20
>      * 1.93 - The SFRaves/socal-raves X-country ski trip in Yosemite. Dan=
a
> ties my boom box to his backpack and we listen to Spun's tape while skiin=
g
> the back country in Yosemite.
>      * 2.2.93 - was supposed to be the last Come/Unity.
>      * 3.13.93 - Connection 2 planned for a spot in northwest SF. Rain
> forces it into the Charter Oak warehouse, but it is busted partway into
> Scott Hardkiss's set. After some scrambling, and a regrouping at the Cala
> Foods, the party is moved to the Berkeley Marina and rewards the SFRavers
> who brave a light drizzle. Jon Drukman plays on one turntable for a while=
,
> leading into sets from Moonpup, Lee and Blurrrr. Bob Ramstad may still
> have tapes :)
>      * 4.93 - The San Francisco community gets together to throw a benefi=
t
> party for Malachy, who was seriously injured after the full moon party
> early in March.
>      * summer '93 - the South Bay lunch begins. I think the first one was
> at Jing Jing in Palo Alto, then it is agreed that it works better as a
> bring-yr-food picnic in Greer Park.
>      * 7.29.93 - I take over the SFR calendar from Brian.
>      * 9.5.93 - Liquid Grooves at Crissy Field in San Francisco. This
> started a string of Liquid Air parties, leading up to the first Friends
> and Family at the Blue Cube. The original group of Liquid Air DJs include=
d
> Ethan, Bryce, Tamara Palmer, Jon Drukman, Lee An, and Laura La Gassa.
>      * 10.3.93 - Lee F., along with Ethan and Bryce throw Connection Eart=
h,
> an SFR-sponsored party at Marx Meadows in Golden Gate Park.
>=20
> Other highlights: Your Sisters' House, Boogie Buffet, Together, Zanzibar,
> Mission Rock, Groove Kitchen, MESS, Fluid Groove
> 1994
>=20
>      * 1.15.94 - the first Friends and Family goes off in the Blue Cube.
> Ethan, Bryce and the F&F collective pull it all together after learning
> the ropes with fluid groove and liquid air. Subsequent F&F's pack Klub
> Komotion with a hot & sweaty group of revelers.
>      * 5.28.94 - Lee F. takes the lead in the SFR-organized party "In the
> Light" at the bandshell in Golden Gate Park.
>      * 7.94 - Hyperreal comes up and SFR is moved to it.
>=20
> Other highlights: Sunset, Pure Space, Organic
> 1995: SFR: Friends & Family
>=20
>      * 3.95 - The SFR Calendar goes up on the web
>      * 3.95 - Thanks to the Zippies, SFR has a record 1080 messages over
> the month.
>      * 8.95 - Friends and Family outgrows Komotion and produces the first
> of two stellar parties in an Oakland warehouse. The F&F Collective grows
> to many dozen people. The first is so wildly successful that 600 tickets
> for the next F&F sell out in advance, in one weekend.
>      * 9.16.95 - Net.ravers from across the country gather and celebrate
> Brian and Laura's wedding with a pre-party at Bonny Doon Beach. They are
> married the next day.
>=20
> Other highlights: Sunset, Simply Done, the Gardening Club, Frequency 8,
> Area 51.
> 1999: SFR: Best Local Online Rave Resource
> SFR
>=20
>      * .99 - SF Raves won the SF Bay Guardian Best Of The Bay 1999 Award
> for Best Local Online Rave Resource!
>=20
> 2000: SFR Keeps Going Till the End of the 20th Century
>=20
>      * 3.00 - SFR 8 Years in the Mix - D.O.B. March 1992
>=20
> 2001: SFR Keep's On Thumpin Into the 21st Century
>=20
>      * 1.01 - SF Raves is 9 years Old, in the Mix
>      * 4.07.01 Epiphany - Ponies and Stuff
>      * 4.26.01 - SF Raves throws Relic - a party to Remember
>      * 5.01 - SF Raves' server taz, is retired, new and improved
> taz3.hyperreal.org is born
>      * 5.05.01 - SFRavers gather for a house party called Mexicon
>      * 5.12.01 - Free Beats Throws a Notable Renegade Party in Berkeley, =
CA
>      * 5.17.01 - Oxygen - A bi-weekly Party at the Oxygen Bar, leaves man=
y
> fond memories in the mind of Karina
>      * 5.22.01 - SF Ravers Justin Hale and Michael Liu throw a fabulous
> party in the South Bay Called Secret Society
>      * 6.16.01 - Fond Memories of Parties in GGP
>      * 6.16.01 - Sf Ravers from Butterzone.net throw a fond weekly shindi=
g
> called Sunday of Slack
>      * 6.28.01 - Local Collective Epiphany has a three year anniversary
> party
>      * 7.07.01 - Eklektic makes its mark as a place for Junglists
>=20
> 2002: SFRaves Celebrates its Decade Anniversary
> # SFR-P throws Amalagamation
> # 09.29.02 -
> SFRaves 10 YEAR ANNIVERSARY!
> A Decade of SFRaves !!! - FREE OUTDOOR PARTY in the Park !!!
> *** SFRaves History: SFRaves 10 Year Archives ****
> Bringing the SFR Community an unforgettable day in the Sun, to enjoy and
> celebrate a decade of Music, Dance, Friendship and experiences of SFRaves
> over the past 10 years. Experience the celebration through the expression
> of ecclectic sound, intriguing memoires and a diverse memorabilia of
> flyers, music, art and dance of spanning 1992 - 2002. Sound provided by
> Neuroscience Creations.
> Your lineup is as follows:
>=20
>      * Brian Behlendorf (SFRAVES, Connection, Hyperreal.org)
>      * Ethan (Friends and Family) [www.bass-station.com/FnF]
>      * Galen/Solar (Sunset/Pacific)
>      * AndyW & Li [on 4 decks] (Viberation, Resource Records)
> [www.viberation.com]
>      * Amber & Drag'nfly [on 4 decks] (Sister, DNA, sfr-p, Teknique,
> Epiphany) [www.iamthedj.com] (Amber) & [www.djdragnfly.com]
>      * DJ2 (Moksha Tribe, Live Funk/Electro/Acid performance (Drag'nfly)
>=20
> This event is ALL AGES AND FREE!!! Free refreshments and snacks. 12pm-6pm
> @ the beautiful McLaren Amphitheater, in San Francisco, CA
> * Map and Directions: http://members.aol.com/peyote4000/map.htm
> * Infolines: 415.564.4768 or 415.789.8236 **http://www.sfraves.org**

> 2003
>=20
>      * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface grows in functionality, people an=
d
> size. The SFR Calendar is enhanced with multiple features. Features are
> updated to include enhancements in the Events Calendar, Event Calendar
> Interface, Groups, User/People profiles, Polls

>=20
> 2004
>=20
>      * SFRaves/Hyperreal Rave Interface reaches the 1.0 milestone. SFR
> calendar features continue enhancement and shift direction to broaden
> scope and improved Quality standards.
>      * Updated features: Events Calendar, Event calendar Groups,
> User/People profiles
>      * User Registration has skyrocketed to 258 groups and 1666 people as
> of September 2004!

> Livejournal.com, SFRaves @ Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves
> Myspace Group and SFRaves @ Myspace, and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>      * SFRaves serves the community for 12 years strong!
>=20
> 2005
>=20
>      * SFRaves Calendar continues to grow in reach, registration of Users=
,
> Groups and features.
>      * SFRaves becomes a teenager in 2005! 13 years and counting...
>      * SFRaves continues branches out and networks nonstop. The community
> has grown by leaps and bounds to include direct networking connections on
> various sites on the web. As a result, both the user base and the breadth
> of our community has an extended reach and continues to grow.
>      * SFRaves Calendar User Registration has skyrocketed to 310 groups a=
nd
> 1985 people as of January 2005!
>      * SFRaves Network Contacts: SFRaves @ Livejournal.com, SFRaves @
> Tribe.net, SFRaves @ Friendster.com, SFRaves Myspace Group, SFRaves @
> Myspace and SFRaves @ Orkut.com
>      * SFRaves serves the community for 13 years strong!

Subject: Re: [sfraves] News: New Rave Drug Have Experts Concerned

--- Karina <karina@hyperreal.org> wrote:

> http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=366370&page=1
> 
> New Rave Drugs Have Experts Concerned
> Use of Synthetic Hallucinogens Is on the Rise, But
> Health Effects Are 
> Unknown
> 
> Dec. 30, 2004 . A new class of drugs is getting
> increased attention from 
> police and partyers alike.
> 
> Synthetic hallucinogens, which are growing in
> popularity at nightclubs and 
> rave parties, are so new that many don't even have
> street names yet.
> 
> Top Stories
> 
>      * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
>      * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
>      * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage
> 
> Usually manufactured in small home-based
> laboratories, these drugs have 
> law enforcement and health officials concerned
> because their long-term 
> health effects are virtually unknown.
> 
> 'Colors Were Really Brilliant and Crisp'
> 
> The drugs reportedly have effects similar to the
> popular rave drug 
> ecstasy: feelings of euphoria, emotional empathy and
> colorful 
> hallucinations. The typical user is a young, white,
> college-educated and 
> Web-savvy person who finds that these drugs
> complement the dance music 
> heard at nightclubs and raves.
> 
> "It's kind of mildly hallucinogenic and visual,"
> said Gregory, a graphic 
> designer from California who tried one of these
> drugs for the first time 
> last year. "Colors were really brilliant and crisp,
> and I became really 
> relaxed."
> 
> Most synthetic hallucinogens are still referred to
> by a confusing alphabet 
> soup of names based on their chemical compounds.
> 
> 2C-B is considered one of the most popular of these
> drugs. 2C-T-7 is often 
> compared to LSD for its colorful hallucinations. AMT
> was originally 
> developed in the 1960s for antidepressant research,
> but was abandoned 
> shortly thereafter. 5-MEO-DiPT, also referred to as
> "Foxy," is sometimes 
> used as a substitute for ecstasy.
> 
> Buyer Beware
> 
> "Because these drugs are unstudied in the medical
> literature, we don't 
> know all of the side effects or all of the dangers
> involved in the use of 
> these drugs," said Paula Berezansky, intelligence
> analyst for the National 
> Drug Intelligence Center, a component agency of the
> U.S. Department of 
> Justice.
> 
> The illicit way in which synthetic hallucinogens are
> sold presents another 
> problem. "A user may not know what they're buying,"
> Berezansky added. 
> "Something sold as one drug may be another."
> 
> Most synthetic hallucinogens fall into two general
> categories, 
> phenethylamines and tryptamines. Both chemical
> compounds occur in nature 
> and are found in common plants and foods . small
> amounts of phenethylamine 
> are even found in chocolate.
> 
> Nationwide, a handful of overdoses and hospital
> admissions have been 
> attributed to synthetic hallucinogens. But because
> many of these drugs are 
> mixed with other drugs or their actual chemical
> nature is unknown even to 
> the users, accurate records are difficult to gather.
> 
> Top Stories
> 
>      * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
>      * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
>      * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage
> 
> Health Effects Are Unknown
> 
> "We've actually had patients come in with a
> condition called monoamine 
> oxidase toxicity from taking combinations of drugs
> that include 
> tryptamines," said Dr. Edward Boyer, director of
> toxicology at the 
> University of Massachusetts Medical Center in
> Worcester.
> 
> "What concerns me . is that kids are turning to
> psychoactive drugs at a 
> younger age," Boyer added. "We simply don't know
> what these tryptamines do 
> to a developing neurological system. Tryptamines are
> powerful 
> hallucinogens."
> 
> "People can't even decide what the long-term effects
> of a common drug like 
> ecstasy are, let alone something like 2C-B," said
> Boyer.
> 
> Law enforcement officials echo the concerns of the
> medical community.
> 
> "It's a young group of people who are using this and
> half the time they 
> don't know what they're using . they're going on
> what a friend says," said 
> Lt. Patrick J. Garey, a member of the Community
> Narcotics Enforcement Team 
> of the New York State Police.
> 
> "There's so much poly-drug mixing of drugs that
> occurs, you could be 
> taking ecstasy mixed with a bunch of other drugs,"
> he said.
> 
> Psychonauts Surfing the Web
> 
> "One of the reasons we've seen these drugs increase
> in use over the last 
> few years is the use of the Internet," said
> Berezansky. "The abusers can 
> find out a lot about these drugs very easily."
> 
> She refers to users by the name law enforcement
> officials have coined for 
> those who surf the Web for drug information:
> "psychonauts."
> 
> But drug users aren't the only ones surfing the
> Internet for drug 
> information.
> 
> When Garey was called to participate in a recent
> seizure of a 2C-B lab at 
> a home in Tioga County in upstate New York, he told
> ABCNews.com: "It kind 
> of came out of the blue. We'd never seen it before.
> I'd never even heard 
> of it. I had to go on the Internet to find out what
> it was."
> 
> The DEA is also using the Internet, but to snare the
> dealers who profit 
> from the sale of synthetic hallucinogens. In July,
> the DEA announced the 
> conclusion of "Operation Web Tryp," named for the
> tryptamines that were 
> part of the operation's focus.
> 
> Operation Web Tryp targeted five Web sites and
> resulted in the arrest of 
> 10 individuals from across the United States.
> 
> But many of these drugs are so new their legal
> status is a matter of some 
> confusion. 5-MEO-DiPT, for example, was not even
> permanently placed on the 
> Federal Register as a Schedule I controlled
> substance until September of 
> this year.
> 
> A User's Experience
> 
> Rod, a computer hardware engineer in the San
> Francisco Bay area who 
> preferred to use an assumed name, has experimented
> with the synthetic 
> hallucinogen 2C-B.
> 
> Top Stories
> 
>      * Meth Becoming a Threat in Some Cities
>      * Tsunami Epidemics Still a Risk
>      * Medicare Expands Defibrillator Coverage
> 
=== message truncated ===

>realize it's gone, you're like somebody's grandpa, and

Yep...and some advice from someone who has been through many "new 
moments:"  what you seek is not in the past, or in some heroic yet 
ultimately empty attempt to recreate it.  The big epiphanies, the major 
transformative lightening bursts on the dancefloor, will probably not be 
found within your comfortable, familiar walls.  Life is a quest, and it is 
the quest that is life.  Once you've found what you seek you're dead 
meat.  The big orgasm is out there...you gotta' look for it...or you buy 
some Viagra -- I guess |-O
